componenttext: Good afternoon. My name is Kim and I'll be your conference operator for today. At this time, I would like to welcome, everyone to the Fourth Quarter Prologis Earnings Conference Call. [Operator Instructions] Thank you. Ms. Tracy Ward, Senior Vice President, Investor Relations, you may begin your conference.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2015 Conference Call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our C
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2015 Conference Call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and the market environment; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance.
Also joining us today for the call are Gary Anderson, Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly, and Diana Scott. Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this conference call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates, as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. 
Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings. Additionally, our results press release and supplementals do contain financial measures such as FFO, EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures. And in accordance with Reg G, we have provided a reconciliation to those measures.
With that, I'll turn the call over to Hamid and we'll get started.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning. At Prologis, 2015 was a banner year. Business remains exceptionally strong in the fourth quarter, wrapping up the year that exceeded expectations in virtually all aspects of the business. Broad-based demand and restraints
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning. At Prologis, 2015 was a banner year. Business remains exceptionally strong in the fourth quarter, wrapping up the year that exceeded expectations in virtually all aspects of the business. Broad-based demand and restraints supply are creating favorable conditions around the world. Focusing on the top global original markets has helped us outperform the broader market. 
Core FFO grew 19% year-over-year. Occupancy reached a record 96.9% and rents increased 13%. We're 2 years into our 3-year strategic plan and have already exceeded all of our financial goals a year ahead of plan. Core FFO however, doesn't tell the whole story. While the key drivers of our operating performance on core FFO, our occupancy, rent and fees, we also create value from our development and value-added conversions. 
The results of these activities materially add to our NAV. Last year, value creation totaled $700 million, representing an additional $1.30 per share of NAV. Industrial real estate market conditions are healthy in most of the world in spite of concerns about emerging market economies, including slower growth in China. In Europe for example, where we've allocated significant capital over the last several years, value appreciation has been extremely robust. 
While several macroeconomic indicators tell a mixed story around the world, those most correlated with our business point to favorable business trends in 2015. These include: global consumption with flat growth in '16, at over 4%; global trade, up in '16 by about 3.5%; U.S. container imports, up in '16 by about 5.5%; and strong e-commerce with growth again in the double-digits. 
The best indicator for our business however, is the health and outlook offer customers. Their space needs tell the story of global consumption. For many customers, that story is one of continued expansions. Demand continues to exceed supply. As we said on our last call, equilibrium in the U.S. will likely be reached in late 2016. 
Globally our share in place portfolio rents is 10% under market today, which will lead to continued NOI growth ahead of inflation as leases turnover. We're disciplined about managing risk in our respective development with a focus on profitability, not volume. Unlike previous cycles, other developers and lenders in our sector also appear to be showing discipline. 
As a result, healthy supply demand environment continues, now in its sixth year. Supply-chain reconfiguration is a key long-term driver of our business. This is true for the full spectrum of our customer base. Where growth is slowing, customers are investing in ways to squeeze more efficiency out of their supply chain. Even in a low growth environment, our business can grow. 
At the other end of the spectrum, the growth in e-commerce continues to be a good source of demand for industrial real estate. Online sales grew 15% in the U.S. while traditional retail grew only 2%. The allure for brick-and-mortar retailers to create or expand our e-commerce business will continue well into the future. To meet consumer demand for faster deliveries, this channel requires facilities that are closer to labor and population centers. 
We speak regularly with our customers about their changing space needs. Good examples are Home Depot and Walmart. Once considered traditional retailers, they are well underway with major reconfigurations of their supply chain, designed to handle the rapidly changing e-commerce segment. 
Our existing building and development portfolio has accommodated our most sophisticated e-commerce customers needs, and has done so across the wide range of space configurations from the largest fulfillment master-planned parks, down to smaller last mile delivery centers in our infield buildings. We believe our business momentum will continue in 2016. This is due to steady market conditions and broad-based demand from other sectors such as food and beverage, automotive and electronics. 
The last several years, we work to realign our portfolio and strengthen our capital structure. We had an outstanding 2015 and made significant progress on our priorities, finishing the year better positioned than ever. The result is a business that outperforms during improving macro conditions that can capitalize on opportunities in the downturn. Based on our customers input and the position of our portfolio, we have a positive outlook for 2016. Tom?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid. We had great results for the fourth quarter and full year. Core FFO was $0.64 per share for the quarter and $2.23 per share for the year, an increase of 19% year-over-year. This includes $0.05 of net promote income we earned in the fourth q
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid. We had great results for the fourth quarter and full year. Core FFO was $0.64 per share for the quarter and $2.23 per share for the year, an increase of 19% year-over-year. This includes $0.05 of net promote income we earned in the fourth quarter from our pelp venture. We exceeded the top end of our guidance, primarily due to operations and timing of capital employment. 
Starting with operations. Occupancy reached an all-time high of 96.9% and was above 95% in every region. Our share of GAAP rent change was 12.4%, driven by the U.S. at 18%. The KTR assets had performed of our under running for both occupancy and rent change. KTR has been fully integrated in our portfolio and is included in the operating statistics I discussed. 
Our share of GAAP same-store NOI increased 6.6% in the quarter, driven by the U.S. at 8.7%. As we discussed last quarter, the negative impact of on GAAP -- on GAAP NOI from the amortization of lease intangibles related to the merger have fully burned off. This again, had a positive impact of about 100 basis points on GAAP same-store. 
Moving to our share of capital employment. We had an exceptional year and created significant value for shareholders. We stabilized $1.6 billion of developments with an estimated margin of 33%. The initial yield on these stabilizations was 7.3% and the incremental cash return, excluding our already own land was 9.2% [ph].  Dispositions and contributions totaled $2.5 billion at a 5.3% weighted average stabilized cap rate, and included $166 million of value creation from value-added conversions. 
Dispositions and contributions volumes was about $400 million short of the midpoint of our guidance. We elected to split a few sales across multiple buyers to maximize proceeds, and deferred certain contributions to amass better scale, pushing this activity into the first half of 2016. We started $1.8 billion of development. We've built [indiscernible] making up 44%. The starts will generate estimated value creation of $388 million and margin of 21%. 
Turning to capital markets. We had an active quarter and closed the year with our lines of credits fully undrawn, and reduced the short-term loan associated with the KHR acquisition to $400 million. We're on track to pay off the remainder of the term loan by the end of the first half of 2016, if not sooner. Our leverage on a book basis dropped 130 basis points to 38.4% at quarter end. 
Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains improved to 6x for the quarter. While leverage and debt to EBITDA are very important credit metrics, there are other factors, which demonstrates the strength of our balance sheet. The first is liquidity. We ended the year with over $2.8 billion of liquidity and only 12% of our debt maturing in the next 24 months. Maintaining significant liquidity at all times is a pillar of our balance sheet strategy, as it mitigates credit market disruptions that provides ready capital to be opportunistic. 
Second is our significant nominal EBITDA coverage. We had over $1.5 billion of annualized EBITDA in excess of our fixed charges,is underpinned by more than $25 billion of unencumbered assets. The bottom line is our balance sheet is in great shape and we expect it to get even stronger in 2016. 
Let's switch to 2016 guidance. For operation, we expect our year-end occupancy to range between 96% and 97%, and our share GAAP same store NOI growth of between 3.5% and 4.5%. Cash same store NOI growth should be higher than GAAP in 2016. The split of our share of NOI by geography will be approximately 80% Americas, 15% Europe and 5% Asia. We expect our share development stabilizations to be between $1.6 billion and $1.8 billion as stabilization has increased meaningfully over the past 3 [ph] years and now approach our starts volume, continue to see significant annual NOI growth from our developments. 
For 2016, we expect FFO from development stabilization of $0.10 to $0.12 per share. Related to FX, our 2016 earnings are very well insulated from foreign currency fluctuations, and over 90% is already hedged. For net G&A, we're forecasting a range of $235 million to $245 million, essentially flat to last year at the midpoint, while managing more than $6 billion in assets. 
For strategic capital, we expect revenue without promotes to range between $180 million and $190 million. We have promote opportunities from 3 of our ventures in 2016, Patel and Pep 2, in the third quarter and USLV in the fourth quarter. We project net promotes to contribute between $0.17 and $0.19 per share to core FFO. The magnitude of these promotes is a testament to our strategic capital franchise, as well as our strategy to allocate capital to Europe over the last 5 years. 
Over this period, we took advantage of a dislocation in asset prices in the market. Our European portfolio has consistently outperformed the market in terms of both occupancy and returns. Our capital deployment guidance is spelled out in our supplemental. At the midpoint of our net deployment, we will generate proceeds of about $400 million. Additionally, we have 2 other very significant sources of cash in 2016. 
First, we will receive $199 million in cash in the first quarter from a completion of the installment sale related to Facebook. And second, we redeemed a total of $400 million between our USLF and Patel ventures, which we'll fund in the second quarter of 2016. These ownership rebalancing and these 2 open-ended funds is aligned with our long-term ownership targets and facilitates the deployment of substantial investment queues in these ventures. 
As a result, we expect to generate net deployment proceeds in excess of our capital needs of $1 billion in 2016 or $600 million after repayment of the last $400 million of the KTR term loan. Putting this altogether, we expect our 2016 core FFO to range between $2.50 and $2.60, including promotes. This represents 14% year-over-year growth or an increase of $0.32 per share at the midpoint. We expect AFFO growth will exceed core FFO growth in 2016. 
If we assume a normalized annual net promote of $0.05 per share, our core FFO range for 2016 would be between $2.38 a share and $2.46 a share, an increase of 9% year-over-year at the midpoint. In closing, we had incredible year and enter 2016 with confidence, though mindful of potential economic cross currents. We have a portfolio that has never been in better shape, a strong balance sheet and a plan that grows core FFO 14%, pays off the remaining KTR debt, self-funds all deployment generates $1 billion of net deployment in excess for capital needs, maintain significant with liquidity and provides flexibility and optionality to adjust to changes in market conditions. 
With that, I'll turn it over to the operator for questions.

componenttext: Just a question on the dividend. How do you guys think about the coverage relative to AFFO and particularly, just given the variability in developments?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes. This is Tom, I'll take that. So a couple of things to think about there. One, when you look at our coverage in 2015, our coverage with development gains is 69%. Without development gains is 89%. For 2016, similar numbers would be with development gai
componenttext: Yes. This is Tom, I'll take that. So a couple of things to think about there. One, when you look at our coverage in 2015, our coverage with development gains is 69%. Without development gains is 89%. For 2016, similar numbers would be with development gains of 65% roughly. And without development gains of about 75%. So we have significant AFFO coverage in excess of our dividend. Now you had a question about how the dividend might be impacted. If it could be impacted by changes in development. So what -- so the first thing you need to think about and I'm assuming you're referring to capitalized overhead and capitalized interest. So the first thing you need to think about though is how we're capitalizing development. We're capitalizing development by self funding, so we're selling assets and rolling those into development. And we're selling assets that are yielding, let's just call it 6%. And we're capping interest at a rate of roughly 3%. And when you look at our cap overhead, our cap overhead actually related to the development, annually is about $47 million. And when you express that $47 million over development, it's about 3%. So if you think about -- if we slow down development, let's just take an extreme example. Let's just assume there's no development. So if we had a development of $2 billion, we were going to sell $2 billion to fund that, the 6%, we were earning on that development is going to stay in our income statement. The interest expense that we would've capped is going to stay on our income statement. The overhead that we were going to cap is going to stay on our income statement, and you know what? There's a 0 impact on our income statement because all of that NOI that we would've used to fund that development, is going to stay on our books. So we're self-funding. So if the development slows down, then there are really no impact to our earnings.

componenttext: Yes, this is Tom. I'll take that again. So as I said in my prepared remarks, we had some activity that just got pushed into 2016. But I want you to focus on a couple of things. So -- and when I talked about the sources of cash that we had. We have $600 million that's locked and loaded, that's going to close in the first and second quarter of 2016 between the face book note and the fund rebalancing. That's $600 million. There's another $400 million of acquisitions alone, that Mike can give color on the -- disposition, I'm sorry. That Mike can give color on, that we feel extremely good about. There's $1 billion of capital right there that we will realize very, very quickly in cash. So it was really just a shift of timing to the end of the year, a point in time and we elected to shift some activity into '16 for very good, economic reasons. But we feel great good about where we are. We're ahead of schedule from a KTR standpoint. We talked about that funding, paying off the remaining $400 million by the end of the first half of the year. I think it's going to be April to be very specific when you look at all of the funding that we have in place that is certain to close.

componenttext: We're not -- we're really looking for it. We read the same paper's everybody else, Obviously, we're very vigilant about it. But we haven't seen it, I mean that's probably the question I ask the team every Monday. And we have pretty real data on leasing. We track that stuff very closely and we haven't seen this. componenttext: Maybe related to that. So it sounds like your comments were -- and performance in the quarter, all very strong from a fundamental perspective. It sounds like you feel that way about the outlook. But it also feels like you're slowing down a little bit in terms of development starts. And it feels like maybe you're scaling back the growth drivers of the business a little. And I'm just wondering, is that because there's concern that there could be a slowdown or do you feel like it's just a prudent way to manage the business in what's, fifth or sixth year of economic expansion? Or is this just more normal course kind of what we should expect maybe around $2 billion of starts as opposed to $2.5 billion, I think you were running at last year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Brandon, you probably remember this. But back in the beginning of time 2011 or something. We actually laid out a plan that talked about development in aggregate, being about $2 billion to $3 billion a year on a run rate basis in total, not our share obvio
componenttext: Brandon, you probably remember this. But back in the beginning of time 2011 or something. We actually laid out a plan that talked about development in aggregate, being about $2 billion to $3 billion a year on a run rate basis in total, not our share obviously, the numbers we were reporting are our share, which are a little bit lower. And I will still say that, that's an opportunity set. But why get ahead of ourselves? I mean, we've got a very robust businesses pipeline, right now. You can see that for the first time, we're projecting build-to-suits to be over 50% of our leasing activity. Again, reading the same papers, we want to be cautious. There is nothing that will stop us from starting up more development if we see more opportunity down the road. As Tom mentioned, we have $1 billion more capital than we need to finance KTR. We have the capital. We can do it. We have a lot of the land already and we have time to make that decision. So I think we're being prudent. But we'll do the right thing, whatever that might be at the time.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Sure. I mean, remember what we're selling. We've -- first of all, let me take you back to the time of the merger, again the beginning of time. We sold over $8 billion of properties. Just think about that. I mean that I think would be the size of maybe the
componenttext: Sure. I mean, remember what we're selling. We've -- first of all, let me take you back to the time of the merger, again the beginning of time. We sold over $8 billion of properties. Just think about that. I mean that I think would be the size of maybe the second largest company in the sector. That's what we sold. And I think you know that we've been selling from the nonstrategic end of the spectrum. So you would expect those cap rates to be higher than our portfolio. And there has been a lot of talk out there about what would devalue the portfolio be on a constant cap rate basis and the like. When you sell $8 billion from the lower tier of your portfolio, the mix has a very substantial impact on what cap rate is even in the steady environment and what's left of your portfolio. So we think the IRR at the end of the days won't matter, and those cap rates are higher because those growth rates are lower. And we feel really good about our capital allocation decisions. Just think about that capital we allocated to Europe, a couple of years ago. How do we fund that? We funded that by selling some nonstrategic assets a year. At the time, people thought we were crazy. We were selling assets in the U.S. in the mid 6s and low 7s, and we were buying assets in Europe in the lower rates. And those assets [indiscernible], so we're now in the high 5s and the low 6s. So you got to take a longer-term view of these, and I wouldn't read too much into any quarter by quarter things, particularly when you have this mix issue going on with the numbers, at this scale.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Let me clarify something about the promotes. We've received questions recently about our promotes, that's why we're selling it. Our promotes have nothing to do with what assets we sell or what assets we hold. They're completely based in the vast majority
componenttext: Let me clarify something about the promotes. We've received questions recently about our promotes, that's why we're selling it. Our promotes have nothing to do with what assets we sell or what assets we hold. They're completely based in the vast majority of cases on appraised values on a quarter by quarter basis at the time of the promotes. So actually selling assets doesn't do anything to the promotes. So I just wanted to clarify that. Secondly, I would say we have pretty good visibility into the valuations because we appraise the portfolio, particularly the deals that are in the ventures on a quarterly basis. We know what the carrying values are in the fourth quarter, and we put some sensitivity around that at scenarios that include cap rate expansion, flat cap rates, reducing cap rates. And we've picked up prudent number to project those. Now to answer your specific questions, the promotes today are based in the high 5, low 6% cap rates. And we think there's a bit of room in those numbers to the good. But we're not going to get ahead of ourselves now.

componenttext: Yes, we talked about this last quarter, I believe. So we said we were going to reach equilibrium this year, but we're going to reach equilibrium at least in the U.S. at least at a sort of mid-5 vacancy rate I think we'll be 5, 7 at the end of it. And I think we can grow rents substantially above inflation during an equilibrium period, if your vacancy rate is that low. So I would guess for this year, we're going to see continued growth that's going to be 5-ish. And my view beyond that is that it's probably 4 to 5 in the following year. Because I don't think we're going to see excess construction next year or the year after. So it's in that range.

componenttext: The only thing I would add to what Gene said, Ross, is that for a couple of years now, we've been predicting cap rates are going to stay the same or expand, and we've been wrong about that. Now if the cap rates do stay the same or expand, rental growth will be stronger because of the headwind of cap rate compression is going to be maybe turning into a tailwind or neutral wind anyway. So that's something to keep in mind as well.

componenttext: I think that's particularly turn Europe [ph] obviously, where we had 70 basis points of cap rate compression over last year, 20 basis in the last quarter, and that's certainly been a headwinds to [indiscernible] to push rents, but I expect that to subside back after this year.

componenttext: This is Mike Curless. Last year, we ended up about 45% and given our -- just to give you a little context, we've gone 30 build-to-suits in the last 12 months. And as we look into next year, we've got more in the pipeline than we've ever had before at this stage in the year, and given the track record and all the leases I mentioned before, we're very bullish on our ability to see those percentages approaching 50% next year.

And guess on the flip side to that, are there any markets that you're particularly optimistic about for 2016?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Sure. Tom, first of all, thank you for remembering that, because I think that's a very important part of our responsibilities to call out markets that have any risk of getting over built from our vantage point. And the reason I had mentioned it is because
componenttext: Sure. Tom, first of all, thank you for remembering that, because I think that's a very important part of our responsibilities to call out markets that have any risk of getting over built from our vantage point. And the reason I had mentioned it is because nothing has really changed in that regard. It's  Houston -- obviously, from demand reasons is a bit softer. Although, it's pulling up a bit better than we would've expected at this point. And that looks continues to have a lot of development but absorption is keeping pace. So, so far, so good, but we're really watching those 2 markets probably more than any others in the U.S. I would say going over to Europe, Paris is a bit soft and its not really a supply problem, it's more of a demand problem, and I think some of it has to do with some of this heritage stuff that went on last quarter. But I don't know if France has generally been a little bit slower. The place that's been surprisingly strong in Europe for us, has been Spain. Spain's really done a turn around and I would say, it's done extremely well. The U.K. was early in Europe. And we thought it got a little bit ahead of itself and it may go the other way or soften, it has and it continues to be pretty strong in terms of cap rates. And in the U.S., Chicago has been pretty good on the upside in the cycle. And the large California markets continue to be very, very strong. In the longer term, I'm a little concerned about the technology, sort of bubble and valuations and all that. And ultimately, that may have an impact on the area numbers not next year, but probably -- not that the year after. But we've essentially taken a lot of chip off the table from that R&D type of product. And I don't think it will have much of an effect on the distribution space.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: We talked about the sell-down in the rebalancing part of Tom's prepared remarks. So that's what we're doing. Our funds are -- we are way over the percentage that we need to have in the funds, I mean like double or triple of what our percentage should be.
componenttext: We talked about the sell-down in the rebalancing part of Tom's prepared remarks. So that's what we're doing. Our funds are -- we are way over the percentage that we need to have in the funds, I mean like double or triple of what our percentage should be. And we're getting a lot of interest from our investors who are in the queues for investing in these funds to put their capital in and to invest. And we wanted them and we said okay, we're prepared to settle down to accommodate your needs. And by the way, we also told the other investors, look, if you want to settle down along with us, come on down because we've got plenty of people who want to buy in and this is a good time to rebalance your portfolio. And 1 or 2 investors have taken advantage of that, but by and large, other people had not wanted to sell-down and we never intended to [indiscernible] 40% in our funds, and the target was more around 15% or 20% and we're not going to go all the way down to that level. Certainly, but we're going to get back to a more normal allocation of our funds. I think there's some transactions that are locked and loaded that will -- that are better based on fourth quarter valuations. So we know the values, we know the timing, we know the amounts. And that's why we feel so confident in our capital plan and not at all concerned about the things that we were asked in terms of dispositions in the fourth quarter and all that. So we're watching these things on a realtime basis and we have to adjust our disposition plans to balance the fund investments and that can continue to be a source of capital for us. I think in a couple of quarters ago, we walked you through it, there was about $3 billion of capital available because of our excess investment in our fund. So that is an effect of forward funding opportunity for anything that we may need capital for. And for the time being, we're really happy having our capital investment.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Now Erik, with respect to your question about land, that's quite conscious. And as you've heard me talk about, we have too much land to support our development. And that's partly a legacy issue from the last cycle and we've got a challenge because that's
componenttext: Now Erik, with respect to your question about land, that's quite conscious. And as you've heard me talk about, we have too much land to support our development. And that's partly a legacy issue from the last cycle and we've got a challenge because that's being monetized land in our development, since the value keeps on -- they'll value what remains keep going up, so we've got a bit of a headwind in terms of getting our land down. And you're just seeing the book value, actually. The market value is substantially higher than that. So we have a conscious decision to work down our land. In fact, what I'd like to see in our land be is to be under $1 billion, because I think it can support 2 or 3 years of development without having that amount of land on our books. That means that we can unlock about $1 billion of capital from our land bank over some period of time. I hope it's sooner than later. But there's $1 billion of capital sitting there. If that were invested in income-producing properties, everything else being the same, that's another $60 million of earnings that are being wasted because they're part in dead land. So that's another, what $0.12 a share, that would be really meaningful to our business. And our team is working hard to getting the land bank down. It takes time, but we'll get there.

componenttext: Steve, as you know, I've been in this business since the early '80s and here in, and originally our business was entirely focused on the Bay Area. So we've seen -- I don't know 4 of these cycles before, it doesn't mean each 1 is going to be exactly the same as the last 1. But it just feels like everything is overstretched then you're seeing a couple of canneries in the coal mines, you're seeing the IPOs get priced at the lower end of the range. You're seeing a lot of the companies go through down ground and over the ratchets, a very -- really getting some investor squeeze. All of that stuff ultimately, will affect demand for space particularly -- and I should stop there because I'm not an office expert or an R&D expert. And frankly, our portfolio with the face book and the other major sale in [indiscernible] is essentially -- we're done with that product type almost. So it just feels like it's stretched. That's all I was trying to communicate there. I think the chances of real estate values going up a lot are not as high as they were chances of values going down. How much is your guess, is as good as mine.

componenttext: So people have asked about the dispositions and contributions, but I just wanted to kind of ask it in one other way. Last quarter, you talked about doing $400 million of contribution, to kind of talked about it as if that was in the bag. I know it looks like you guys only completed about $100 million. And what are we supposed to read into that, I mean does it just get pushed to January 1, is it just a timing issue? Are you getting a little bit of pushback from your fund investors on taking some of these properties?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: This is Tom. It's all about timing. We look to amass a certain amount of scale. And if we see it in other asset that might be leasing up ahead of schedule, we will wait to amass that versus trying to do that as a one-off or weighting. So it's really timin
componenttext: This is Tom. It's all about timing. We look to amass a certain amount of scale. And if we see it in other asset that might be leasing up ahead of schedule, we will wait to amass that versus trying to do that as a one-off or weighting. So it's really timing. We feel very good about that. The process is very transparent on contributions. We don't have an obligation to all. Our partners on venture do not have an obligation to acquire, but we go through fair value. So there's nothing there from a process standpoint that has changed or a lack of desire. It's really timing. But you can see that timing shift when you look at our numbers right, as far as the $1 billion, even without contributions. We see about $1 billion. It's really locked and loaded as we look to the next quarter and a half. 600 million of that face book and redemption is gosh, 2 months away.

Good afternoon. My name is Kim, and I'll be your conference operator today. At this time, I would like to welcome everyone to the fourth quarter Prologis earnings conference call. [Operator Instructions] Thank you. 
Ms. Tracy Ward, Senior Vice President, Investor Relations, you may begin your conference.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2015 Conference Call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our C
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2015 Conference Call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and the market environment; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance.  Also joining us today for the call are Gary Anderson, Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly, and Diana Scott. 
Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this conference call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. 
Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings. 
Additionally, our results press release and supplemental do contain financial measures, such as FFO and EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures. And in accordance with Reg G, we have provided a reconciliation to those measures.
With that, I'll turn the call over to Hamid, and we'll get started.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning. At Prologis, 2015 was a banner year. Business remains exceptionally strong in the fourth quarter, wrapping up a year that exceeded expectations in virtually all aspects of the business. Broad-based demand and restraints su
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning. At Prologis, 2015 was a banner year. Business remains exceptionally strong in the fourth quarter, wrapping up a year that exceeded expectations in virtually all aspects of the business. Broad-based demand and restraints supply are creating favorable conditions around the world. Focusing on the top global and reginal markets has helped us outperform the broader market. 
Core FFO grew 19% year-over-year. Occupancy reached a record 96.9%, and rents increased 13%. We're 2 years into our 3-year strategic plan and have already exceeded all of our financial goals, a year ahead of plan. Core FFO, however, doesn't tell the whole story. While the key drivers of our operating performance on core FFO are occupancy, rent and fees, we also create value from our development and value-added conversions. 
The results of these activities materially add to our NAV. Last year, value creation totaled $700 million, representing an additional $1.30 per share of NAV. 
Industrial real estate market conditions are healthy in most of the world in spite of concerns about emerging market economies, including slower growth in China. In Europe, for example, where we've allocated significant capital over the last several years, value appreciation has been extremely robust. 
While several macroeconomic indicators tell a mixed story around the world, those most correlated with our business, point to favorable business trends in 2015. These include: global consumption with flat growth in '16, at over 4%; global trade, up in '16 by about 3.5%; U.S. container imports, up in '16 by about 5.5%; and strong e-commerce with growth again in the double digits.
The best indicator for our business, however, is the health and outlook of our customers. Their space needs tell the story of global consumption. For many customers, that story is one of continued expansions. Demand continues to exceed supply. As we said on our last call, equilibrium in the U.S. will likely be reached in late 2016.
Globally, our share of in-place portfolio rents is 10% under market today, which will lead to continued NOI growth ahead of inflation as leases turnover. We're disciplined about managing risk in our spec development, with a focus on profitability, not volume. Unlike previous cycles, other developers and lenders in our sector also appear to be showing discipline.
As a result, a healthy supply/demand environment continues, now in its sixth year. Supply chain reconfiguration is a key long-term driver of our business. This is true for the full spectrum of our customer base, where growth is slowing, customers are investing in ways to squeeze more efficiency out of their supply chain. Even in a low-growth environment, our business can grow.
At the other end of the spectrum, the growth in the e-commerce continues to be a source of demand for industrial real estate. Online sales grew 15% in the U.S., while traditional retail grew only 2%. The allure for brick-and-mortar retailers to create or expand their e-commerce business will continue well into the future. To meet consumer demand for faster deliveries, this channel requires facilities that are closer to labor and population centers.
We speak regularly with our customers about their changing space needs. Good examples are Home Depot and Walmart. Once considered traditional retailers, they are well underway with major reconfigurations of their supply chain, designed to handle the rapidly changing e-commerce segment. 
Our existing building and development portfolio has accommodated our most sophisticated e-commerce customers' needs and has done so across the wide range of space configurations from the largest fulfillment centers in our master-planned parks, down to smaller last mile delivery centers in our infill buildings. We believe our business momentum will continue in 2016. This is due to steady market conditions and broad-based demand from other sectors, such as food and beverage, automotive and electronics.
The last several years, we worked to realign our portfolio and strengthen our capital structure. We had an outstanding 2015 and made significant progress on our priorities, finishing the year better positioned than ever. The result is a business that outperforms during improving macro conditions and can capitalize on opportunities in the downturn. Based on our customers input and the position of our portfolio, we have a positive outlook for 2016. Tom?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid. We had great results for the fourth quarter and full year. Core FFO was $0.64 per share for the quarter and $2.23 per share for the year, an increase of 19% year-over-year. This includes $0.05 of net promote income we earned in the fourth q
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid. We had great results for the fourth quarter and full year. Core FFO was $0.64 per share for the quarter and $2.23 per share for the year, an increase of 19% year-over-year. This includes $0.05 of net promote income we earned in the fourth quarter from our PELP venture. We exceeded the top end of our guidance, primarily due to operations and timing of capital deployment.
Starting with operations. Occupancy reached an all-time high of 96.9% and was above 95% in every region. Our share of GAAP rent change was 12.4%, driven by the U.S. at 18%. The KTR assets had performed ahead of our underwriting for both occupancy and rent change. KTR has been fully integrated in our portfolio and is included in the operating statistics I discussed. 
Our share of GAAP same-store NOI increased 6.6% in the quarter, driven by the U.S. at 8.7%. As we discussed last quarter, the negative impact of on GAAP -- on GAAP NOI from the amortization of lease intangibles related to the merger have fully burned off. This again had a positive impact of about 100 basis points on GAAP same-store. 
Moving to our share of capital employment. We had an exceptional year and created significant value for our shareholders. We stabilized $1.6 billion of developments with an estimated margin of 33%. The initial yield on these stabilizations was 7.3% and the incremental cash return, excluding already owned land was 9.2%. Dispositions and contributions totaled $2.5 billion at a 5.3% weighted average stabilized cap rate and included $166 million of value creation from value-added conversions.
Dispositions and contributions volume was about $400 million short of the midpoint of our guidance. We elected to split a few sales across multiple buyers to maximize proceeds, and deferred certain contributions to amass better scale, pushing this activity into the first half of 2016. We started $1.8 billion of development, with build-to-suits making up 44%. The starts will generate estimated value creation of $388 million and margin of 21%.
Turning to capital markets. We had an active quarter and closed the year with our lines of credit fully undrawn, and reduced the short-term loan associated with the KTR acquisition to $400 million. We're on track to pay off the remainder of the term loan by the end of the first half of 2016, if not sooner. Our leverage on a book base has dropped to 130 basis points to 38.4% at quarter end. 
Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains improved to 6x for the quarter. While leverage and debt-to-EBITDA are very important credit metrics, there are other factors, which demonstrate the strength of our balance sheet. The first is liquidity. We ended the year with over $2.8 billion of liquidity and only 12% of our debt maturing in the next 24 months. Maintaining significant liquidity at all times is a pillar of our balance sheet strategy, as it mitigates credit market disruptions and provides ready capital to be opportunistic. 
Second is our significant nominal EBITDA coverage. We have over $1.5 billion of annualized EBITDA in excess of our fixed charges, underpinned by more than $25 billion of unencumbered assets. The bottom line is our balance sheet is in great shape and we expect it to get even stronger in 2016. 
Let's switch to 2016 guidance. For operation, we expect our year-end occupancy to range between 96% and 97% and our share of GAAP same-store NOI growth between 3.5% and 4.5%. Cash same-store NOI growth should be higher than GAAP in 2016. The split of our share of NOI by geography will be approximately 80% Americas, 15% Europe and 5% Asia. We expect our share development stabilizations to be between $1.6 billion and $1.8 billion, as stabilizations have increased meaningfully over the past 3 years and now approach our starts volume, continue to see significant annual NOI growth from our developments. 
For 2016, we expect FFO from development stabilizations of $0.10 to $0.12 per share. Related to FX, our 2016 earnings are very well insulated from foreign currency fluctuations as over 90% is already hedged. For net G&A, we're forecasting a range of $235 million to $245 million, essentially flat to last year at the midpoint, while managing more than $6 billion in assets. 
For strategic capital, we expect revenue without promotes to range between $180 million and $190 million. We have promote opportunities from 3 of our ventures in 2016, PTELF and PEPF II in the third quarter and USLV in the fourth quarter. We project net promotes to contribute between $0.17 and $0.19 per share to core FFO. The magnitude of these promotes is a testament to our strategic capital franchise as well as our strategy to allocate capital to Europe over the last 5 years. 
Over this period, we took advantage of a dislocation in asset prices in the market. Our European portfolio has consistently outperformed the market in terms of both occupancy and returns. 
Our capital deployment guidance is spelled out in our supplemental. At the midpoint of our net deployment, we will generate proceeds of about $400 million. Additionally, we have 2 other varied significant sources of cash in 2016.
First, we will receive $198 million in cash in the first quarter from a completion of the installment sale related to Facebook. And second, we redeemed a total of $400 million between our USLF and PTELF ventures, which we'll fund in the second quarter of 2016. This ownership rebalancing in these 2 open-ended funds is aligned with our long-term ownership targets and facilitates the deployment of substantial investment queues in these ventures. 
As a result, we expect to generate net deployment proceeds in excess of our capital needs of $1 billion in 2016 or $600 million after repayment of the last $400 million of the KTR term loan. 
Putting this altogether, we expect our 2016 core FFO to range between $2.50 and $2.60 pre share, including promotes. This represents 14% year-over-year growth or an increase of $0.32 per share at the midpoint. We expect AFFO growth will exceed core FFO growth in 2016. 
If we assume a normalized annual net promote of $0.05 per share, our core FFO range for 2016 would be between $2.38 a share and $2.46 a share, an increase of 9% year-over-year at the midpoint. In closing, we had an incredible year and enter 2016 with confidence though mindful of potential economic crosscurrents. We have a portfolio that has never been in better shape, a strong balance sheet and a plan that grows core FFO 14% pays off the remaining KTR debt; self funds all deployment; generates $1 billion of net deployment in excess for capital needs; maintain significant liquidity and it provides flexibility and optionality to adjust to changes in market conditions.
With that, I'll turn it over to the operator for questions.

componenttextpreview: Yes, Juan, this is Tom. I'll take that. So a couple of things to think about there. One, when you look at our coverage in 2015, our coverage with development gains is 69%; without development gains is 89%. For 2016, similar numbers would be with developme
componenttext: Yes, Juan, this is Tom. I'll take that. So a couple of things to think about there. One, when you look at our coverage in 2015, our coverage with development gains is 69%; without development gains is 89%. For 2016, similar numbers would be with development gains of 65% roughly and without development gains of about 75%. So we have significant AFFO coverage in excess of our dividend. Now you had a question about how the dividend might be impacted, if it could be impacted by changes in development. So what -- so the first thing you need to think about -- and I'm assuming you're referring to capitalized overhead and capitalized interest. So the first thing you need to think about though is how we're capitalizing development. We're capitalizing development by self funding, So we're selling assets and rolling those into development. And we're selling assets that are yielding, let's just call it 6%. And we're capping interest at a rate of roughly 3%. And when you look at our cap overhead, our capital overhead actually related to development, annually is about $47 million. And when you express that $47 million over development, it's about 3%. So if you think about -- if we slow down development, let's just take an extreme example. Let's just assume there's no development. So if we had development of $2 billion, we were going to sell $2 billion to fund that. The 6% we were earning on that development is going to stay in our income statement. The interest expense that we would've capped is going to stay in our income statement. The overhead that we were going to cap is going to stay on our income statement. And you know what? There's a 0 impact on our income statement, because all of that NOI that we would've used to fund that development, is going to stay on our books. So we're self-funding. So if the development slows down, never really impact -- no impact on our earnings.

Yes, this is Tom. I'll take that again. So as I said in my prepared remarks, we have some activity that just got pushed into 2016. But I want you to focus on a couple of things. So -- and when I talked about the sources of cash that we have, we have $600 million that's locked and loaded that's going to close in the first and second quarter of 2016 between the Facebook note and the fund rebalancing. 
That's $600 million. There's another $400 million of acquisitions alone that Mike can give color on that dispositions -- I'm sorry that Mike can give color on, that we feel extremely good about. There's $1 billion of capital right there that we will realize very, very quickly in cash. So it was really just a shift of timing to the end of the year, a point in time and we elected to shift some activity into '16 for very good economic reasons. But we feel great good about where we are. We're ahead of schedule from a KTR standpoint. I talked -- we talked about that funding, paying off the remaining $400 million by the end of the first half of the year. I think it's going to be April to be very specific when you look at all of the funding that we have in place that is certain to close.

componenttextpreview: Brendan, you probably remember this. But back in the beginning of time, 2011 or something, we actually laid out a plan that talked about development, in aggregate, being about $2 billion to $3 billion a year on a run rate basis in total, not our share. Ob
componenttext: Brendan, you probably remember this. But back in the beginning of time, 2011 or something, we actually laid out a plan that talked about development, in aggregate, being about $2 billion to $3 billion a year on a run rate basis in total, not our share. Obviously, the numbers you were quoting are our share, which are a little bit lower. And I would still say that's the opportunity set. But why get ahead of ourselves? I mean, we've got a very robust businesses pipeline right now. You can see that for the first time, we're projecting build-to-suits to be over 50% of our leasing activity. Again, reading the same papers, we want to be cautious. There is nothing that will stop us from starting up more development if we see more opportunity down the road. As Tom mentioned, we have $1 billion more capital than we need to finance KTR. We have the capital. We can do it. We have a lot of the land already, and we have time to make that decision. So I think we're being prudent and -- but we'll do the right thing whatever that maybe at that time.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Sure. I mean, remember what we're selling. We've -- first of all, let me take you back to the time of the merger, again, beginning of time. We sold over $8 billion of properties. Just think about that. I mean that I think would be the size of maybe the se
componenttext: Sure. I mean, remember what we're selling. We've -- first of all, let me take you back to the time of the merger, again, beginning of time. We sold over $8 billion of properties. Just think about that. I mean that I think would be the size of maybe the second-largest company in the sector. That's what we sold. And I think you know that we've been selling from the nonstrategic end of the spectrum. So you would expect those cap rates to be higher than our portfolio. And there is a lot of talk out there about what would the value of the portfolio be on a constant cap rate basis and the like. When you sell $8 billion from the lower tier of your portfolio, the mix has a very substantial impact on what cap rate is even in the steady environment on what's left in your portfolio. So we think the IRR at the end of the days is what matter, and those cap rates are higher because the growth rates are lower. And we feel really good about our capital allocation decisions. Just think about that capital we allocated to Europe couple of years ago. How do we fund that? We funded that by selling some nonstrategic assets in Europe. At the time, people thought we were crazy. We were selling assets in the U.S. in the mid 6s and low 7s, and we are buying assets in Europe in the low 8s. And those assets  that we bought in the low 8s are now in the high 5s and low 6s. So you got to take a longer-term view of these, and I wouldn't read too much into any quarter by quarter things, particularly when you have this mix issue going on with the numbers at this scale.

componenttextpreview: Let me clarify something about the promotes. We've received [ph] questions recently about our promotes, that's why we're selling assets. Our promotes have nothing to do with what assets we sell or what assets we hold. They're completely based, in the vast
componenttext: Let me clarify something about the promotes. We've received [ph] questions recently about our promotes, that's why we're selling assets. Our promotes have nothing to do with what assets we sell or what assets we hold. They're completely based, in the vast majority of cases, on appraised values on a quarter-by-quarter basis at the time of the promotes. So actually selling assets doesn't do anything to the promotes. I just wanted to clarify that. Secondly, I would say, we have pretty good visibility into the valuations because we appraise the portfolio, particularly the deals that are in the ventures on a quarterly basis. And we know what the carrying values are in the fourth quarter, and we put some sensitivity around that at scenarios that include cap rate expansion, flat cap rates, reducing cap rates. And we pick the prudent number to project those. Now to answer your specific questions, the promotes today are based in the high 5%-low 6% cap rate. And we think there's a bit of room in those numbers to the good, but we're not going to get ahead of ourselves now.

componenttext: Can you talk, Hamid, a little bit about what you're expecting market rents to do this year in light of the comments that you had earlier about reaching equilibrium? And then -- and maybe some thoughts even into next year as how the market rents for industrial plays out in the U.S.?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, let me -- let Gene address that. Gene?
componenttext: Yes, let me -- let Gene address that. Gene?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, so I think -- and we talked about this last quarter, I believe. So we said we're going to reach equilibrium this year, but we're going to reach equilibrium in the U.S. at least at a sort of mid-5 vacancy rate. I think, it'll be 5, 7 at the end of it.
componenttext: Yes, so I think -- and we talked about this last quarter, I believe. So we said we're going to reach equilibrium this year, but we're going to reach equilibrium in the U.S. at least at a sort of mid-5 vacancy rate. I think, it'll be 5, 7 at the end of it. And I think you can grow rents substantially above inflation during an equilibrium period, if your vacancy rate is that low. So I would guess for this year, we're going to see continued growth, so it's going to be 5-ish. And my view beyond that is that it's probably 4 to 5 the following year, because I don't think we're going to see excess construction next year or the year after. So it's in that range.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: The only thing I would add to what Gene said, Ross, is that for a couple of years now, we've been predicting cap rates are going to stay the same or expand, and we've been wrong about that. Now if CapEx do stay the same or expand, rental growth will be st
componenttext: The only thing I would add to what Gene said, Ross, is that for a couple of years now, we've been predicting cap rates are going to stay the same or expand, and we've been wrong about that. Now if CapEx do stay the same or expand, rental growth will be stronger because of the headwind of cap rate compression is going to be maybe turning into a tailwind or neutral wind anyway. So that's something to keep in mind as well.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: I think that's particularly shown in Europe, obviously, where we had 70 basis points of cap rate conversion over the last year and 20 basis in the last quarter and that's certainly been a headwind to arguably to push rents, but I expect that subsides back
componenttext: I think that's particularly shown in Europe, obviously, where we had 70 basis points of cap rate conversion over the last year and 20 basis in the last quarter and that's certainly been a headwind to arguably to push rents, but I expect that subsides back after this year.

componenttext: Hamid, you previously used the call as a platform to call attention to markets or even some markets that used felt some concern about -- are there any that stand out to you today? And I guess on the flip side of that, are there any markets that you're particularly optimistic about for 2016?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Sure. Tom, first of all, thank you for remembering that, because I think that's a very important part of our responsibilities to call out markets that have any risk of getting over built as from our vantage point. And the reason I hadn't mentioned it is b
componenttext: Sure. Tom, first of all, thank you for remembering that, because I think that's a very important part of our responsibilities to call out markets that have any risk of getting over built as from our vantage point. And the reason I hadn't mentioned it is because nothing has really changed in that regard. It's -- Houston, obviously, from demand reasons is a bit softer although it's holding up a bit better than we would've expected at this point. And Dallas continues to had a lot of development but absorption is keeping pace. So, so far, so good, but we're really watching those 2 markets probably more than any others in the U.S. I would say going over to Europe, Paris is a bit soft and its not really a supply problem, it's more of a demand problem. And I think some of it has to do with some of this heritage stuff that went on last quarter. But I don't know if France has generally been a little bit slower. The place that's been surprisingly strong in Europe for us, has been Spain. Spain's really done a turn around and I would say, it's done extremely well. The U.K. was early. In Europe -- and we thought it got a little bit ahead of itself and it may go the other way or soften. It hasn't, it continues to be pretty strong in terms of cap rates. And in the U.S., Chicago has been pretty good on the upside in the cycle. And the large California markets continue to be very, very strong. In the longer term, I'm a little concerned about the technology, sort of bubble and valuations and all that. And ultimately, that may have an impact on Bay area numbers not next year and probably the -- not that year after. But we've essentially taken a lot of chips off the table and that -- from that R&D type of product. And I don't think you will have much of an effect on the distribution space.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: We talked about the fund sell-downs in the rebalancing part of Tom's prepared remarks. So that's what we're doing. Our funds are -- we are way over the percentage that we need to have in the funds, I mean like double or triple of what our percentage shoul
componenttext: We talked about the fund sell-downs in the rebalancing part of Tom's prepared remarks. So that's what we're doing. Our funds are -- we are way over the percentage that we need to have in the funds, I mean like double or triple of what our percentage should be. And we're getting a lot of interest from our investors who are in the queues for investing in these funds to put their capital in and to invest. And we've gone to them and we said, "Okay, we're prepared to sell down to accommodate your needs." And by the way, we've also told the other investors, "Look, if you want to sell down along with us, come on down because we've got plenty of people who want to buy in and this is a good time to rebalance your portfolio." And 1 or 2 investors have taken advantage of that, but by and large, other people have not wanted to sell down and we never intended to have 40% in our funds. And the target was more around 15% or 20%, and we're not going to go all the way down to that level, certainly. But we're going to get back to a more normal allocation of our funds. I think there's some transactions that are locked and loaded that will -- that are based on fourth quarter valuations. So we know the values, we know the timing, we know the amounts. And that's why we feel so confident in our capital plan and not at all concerned about the things that we were asked about in terms of dispositions in the fourth quarter and all that. So we're watching these things on a real-time basis, and we have to adjust our disposition plans to balance the fund investments and that can continue to be a source of capital for us. I think in -- couple of quarters ago, we walked you through that there was about $3 billion of capital available because of our excess investment in our fund. So that is an effect of forward funding opportunity for anything that we may need capital for. And for the time being, we're really happy having our capital invested in that.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: Now Erik, with respect to your question about land, that's quite conscious. As you've heard me talk about, we have too much land to support our development, and that's partly a legacy issue from the last cycle. And we've got a challenge because as we mone
componenttext: Now Erik, with respect to your question about land, that's quite conscious. As you've heard me talk about, we have too much land to support our development, and that's partly a legacy issue from the last cycle. And we've got a challenge because as we monetize land in our development since value keeps going -- their value what remains keeps going up. So we've got a bit of a headwind in terms of getting our land down and you're just seeing the book value, actually. The market value is substantially higher than that. So we have a conscious decision to work down our land. In fact, what I'd like to see in our land be is to be under $1 billion, because I think it can support 2 or 3 years of development, with having that amount of land on our books. That means that we can unlock about $1 billion of capital from our land bank over some period of time. I hope it's sooner than later. But there's $1 billion of capital sitting there. If that were invested in income-producing properties, everything else being the same, that's another $60 million of earnings that are being wasted because they're parked in dead land. So that's another, what $0.12 a share, that would be really meaningful to our business. And our team is working hard to getting the land bank done. It takes time, but we'll get there.

componenttextpreview: Steve, as you know, I've been in this business since the early '80s and here in, originally, our business was entirely focused on the Bay Area. So we've seen -- I don't know 4 of these cycles before, it doesn't mean each 1 is going to be exactly the same
componenttext: Steve, as you know, I've been in this business since the early '80s and here in, originally, our business was entirely focused on the Bay Area. So we've seen -- I don't know 4 of these cycles before, it doesn't mean each 1 is going to be exactly the same as the last 1. But it just feels like everything is overstretched then you're seeing a couple of canneries in the coal mine, you're seeing the IPOs get price at the lower end of the range. You're seeing a lot of the companies go through down grounds and with the ratchets, really getting some investors squeezed. All of that stuff ultimately will affect demand for space, particularly -- and I should stop there because I'm not an office expert or R&D expert. And frankly, our portfolio with the Facebook and the other major sale in Moffett is essentially done -- we're done with that product-type almost. So it just feels like it's stretched. That's all I was trying to communicate there. I think the chances of real estate values going up a lot are not as high as their chances of values going down. How much is, your guess is as good as mine.

componenttext: So lot of people have asked about the dispositions and contributions, but I just wanted to kind of ask in one other way. Last quarter, you talked about doing $400 million of contributions you kind of talked about it as if that was in the bag. I know it looks like you guys only completed about $100 million. And what are we supposed to read into that, I mean, if it just get pushed to January 1, is it just a timing issue? Are you getting a little bit of pushback from your fund investors on taking some of these properties?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q4 2015 Earnings Call, Jan 26, 2016
componenttextpreview: This is Tom. It's all about timing. We look to amass a certain amount of scale. And if we see it in other asset that might be leasing up ahead of schedule, we will wait to amass that versus trying to do that as a one-off for weighting. So it's really timi
componenttext: This is Tom. It's all about timing. We look to amass a certain amount of scale. And if we see it in other asset that might be leasing up ahead of schedule, we will wait to amass that versus trying to do that as a one-off for weighting. So it's really timing. We feel very good about it. The process is very transparent on contributions. We don't have an obligation to all. Our partners on venture do not have an obligation to acquire, but we go through fair value. So there's nothing there from a process standpoint that has changed or a lack of desire. It's really timing. But you can see the timing shift when you look at our numbers, right, as far as the $1 billion. Even without contributions, we see about $1 billion. It's really locked and loaded as we look to the next quarter and a half. $600 million of that Facebook and redemption is, gosh, 2 months away.
