headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our First Quarter 2016 Conference Call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our First Quarter 2016 Conference Call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and the market environment; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance. Also joining us for today's call are Gary Anderson, Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly, and Diana Scott.
Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this conference call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings. 
Additionally, our first quarter press release and supplemental do contain financial measures such as FFO and EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures and in accordance with Reg G, we have provided a reconciliation to those measures. 
With that, we'll get started and I'll turn the call over to Hamid.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. 2016 is off to a great start. The momentum we had at the end of last year has continued into the new year. We posted record first quarter numbers on rent change, which was stronger than expected at over 20% and c
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. 2016 is off to a great start. The momentum we had at the end of last year has continued into the new year. We posted record first quarter numbers on rent change, which was stronger than expected at over 20% and core FFO, which grew 24% year-over-year. At this point in the cycle, we're pushing rent growth over occupancy. Nevertheless, occupancy is still very high at over 96%. These and other metrics, which Tom will discuss in a moment, point to continued growth ahead for Prologis. 
I'd like to take a moment to elaborate on how and where we make our money. Many of you already know this, but I believe it's worth repeating. We make over 90% of our core FFO by collecting rents. The rest is generated by fees and promotes from our strategic capital business. Together, rents and fees represent a stable cash flow created from our operating portfolio. Separately, the value creation from our development business, including value-added conversions, propels our future earnings growth. So our operating and development activities address how we make money. 
Now as to where we make our money when collecting rents, 72% is in the U.S. and 28% comes from abroad, roughly 90% of our net equity is in US dollar. Many ask us why we're global. In short, we're global because our customers are global. And so we've organized our business to capitalize on this unique aspect of our sector. About 2/3 of our development value creation, fees and promotes are generated outside the U.S. 
As on aside, these benefits actually cover more than 100% of our global overhead. I view Prologis as an owner-operator in the U.S. and a fund manager and developer in the U.S. and Asia. We have minimal exposure to emerging economies. Market conditions remain favorable in the world's most vibrant centers of commerce. In these strategic locations, demand was solid with supply still very disciplined. These business conditions have persisted for several years now. While we anticipated supply, demand reaching equilibrium this year, we see obstacles on the road ahead that could disrupt that balance. 
In the U.S. quality properties remain scarce, which is leading to strong rent growth and high occupancies. We'll continue to signal watchlist markets and this quarter, we have no new markets to call out. In Europe and Asia, rents are up modestly from last quarter, balanced by slightly lower occupancies. In Mexico, rents are up slightly and occupancy is flat. While in Brazil, rents are down modestly but occupancy is at 100%. The key drivers of our business, consumption and e-commerce, continue to grow faster than underlying economies. We have every reason to expect these trends to continue into the future. 
KTR is all paid off. Our funding activities, specifically the short-term loan associated with that deal, concluded less than one year after it was announced and ahead of schedule. With the transaction paid in full and the portfolio integrated, today's call is probably the last time you'll hear us talk about KTR. We have capacity to fund more than 5 years of capital deployment. At our current run rate, our total annual funding requirement is $600 million. We expect to fund this through the rebalancing of our co-investment ventures, reducing our land bank and reducing our nonstrategic assets. These onetime sources totaled more than $3.5 billion and give us the ability to fund more than 5 years of met deployment activity. 
We'll further simplify our business over time. Over the last several years, we made great strides in optimizing our business to put us on a path for long-term sustained earnings growth. In addition, look for us to continue streamline our business through the ongoing realignment of our portfolio, further G&A efficiencies, land bank optimization and reduced leverage. 
Now let me turn it over to Tom for further comments.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid. We began the year with terrific results. Core FFO was $0.61 per share for the quarter, an increase of 24% year-over-year and driven by strong operating fundamentals and an increase in AUM. Starting with operations. Occupancy in the U.S. was
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid. We began the year with terrific results. Core FFO was $0.61 per share for the quarter, an increase of 24% year-over-year and driven by strong operating fundamentals and an increase in AUM. Starting with operations. Occupancy in the U.S. was 96.6% at quarter end and 95.4% outside the U.S. Leasing volume for the quarter was a record at 46 million square feet. 
Just a quick reminder that my comments as I go through the rest of the operating and capital deployment activity will focus on our share. GAAP rent change on rollover was an all-time high of 20.1% led by the U.S. at 27.2% and 4% outside the U.S. GAAP same-store NOI increased 7.4% positive across all major geographies and driven by the U.S. at 9.6%. There are 2 items I want to highlight. 
First, as we previously discussed, the negative impact on GAAP NOI from the amortization of lease intangibles related to the merger burned off in the second quarter of 2015. As a result, this had a positive noncash impact of about 170 basis points on GAAP same-store growth in the third quarter. 
Second, expense timing drove an approximate 70 basis points positive impact. After adjusting for these 2 items, GAAP same-store growth was 5%, which was attributable to the strong rental increases and year-over-year occupancy gains. Strategic capital fees were $50 million for the quarter with a majority coming from our international joint ventures. Capital deployment activity is progressing as planned. There are 2 items I would like to highlight this quarter. 
First, that our stabilization had an estimated margin of 27%; and second, that build-to-suits comprised 42% of our development starts. Turning to Capital Markets. Our leverage on a book basis was 38.1% at quarter-end and 33.9% based on market capitalization. Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains, improved to 5.6x. 
As Hamid mentioned, we fully repaid the $400 million term loan associated with the KTR acquisition and liquidity remains strong. Last quarter -- this week, we recast our Global Line of Credit, lowering our spread by 10 basis points and increasing the capacity by $640 million. As a result, our total line capacity is now $3.4 billion, further enhancing our current significant liquidity levels. We expect to see further improvement in our debt metrics throughout the remainder of the year as our venture rebalancings were completed this month and the pace of dispositions accelerate. 
The continued strengthening of our balance sheet was acknowledged this quarter by both Moody's and Standard & Poor's, updated our credit outlook positive. We believe we're on the doorstep of an A rating. Before discussing guidelines, I want to highlight enhancements to our earnings supplemental this quarter. The changes are based on the feedback we received from investors and analysts as well as to better align our disclosure with how we think about and how we run the company. As part of this, we've revisited the classification of certain personnel costs at our income statement, which had the effect of increasing expenses related to our strategic capital business by $17 million on an annualized basis and reducing G&A by the same amount. 
There is no bottom line impact on net income or core FFO. For context, we completed the significant volume of co-investment activity over the past 5 years and almost doubled our third-party AUM. With this increase, we now have more full-time employees dedicated to our strategic capital business. 
Moving to 2016 guidance. We're maintaining guidance for most of our operating metrics, capital deployment and strategic capital revenues, all of which you can see on Page 6 of our supplemental. On same-store NOI, we are increasing the bottom end and narrowing the range to between 4% and 4.5% with a bias towards the upper half of this range. For net G&A, we are lowering the range to between $218 million and $228 million to reflect the reclassification I just mentioned. 
Related to FX. Our 2016 earnings remains well insulated from foreign currency at fluctuations as over 95% are hedged. We continue to expect to generate $1 billion of total proceeds in excess of our capital in 2016. This consists of $400 million in net deployment proceeds, $198 million of cash that we already received from the completion of the Facebook installment sale and $400 million from the ownership rebalancing in our U.S. and hotel ventures, which we will receive in a few weeks.
Further, we like what we are seeing in the disposition market and are likely to increase our volume. So while operating conditions are stronger than we expected, we are not increasing our core FFO given the potential dilution from increased dispositions. Therefore, we are maintaining our 2016 core FFO kind of between $2.50 and $2.60 per share. This includes $0.17 to $0.19 per share of promotes, which will recognize in the second half of this year. If we assume normalized annual net promote of $0.05 per share, our core FFO for 2016 would range from between $2.38 to $2.46 per share. 
Core FFO will not be evenly distributed for the balance of the year given the timing of our asset sales and venture rebalancing. As a result, we expect core FFO to be $0.03 or $0.04 lower in the second quarter, followed by an acceleration in the back half of the year from promote income. 
In closing, we are off to a really good start. Our focus for the rest of the year -- 2016 is simply about capturing the significant spreads between in-place and market rents, generating profitable returns by putting our land back to work and continuing to strengthen our balance sheet. 
With that I'll turn it over to the operator for questions.

componenttextpreview: Hamid, as we think about demand for industrial space, we spent a lot of time thinking about inventory levels given the historical correlation between absorptions and inventories. And then I look at what's been going on with inventory, the sales ratios lat
componenttext: Hamid, as we think about demand for industrial space, we spent a lot of time thinking about inventory levels given the historical correlation between absorptions and inventories. And then I look at what's been going on with inventory, the sales ratios lately, and I say lately, it's been ramping the last couple of years over the last year or 2, it's been ramping quite significantly. How do you think inventory to sales ratios are going to play out here going forward? You think we're going to see a bit more, I guess, modest inventory growth given what's been going on in the economy? And how does that play out in terms of demand for your space?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Ross, that's a very good question. And I think the answer is too soon to know for sure. But it appears that the secular decline in inventory to sales ratio that all of you are used to seeing on our materials going back, I don't know, 15 years or something
componenttext: Ross, that's a very good question. And I think the answer is too soon to know for sure. But it appears that the secular decline in inventory to sales ratio that all of you are used to seeing on our materials going back, I don't know, 15 years or something, really has reversed in the last 3 years. And there are lots of explanations for it. But the most credible one I think is the one that sales shift to commerce, there are more skews and there's a need to keep more inventory around. And as a result, there may be a secular shift. If that's the case, that's an unexpected windfall to demand for industrial space. We have not built our business with that expectation. But that will be a nice surprise if it happens and if it has legs forever. So too soon to tell for sure, but I think the early signs are pretty good.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: So going back to your opening comments, Hamid, you talked about the $3.5 billion of onetime funding sources, and how you're funding your -- you're going to be self-funding for the next 5 is a big activity. And that's been a pretty consistent message comin
componenttext: So going back to your opening comments, Hamid, you talked about the $3.5 billion of onetime funding sources, and how you're funding your -- you're going to be self-funding for the next 5 is a big activity. And that's been a pretty consistent message coming from you guys lately. But I guess, the equation to issue equity or not issue equity, and how to fund that activity it's a different equation at $40 versus $45 stock price. Could you just talk about how you think about that as your stock price has changed? Or is it still that $3.5 billion, is that still your primary source or how you want to fund it?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Look, I'm not going to sit here and say that we will never do equity if the stock price is at $60 or $70 or something like that. We'd be foolish not to do that because that clearly would be higher than our NAV. But our view of NAV, we've been pretty open
componenttext: Look, I'm not going to sit here and say that we will never do equity if the stock price is at $60 or $70 or something like that. We'd be foolish not to do that because that clearly would be higher than our NAV. But our view of NAV, we've been pretty open about it $46, $47 this year, that doesn't really include the value for the development business and I guess, there's a long debate as to whether that business is worth a 1 multiple or a 10 multiple. I can tell you, it's not worth the 15 or 20 multiple that people were valuing it at 2007 that's for sure. But it's worth something. It's worth at least a homebuilder. I think it's worth $3 or $5 a share pretty easily if you look at it as a homebuilder. So you add up all of that stuff, the number is around high 40s, low 50s kind of -- for the way I look at our NAV. So I don't even think about it. So I don't think the equation has changed between $40 and $45 because I think we're still way below where the value of the company is. But you got to look at equity in the context of other investment opportunities. If some portfolio comes up on the market or I don't think that's going to happen, but if something happens where we have an advantage to buy $45 of NAV at $20, we may take advantage of that but I don't think that's going to happen. And we're not an issuer of equity. And I think it is a complete waste of time for people to spend energy, thinking about that issue at these kinds of numbers.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: You guys have talked about getting your land balance down to about $1 billion or under. Some of that obviously, involves monetizing land through development. But -- and also involves disposing of land. So my question is, have you seen any movement in land
componenttext: You guys have talked about getting your land balance down to about $1 billion or under. Some of that obviously, involves monetizing land through development. But -- and also involves disposing of land. So my question is, have you seen any movement in land values over the past 6 months or so, especially as you and some of your public peers have become a little bit more conservative with respect to the expected starts this year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: I think land values in terms of good developable land that's near term developable, has gone up as rents have gone up. And it's very hard to find good land in the right markets. Entitlement costs are going up, infrastructure costs are going up. Communitie
componenttext: I think land values in terms of good developable land that's near term developable, has gone up as rents have gone up. And it's very hard to find good land in the right markets. Entitlement costs are going up, infrastructure costs are going up. Communities are getting tougher on land. So general trend and land values has been up. I would say about among our many, many parcels, every quarter we value our land using a land residual analysis. And I would say by and large, that trends has been up. There are I would say 3 or 4 parcels that of a very large number may be down, but the general trend is up. But it's not up as much as it would've been a year ago or 2 years ago. The pace of land value growth has moderated. The other thing I would point out is that yes, our land bank is about $1.5 billion book value, but the market value that in our view of again, based on pretty robust analysis is approaching to may be in the low $2 billion range. So in terms of what we can work our land bank down is not $0.5 billion down to $1 billion, it's like $1 billion down to $1 billion in terms of value because the market value land is what we were targeting for. So we've got quite a bit of liquidity that can come out of the land bank to add to that $3.5 billion that we've talked about.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, Gene, I'll start with that at least. As obviously, Houston and Pennsylvania are 2 markets that we've called out as markets that we were concerned about. Houston, pretty obvious reasons why. And Pennsylvania is sort of a combination of a spike in supp
componenttext: Yes, Gene, I'll start with that at least. As obviously, Houston and Pennsylvania are 2 markets that we've called out as markets that we were concerned about. Houston, pretty obvious reasons why. And Pennsylvania is sort of a combination of a spike in supply and demand tailing off. But I wouldn't draw any conclusions, Erik, about the specific adjustments and vacancy in those markets. I don't think that's going to continue for a long time, I think in both cases, we're going to end up in the sort of mid-90s. But let me say a couple of other things about both of them. So Houston has been on our watch list. Vacancy was up a little bit over the quarter and it has 8 million of square feet of construction. We're defensive there and I think we've been saying that for a while. While the macro headwinds, obviously persists, we're almost 96% leased. The pipe is 50% pre-leased and there's still a 6% vacancy rate in Houston. And Houston isn't creating a lot of jobs, but it's net positive not negative at this point in time. And then in terms of Pennsylvania, probably we're a little more cautious in terms of Pennsylvania at this point in time. To your point on e-commerce trends. Erik, I -- we don't see any new trends coming out of this prior season. I think that everybody participating in this space, it's still -- that's really trying to figure out the supply chain both still the last mile, which everybody is talking about these days all the way to the origin of the product because different participants handle it differently. So we don't really have anything new for you right now. I don't know if Gary, if you see anything different in your.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: And I would just say, there are 2 trends that have occurred over the last 2 years, 2 important customer segments. One is automotive and the other one is e-commerce, and e-commerce started the equation, isn't a seasonal thing. You sort of post your questio
componenttext: And I would just say, there are 2 trends that have occurred over the last 2 years, 2 important customer segments. One is automotive and the other one is e-commerce, and e-commerce started the equation, isn't a seasonal thing. You sort of post your question in terms of seasonality, it's really a structural change, I think in the way companies are doing business today and if you look at our own portfolio as an example, 2 or 3 years ago, it was about 5% of our total portfolio, today it's doubled that. Clearly, it's an important driver and one I wouldn't think about just in terms of a seasonal type trend.

componenttext: Hamid, if we can just turn to the comment you made in the press release and repeated on the call, about sort of trends exceeding underlying economies. Are the economies performing sort of at your expectations and trends are just that much better? Are you seeing a slowing and trends are really kind of what you're expecting, but the economies are not?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Manny, my take on the economy is really out of my depth of expertise here, but seems to me that the U.S. economy is sort of a mid to high 2% grow or minus energy. So that means it's a 1.5% to 2% grower. And so the trends that affect our business, remember
componenttext: Manny, my take on the economy is really out of my depth of expertise here, but seems to me that the U.S. economy is sort of a mid to high 2% grow or minus energy. So that means it's a 1.5% to 2% grower. And so the trends that affect our business, remember energy doesn't go through pipelines, it doesn't go through warehouses. The energy pricing generally being lower has led to better consumption numbers. And more of that consumption is shifting to the e-commerce channel, which is more space intensive. So those 2 things have made demand for our product better than they would have been based on the overall economic numbers. On top of that, this issue that I talked about earlier, which is the inventory to sales ratio is turning up, which may be a third factor or you may look at it as a second factor, which is e-commerce. I don't know. One of those 2. So there are either 2 or 3 factors that are making the -- our demand drivers for our business better than the underlying economy. That's my take of it. I don't know for sure, but we'll see. But that's what I think is going on.

componenttextpreview: My question has to do with international markets. Obviously, you guys have visibility into international markets more so than a lot of other industrial landlords out there. Just wondering if you could comment on trends and fundamentals in both Europe and
componenttext: My question has to do with international markets. Obviously, you guys have visibility into international markets more so than a lot of other industrial landlords out there. Just wondering if you could comment on trends and fundamentals in both Europe and Asia, and if you're seeing any movement in cap rates as well.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes. Let's start in Europe. Cap rates are generally flat for the last couple of quarters. Our expectation there though that you can see another 15 to 30 basis points this year. Trends are good. For the first time, we're viewing Europe as a potential tailw
componenttext: Yes. Let's start in Europe. Cap rates are generally flat for the last couple of quarters. Our expectation there though that you can see another 15 to 30 basis points this year. Trends are good. For the first time, we're viewing Europe as a potential tailwinds of the company the outlook you're looking at market vacancies as a whole, if vacancies not occupancy, vacancies will drop 60 basis points. So we'll be at somewhere around market vacancy, about 5.8%, which is nearing sort of U.S. level, so we expect Europe to perform well on a go-forward basis. And then in Asia, the markets there I think are performing well. Japan is sitting there at about 96.3% occupied, and we're seeing good net absorption. So Japan is performing well. China is a business that I think some have concern of. It's a small business for us but one that again is performing pretty well. We're about 92% occupied in our overall portfolio, but if you look at the supplemental, you'll see that there is a restock, occupy spread of about 200 basis points so you should expect occupancies in China to trend up the other comment that I'd make about China is that we've done about 2 million square feet of development leasing in this quarter, which is about 30% of the total leasing for the quarter for the company. So it's performing very well. So net-net, I'd say the international markets are performing to expectation and it will become a tailwind.

componenttextpreview: Just a question on leverage levels and the uses of cash. There was a modest sequentially decline in net debt from the fourth quarter, but it looks like you already realized over half of that $1 billion you're guiding to, so proceeds for the full year. So
componenttext: Just a question on leverage levels and the uses of cash. There was a modest sequentially decline in net debt from the fourth quarter, but it looks like you already realized over half of that $1 billion you're guiding to, so proceeds for the full year. So I just want to know if there's something else beyond development that we should be thinking about as a substantial use of cash in the quarter? And then also whether we should continue to expect net proceeds deployed to reduce net proceeds over the remainder of the year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Brad, it's Tom. So I'll take those questions. First on LTV. You're right, on LTV, you would have appeared, didn't decline enough based on activity for the quarter, what's happening is it's really a function of weakening of the dollar and the strengthening
componenttext: Brad, it's Tom. So I'll take those questions. First on LTV. You're right, on LTV, you would have appeared, didn't decline enough based on activity for the quarter, what's happening is it's really a function of weakening of the dollar and the strengthening of the yen and the euro, and there's a denominator effect that I will explain. So if you think of in yen and in euro, and only 25% of our assets are. So when the yen and the euro increased against that liability, that debt, that increase took our debt levels up in U.S. dollar terms by about $300 million. But we didn't have the same $300 million increase in our denominator because only 25% of our assets are in euro and in yen. So there's the denominator effect and that affected leverage by about 70 basis points this quarter. So you really economically we add about 100 basis points decline this quarter, a little over actually. But that's FX noise. On your point about deployment proceeds for the rest of the year and how we're going to use that $1 billion of cash, we're going to look at our debt stack and we're going to determine if there is debt where economically or frictionless pay that off. We do have a multicurrency term loan that's out there that matures in a couple of years that would fit that bill. We always look at bond maturities to see if there's economically, if it makes sense to do that and we'll sit on cash. But I can tell you when we look at guidance, either the debt that we pay off is either extremely low rate debt. So it doesn't have a significant impact on our results for the rest of the year.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: And to also state the obvious, the corresponding asset value increase in the same currency obviously, doesn't factor into that leverage calculation. So you need to take that into account as well. So it's not as if our debt went up and the asset didn't go
componenttext: And to also state the obvious, the corresponding asset value increase in the same currency obviously, doesn't factor into that leverage calculation. So you need to take that into account as well. So it's not as if our debt went up and the asset didn't go up, both of those are in the same currency.

componenttext:
Good afternoon. My name is Kim, and I'll be your conference operator today. At this time, I'd like to welcome everyone to the First Quarter 2016 Prologis Earnings Call. [Operator Instructions]
Thank you. Ms. Tracy Ward, Senior Vice President, Investor Relations, you may begin your conference.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our first quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our first quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and the market environment; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance. Also joining us for today's call are Gary Anderson, Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly, and Diana Scott.
Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this conference call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings. 
Additionally, our first quarter press release and supplemental do contain financial measures such as FFO and EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures. And in accordance with Reg G, we've provided a reconciliation to those measures. 
With that, we'll get started, and I'll turn the call over to Hamid.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. 2016 is off to a great start. The momentum we had at the end of last year has continued into the new year. We posted record first quarter numbers on rent change, which was stronger than expected at over 20% and c
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. 2016 is off to a great start. The momentum we had at the end of last year has continued into the new year. We posted record first quarter numbers on rent change, which was stronger than expected at over 20% and core FFO, which grew 24% year-over-year. At this point in the cycle, we're pushing rent growth over occupancy. Nevertheless, occupancy is still very high at over 96%. These and other metrics, which Tom will discuss in a moment, point to continued growth ahead for Prologis. 
I'd like to take a moment to elaborate on how and where we make our money. Many of you already know this, but I believe it's worth repeating. We make over 90% of our core FFO by collecting rent. The rest is generated by fees and promotes from our strategic capital business. Together, rents and fees represent a stable cash flow created from our operating portfolio. Separately, the value creation from our development business, including value-added conversions, propels our future earnings growth. So our operating and development activities address how we make money. 
Now as to where we make our money, when collecting rents, 72% is in the U.S. and 28% comes from abroad. Roughly, 90% of our net equity is in US dollars. Many ask us why we're global. In short, we're global because our customers are global. And so we've organized our business to capitalize on this unique aspect of our sector. About 2/3 of our development value creation, fees and promotes are generated outside the U.S. 
As an aside, these benefits actually cover more than 100% of our global overhead. I view Prologis as an owner-operator in the U.S. and a fund manager and developer in Europe and Asia. We have minimal exposure to emerging economies. Market conditions remain favorable in the world's most vibrant centers of commerce. In these strategic locations, demand was solid with supply still very disciplined. These business conditions have persisted for several years now. While we anticipate supply/demand reaching equilibrium this year, we see few obstacles on the road ahead that could disrupt that balance.
In the U.S., quality properties remain scarce, which is leading to strong rent growth and high occupancies. We'll continue to signal watch-list markets. In this quarter, we have no new markets to call out. In Europe and Asia, rents are up modestly from last quarter, balanced by slightly lower occupancies. In Mexico, rents are up slightly and occupancy is flat. While in Brazil, rents are down modestly, but occupancy is at 100%. The key drivers of our business, consumption and e-commerce, continue to grow faster than underlying economies. We have every reason to expect these trends to continue into the future. 
KTR is all paid off. Our funding activities, specifically the short-term loan associated with that deal, concluded less than 1 year after it was announced and ahead of schedule. With the transaction paid in full and the portfolio integrated, today's call is probably the last time you'll hear us talk about KTR. We have capacity to fund more than 5 years of capital deployment. At our current run rate, our total annual funding requirement is $600 million. We expect to fund this through the rebalancing of our co-investment ventures, reducing our land bank and selling our remaining nonstrategic assets. These onetime sources totaled more than $3.5 billion and give us the ability to fund more than 5 years of net deployment activity. 
We'll further simplify our business over time. Over the last several years, we made great strides in optimizing our business to put us on a path for long term sustained earnings growth. In addition, look for us to continue streamline our business through the ongoing realignment of our portfolio, further G&A efficiencies, land bank optimization and reduced leverage. 
Now let me turn it over to Tom for further comments.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid. We began the year with terrific results. Core FFO was $0.61 per share for the quarter, an increase of 24% year-over-year and driven by strong operating fundamentals and an increase in AUM. Starting with operations. Occupancy in the U.S. was
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid. We began the year with terrific results. Core FFO was $0.61 per share for the quarter, an increase of 24% year-over-year and driven by strong operating fundamentals and an increase in AUM. Starting with operations. Occupancy in the U.S. was 96.6% at quarter end and 95.4% outside the U.S. Leasing volume for the quarter was a record at 46 million square feet. 
Just a quick reminder that my comments, as I go through the rest of the operating and capital deployment activity, will focus on our share. GAAP rent change on rollover was an all-time high of 20.1%, led by the U.S. at 27.2% and 4% outside the U.S. GAAP same-store NOI increased 7.4%, positive across all major geographies and driven by the U.S. at 9.6%. There are 2 items I want to highlight. 
First, as we previously discussed, the negative impact on GAAP NOI from the amortization of lease intangibles related to the merger burned off in the second quarter of 2015. As a result, this had a positive noncash impact of about 170 basis points on GAAP same-store growth in the quarter. 
Second, expense timing drove an approximate 70 basis points positive impact. After adjusting for these 2 items, GAAP same-store growth was 5%, which is attributable to the strong rental increases and year-over-year occupancy gains. Strategic capital fees were $50 million for the quarter, with a majority coming from our international ventures. Capital deployment activity is progressing as planned. There are 2 items I would like to highlight this quarter. 
First, that our stabilizations had an estimated margin of 27%; and second, that build-to-suits comprised 42% of our development starts. Turning to capital markets. Our leverage on a book basis was 38.1% at quarter end and 33.9% based on market capitalization. Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains, improved to 5.6x. 
As Hamid mentioned, we fully repaid the $400 million term loan associated with the KTR acquisition and liquidity remained strong. Last quarter -- I'm sorry, this week, we recast our Global Line of Credit, lowering our spread by 10 basis points and increasing the capacity by $640 million. As a result, our total line capacity is now $3.4 billion, further enhancing our current significant liquidity levels. We expect to see further improvement in our debt metrics throughout the remainder of the year as our venture rebalancings were completed this month and the pace of dispositions accelerate. 
The continued strengthening of our balance sheet was acknowledged this quarter by both Moody's and Standard & Poor's, upgraded our credit outlook to positive. We believe we are on the doorstep of an A rating. Before discussing guidance, I wanted to highlight the enhancements to our earnings supplemental this quarter. The changes are based on the feedback we received from investors and analysts as well as to better align our disclosure with how we think about and how we run the company. As part of this, we've revisited the classification of certain personnel costs in our income statement, which had the effect of increasing expenses related to our strategic capital business by $17 million on an annual basis and reducing G&A by the same amount. 
There is no bottom line impact on net income or core FFO. For context, we completed a significant volume of co-investment activity over the past 5 years and almost doubled our third-party AUM. With this increase, we now have more full-time employees dedicated to our strategic capital business. 
Moving to 2016 guidance. We're maintaining guidance for most of our operating metrics, capital deployment and strategic capital revenues, all of which you can see on Page 6 of our supplemental. On same-store NOI, we are increasing the bottom end and narrowing the range to between 4% and 4.5%, with a bias towards the upper half of this range. For net G&A, we are lowering the range to between $218 million and $228 million to reflect the reclassification I just mentioned. 
Related to FX. Our 2016 earnings remain well insulated from foreign currency fluctuations as over 95% are hedged. We continue to expect to generate $1 billion of total proceeds in excess of our capital needs in 2016. This consist a $400 million in net deployment proceeds, $198 million of cash that we already received from the completion of the Facebook installment sale and $400 million from the ownership rebalancing in our USLF and PTELF ventures, which we will receive in a few weeks.
Further, we like what we are seeing in the disposition market and are likely to increase our volume. So while operating conditions are stronger than we expected, we are not increasing our core FFO given the potential dilution from increased dispositions. Therefore, we are maintaining our 2016 core FFO guidance between $2.50 and $2.60 per share. This includes $0.17 to $0.19 per share of promotes, which will recognize in the second half of this year. If we assume normalized annual net promotes of $0.05 per share, our core FFO for 2016 would range between $2.38 to $2.46 per share. 
Core FFO will not be evenly distributed for the balance of the year, given the timing of our asset sales and venture rebalancing. As a result, we expect core FFO to be $0.03 or $0.04 lower in the second quarter, followed by an acceleration in the back half of the year from promote income. 
In closing, we are off to a really good start. Our focus for the rest of the 2016 is simply about capturing the significant spreads between in-place and market rents, generating profitable returns by putting our land bank to work and continuing to strengthen our balance sheet. 
With that, I'll turn it over to the operator for questions.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Hamid, as we think about demand for industrial space, we spent a lot of time thinking about inventory levels given the historical correlation between absorption and inventories. And then I look at what's been going on with inventory to sales ratios lately
componenttext: Hamid, as we think about demand for industrial space, we spent a lot of time thinking about inventory levels given the historical correlation between absorption and inventories. And then I look at what's been going on with inventory to sales ratios lately, and I say lately, it's been ramping the last couple of years, but over the last year or 2, it's been ramping quite significantly. How do you think inventory to sales ratios are going to play out here going forward? Do you think we're going to see a bit more, I guess, modest inventory growth given what's going on in the economy? And how does that play out in terms of demand for your space?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Ross, that's a very good question. And I think the answer is too soon to know for sure. But it appears that that the secular decline in inventory to sales ratio that all of you are used to see in our materials going back, I don't know, 15 years or somethi
componenttext: Ross, that's a very good question. And I think the answer is too soon to know for sure. But it appears that that the secular decline in inventory to sales ratio that all of you are used to see in our materials going back, I don't know, 15 years or something, really has reversed in the last 3 years. And there are lots of explanations for it. But the most credible one I think is the one that has more sales shift to e-commerce, there are more skews and there's a need to keep more inventory around. And as a result, there may be a secular shift. If that's the case, that's unexpected windfall to demand for industrial space. We have not built our business with that expectation. But that will be a nice surprise if it happens and if it has legs forever. So too soon to tell for sure, but I think the early signs are really good.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: So going back to your opening comments, Hamid, you talked about the $3.5 billion of onetime funding sources, and how you're funding your -- you're going to be self-funding for the next 5 years with activity. And that's been a pretty consistent message com
componenttext: So going back to your opening comments, Hamid, you talked about the $3.5 billion of onetime funding sources, and how you're funding your -- you're going to be self-funding for the next 5 years with activity. And that's been a pretty consistent message coming from you guys lately. But I guess, the equation to issue equity or not issue equity and how to fund that activity is a different equation at $40 versus $45 stock price. Could you just talk about how you think about that as your stock price has changed? Or is it still that $3.5 billion is -- is that still your primary source how you want to funded it?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Look, I'm not going to sit here and say that we will never do equity if the stock price is at $60 or $70 or something like that. We'd be foolish not to do that because that clearly would be higher than our NAV. But our view of NAV, we've been pretty open
componenttext: Look, I'm not going to sit here and say that we will never do equity if the stock price is at $60 or $70 or something like that. We'd be foolish not to do that because that clearly would be higher than our NAV. But our view of NAV, we've been pretty open about it, $46, $47 a share, that doesn't really include the value for development business. And I guess, there's a long debate as to whether that business is worth a 1 multiple or a 10 multiple. I can tell you, it's not worth the 15 or 20 multiple that people were valuing it at 2007, that's for sure. But it's worth something. It's worth at least a homebuilder. I think it's worth $3 or $5 a share pretty easily if you look at it as a homebuilder. So you add up all that stuff, the number is around high 40s, low 50s kind of -- for the way I look at our NAV. So I don't even think about it. So I don't think the equation has changed between $40 and $45 because we're still way below where I think the value of the company is. But you got to look at equity in the context of other investment opportunities. If some portfolio comes up on to market or I don't think that's going to happen, but if something happens where we have an advantage to buy $45 of NAV at $20, we may take advantage of that. But I don't think that's going to happen. And we're not an issuer of equity. And I think it is a complete waste of time for people to spend energy thinking about that issue at these kinds of numbers.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: You guys have talked about getting your land balance down to about $1 billion or under. Some of that obviously involves monetizing lands through development. But -- it also involves disposing of land. So my question is, have you seen any movement in land
componenttext: You guys have talked about getting your land balance down to about $1 billion or under. Some of that obviously involves monetizing lands through development. But -- it also involves disposing of land. So my question is, have you seen any movement in land values over the past 6 months or so, especially as you and some of your public peers have become a little bit more conservative with respect to the expected starts this year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: I think land values in terms of good developable land that's near term developable has gone up as rents have gone up. And it's very hard to find good land in the right markets. Entitlement costs are going up. Infrastructure costs are going up. Communities
componenttext: I think land values in terms of good developable land that's near term developable has gone up as rents have gone up. And it's very hard to find good land in the right markets. Entitlement costs are going up. Infrastructure costs are going up. Communities are getting tougher on land. So general trend in land values has been up. I would say, among our many, many parcels, every quarter we value our land using a land residual analysis. And I would say by and large, the trends has been up. There are, I would say, 3 or 4 parcels that of a very large number may be down, but the general trend is up. But it's not up as much as it would've been a year ago or 2 years ago. The pace of land value growth has moderated. The other thing I would point out is that, yes, our land bank is about $1.5 billion for book value, but the market value of that, in our view, again, based on pretty robust analysis is approaching to may be in the low $2 billion range. So in terms of what we can work our land bank down is not $0.5 billion down to $1 billion, it's like $1 billion down to $1 billion in terms of market value because the market value land is what we were targeting for. So we've got quite a bit of liquidity that could come out of the land bank to add to that $3.5 billion that we've talked about.

componenttext: Okay, Juan. This is Tom. I'll start. The decline -- the benefit we got from the lower occupancy expenses in Q1 this year was really a function of Q1 of '15 being higher than normal. So if you go back and you look at the increase if Q1 of '15, I think it was around 7%. componenttext: First, just a couple of portfolio-specific questions. Could you comment on the occupancy declines in Houston, in Pennsylvania? And then secondly, perhaps you can touch -- perhaps provide e-commerce update and just if you can relay your experiences with your customers in terms of how they accommodate e-commerce growth during the holiday season, whether they see any changes in their supply chain as a result?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Eric, it's Gene, I'll start with that at least. Well, obviously, Houston and Pennsylvania are 2 markets that we've called out as markets we're concerned about. Houston, pretty obvious reasons why. And Pennsylvania is sort of a combination of a spike in su
componenttext: Eric, it's Gene, I'll start with that at least. Well, obviously, Houston and Pennsylvania are 2 markets that we've called out as markets we're concerned about. Houston, pretty obvious reasons why. And Pennsylvania is sort of a combination of a spike in supply and demand tailing off. But I wouldn't draw any conclusions, Eric, about the specific adjustments and vacancy in those markets. I don't think that's going to continue for a long time. I think in both cases, we're going to end up in the sort of mid-90s. But let me say a couple of other things about both of them. So Houston has been on our watch list. Vacancy was up a little bit over the quarter and it has 8 million square feet on construction. We're defensive there and I think we've been saying that for a while. While the macro headwind obviously persists, we're almost 96% leased. The pipe is 50% preleased and there's still a 6% vacancy rate in Houston. And Houston isn't creating a lot of jobs, but it's net positive not negative at this point in time. And then in terms of Pennsylvania, probably we're a little more cautious in terms of Pennsylvania at this point in time. To your point on e-commerce trends. Eric, we don't see any new trends coming out of this prior season. I think that everybody participating in this space is still desperately trying to figure out the supply chain both the last mile, which everybody is talking about these days all the way to the origin of the product because different participants handle it differently. So we don't really have anything new for you right now. I don't know, Gary, if you see anything different in your opinion.

componenttext: And I'd just say that there are 2 trends that have occurred over the last 2 years, 2 important customer segments. One is automotive and the other is e-commerce. And e-commerce started the equation, isn't a seasonal thing. You sort of pose your question in terms of seasonality. And if you look at our own portfolio as an example, 2 or 3 years ago, it was about 5% of our total portfolio; today, it's doubled that. headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Manny, my take on the economies and I'm really out of my depth of expertise here, but seems to me that the U.S. economy is sort of a mid to high 2% grow or minus energy. So that means it's a 1.5% to 2% grower. And so the trends that affect our business, r
componenttext: Manny, my take on the economies and I'm really out of my depth of expertise here, but seems to me that the U.S. economy is sort of a mid to high 2% grow or minus energy. So that means it's a 1.5% to 2% grower. And so the trends that affect our business, remember energy doesn't go through pipelines, it doesn't go through warehouses. The energy pricing generally being lower has led to better consumption numbers. And more of that consumption is shifting to the e-commerce channel, which is more space intensive. So those 2 things have made demand for our product better than they would have been based on the overall economic numbers. On top of that, this issue that I talked about earlier, which is the inventory to sales ratio is turning up, which may be a third factor or you may look at it as part of the second factor, which is e-commerce. I don't know. One of those 2. So there are either 2 or 3 factors that are making the -- our demand drivers for our business better than the underlying economy. That's my take of it. I don't know for sure, but we'll see. But that's what I think is going on.

componenttext: My question has to do with international markets. Obviously, you guys have visibility into international markets more so than a lot of other industrial landlords out there. Just wondering if you could comment on trends and fundamentals in both Europe and Asia, and then if you're seeing any movement in cap rates as well.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes. Let's start in Europe. Cap rates are generally flat for the last couple of quarters. Our expectation there though that you can see another 15 to 30 basis points this year. Trends are good. For the first time, we're viewing Europe as a potential tailw
componenttext: Yes. Let's start in Europe. Cap rates are generally flat for the last couple of quarters. Our expectation there though that you can see another 15 to 30 basis points this year. Trends are good. For the first time, we're viewing Europe as a potential tailwind to the company. The outlook, when you're looking at market vacancies as a whole, that vacancy is not occupancy, vacancies will drop 60 basis points. So we'll be at somewhere around market vacancy is about 5.8%, which is nearing sort of U.S. level, so expect Europe to perform well on a go-forward basis. And in Asia, the markets there I think are performing well. Japan is sitting there at about 96.3% occupied, and we're seeing good net absorption. So Japan is performing well. China is a business that I think some have concern. It's a small business for us, but one that again is performing pretty well. We're at about 92% occupied in our overall portfolio. But if you look at the supplemental, you'll see that there is a list occupied spread of about 200 basis points. So you should expect occupancies in China to trend up. The other comment I'd make about China is that we've done about 2 million square feet of development leasing this quarter, which is about 30% of the total leasing for the quarter for the company. So it's performing pretty very well. So net-net, I'd say that international markets are performing to expectation and will become a tailwind.

componenttext: Just a question on leverage levels and uses of cash. There was a modest sequential decline in net debt from the fourth quarter, but it looks like you've already realized over half of that $1 billion you're guiding to, so proceeds for the full year. So I just want to know if there's something else beyond development that we should be thinking about as a substantial use of cash in the quarter? And then also whether we should continue to expect net proceeds deployed to reduce net debt over the remainder of the year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Brad, it's Tom. So I'll take those questions. First, on LTV. You're right, LTV, you would have appeared, didn't decline enough based on our activity for the quarter and what's happening is it's really a function of weakening of the dollar and the strength
componenttext: Brad, it's Tom. So I'll take those questions. First, on LTV. You're right, LTV, you would have appeared, didn't decline enough based on our activity for the quarter and what's happening is it's really a function of weakening of the dollar and the strengthening of the yen and the euro. And there's a denominator effect that I will explain. So when you think about about half of our debts in yen and euro, but only about 25% of our assets are. So when the yen and the euro increased against that liability, that debt, that increase took our debt levels up in U.S. dollar terms by about $300 million. But we didn't have the same $300 million increase in our denominator because only 25% of our assets are in euro and yen. So there's a denominator effect and that impacted leverage by about 70 basis points this quarter. So you really -- economically, we had about 100 basis points decline this quarter, a little over actually. But that's FX noise. On your point about deployment proceeds for the rest of the year and how we're going to use that $1 billion of cash, we're going to look at our debt stack and we're going to determine if there is debt where we can economically or frictionlessly pay that off. We do have a multicurrency term loan that's out there that matures in a couple of years that would fit that bill. We always look at bond maturities to see if there's economically, it makes sense to do that or we'll sit on cash. But I would tell you when you look at our guidance, either the debt that we have to pay off is extremely low-rate debt. So it doesn't have a significant impact on our results for the rest of the year.

Good afternoon. My name is Kim, and I'll be your conference operator today. At this time, I'd like to welcome everyone to the First Quarter 2016 Prologis Earnings Call. [Operator Instructions]
Thank you. Ms. Tracy Ward, Senior Vice President, Investor Relations, you may begin your conference.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our first quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our first quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and the market environment; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance. Also joining us for today's call are Gary Anderson, Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly, and Diana Scott.
Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this conference call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings. 
Additionally, our first quarter press release and supplemental do contain financial measures such as FFO and EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures. And in accordance with Reg G, we've provided a reconciliation to those measures. 
With that, we'll get started, and I'll turn the call over to Hamid.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. 2016 is off to a great start. The momentum we had at the end of last year has continued into the new year. We posted record first quarter numbers on rent change, which was stronger than expected at over 20% and c
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. 2016 is off to a great start. The momentum we had at the end of last year has continued into the new year. We posted record first quarter numbers on rent change, which was stronger than expected at over 20% and core FFO, which grew 24% year-over-year. At this point in the cycle, we're pushing rent growth over occupancy. Nevertheless, occupancy is still very high at over 96%. These and other metrics, which Tom will discuss in a moment, point to continued growth ahead for Prologis. 
I'd like to take a moment to elaborate on how and where we make our money. Many of you already know this, but I believe it's worth repeating. We make over 90% of our core FFO by collecting rent. The rest is generated by fees and promotes from our strategic capital business. Together, rents and fees represent a stable cash flow created from our operating portfolio. Separately, the value creation from our development business, including value-added conversions, propels our future earnings growth. So our operating and development activities address how we make money. 
Now as to where we make our money, when collecting rents, 72% is in the U.S. and 28% comes from abroad. Roughly, 90% of our net equity is in US dollars. Many ask us why we're global. In short, we're global because our customers are global. And so we've organized our business to capitalize on this unique aspect of our sector. About 2/3 of our development value creation, fees and promotes are generated outside the U.S. 
As an aside, these benefits actually cover more than 100% of our global overhead. I view Prologis as an owner-operator in the U.S. and a fund manager and developer in Europe and Asia. We have minimal exposure to emerging economies. Market conditions remain favorable in the world's most vibrant centers of commerce. In these strategic locations, demand was solid with supply still very disciplined. These business conditions have persisted for several years now. While we anticipate supply/demand reaching equilibrium this year, we see few obstacles on the road ahead that could disrupt that balance.
In the U.S., quality properties remain scarce, which is leading to strong rent growth and high occupancies. We'll continue to signal watch-list markets. In this quarter, we have no new markets to call out. In Europe and Asia, rents are up modestly from last quarter, balanced by slightly lower occupancies. In Mexico, rents are up slightly and occupancy is flat. While in Brazil, rents are down modestly, but occupancy is at 100%. The key drivers of our business, consumption and e-commerce, continue to grow faster than underlying economies. We have every reason to expect these trends to continue into the future. 
KTR is all paid off. Our funding activities, specifically the short-term loan associated with that deal, concluded less than 1 year after it was announced and ahead of schedule. With the transaction paid in full and the portfolio integrated, today's call is probably the last time you'll hear us talk about KTR. We have capacity to fund more than 5 years of capital deployment. At our current run rate, our total annual funding requirement is $600 million. We expect to fund this through the rebalancing of our co-investment ventures, reducing our land bank and selling our remaining nonstrategic assets. These onetime sources totaled more than $3.5 billion and give us the ability to fund more than 5 years of net deployment activity. 
We'll further simplify our business over time. Over the last several years, we made great strides in optimizing our business to put us on a path for long term sustained earnings growth. In addition, look for us to continue streamline our business through the ongoing realignment of our portfolio, further G&A efficiencies, land bank optimization and reduced leverage. 
Now let me turn it over to Tom for further comments.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid. We began the year with terrific results. Core FFO was $0.61 per share for the quarter, an increase of 24% year-over-year and driven by strong operating fundamentals and an increase in AUM. Starting with operations. Occupancy in the U.S. was
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid. We began the year with terrific results. Core FFO was $0.61 per share for the quarter, an increase of 24% year-over-year and driven by strong operating fundamentals and an increase in AUM. Starting with operations. Occupancy in the U.S. was 96.6% at quarter end and 95.4% outside the U.S. Leasing volume for the quarter was a record at 46 million square feet. 
Just a quick reminder that my comments, as I go through the rest of the operating and capital deployment activity, will focus on our share. GAAP rent change on rollover was an all-time high of 20.1%, led by the U.S. at 27.2% and 4% outside the U.S. GAAP same-store NOI increased 7.4%, positive across all major geographies and driven by the U.S. at 9.6%. There are 2 items I want to highlight. 
First, as we previously discussed, the negative impact on GAAP NOI from the amortization of lease intangibles related to the merger burned off in the second quarter of 2015. As a result, this had a positive noncash impact of about 170 basis points on GAAP same-store growth in the quarter. 
Second, expense timing drove an approximate 70 basis points positive impact. After adjusting for these 2 items, GAAP same-store growth was 5%, which is attributable to the strong rental increases and year-over-year occupancy gains. Strategic capital fees were $50 million for the quarter, with a majority coming from our international ventures. Capital deployment activity is progressing as planned. There are 2 items I would like to highlight this quarter. 
First, that our stabilizations had an estimated margin of 27%; and second, that build-to-suits comprised 42% of our development starts. Turning to capital markets. Our leverage on a book basis was 38.1% at quarter end and 33.9% based on market capitalization. Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains, improved to 5.6x. 
As Hamid mentioned, we fully repaid the $400 million term loan associated with the KTR acquisition and liquidity remained strong. Last quarter -- I'm sorry, this week, we recast our Global Line of Credit, lowering our spread by 10 basis points and increasing the capacity by $640 million. As a result, our total line capacity is now $3.4 billion, further enhancing our current significant liquidity levels. We expect to see further improvement in our debt metrics throughout the remainder of the year as our venture rebalancings were completed this month and the pace of dispositions accelerate. 
The continued strengthening of our balance sheet was acknowledged this quarter by both Moody's and Standard & Poor's, upgraded our credit outlook to positive. We believe we are on the doorstep of an A rating. Before discussing guidance, I wanted to highlight the enhancements to our earnings supplemental this quarter. The changes are based on the feedback we received from investors and analysts as well as to better align our disclosure with how we think about and how we run the company. As part of this, we've revisited the classification of certain personnel costs in our income statement, which had the effect of increasing expenses related to our strategic capital business by $17 million on an annual basis and reducing G&A by the same amount. 
There is no bottom line impact on net income or core FFO. For context, we completed a significant volume of co-investment activity over the past 5 years and almost doubled our third-party AUM. With this increase, we now have more full-time employees dedicated to our strategic capital business. 
Moving to 2016 guidance. We're maintaining guidance for most of our operating metrics, capital deployment and strategic capital revenues, all of which you can see on Page 6 of our supplemental. On same-store NOI, we are increasing the bottom end and narrowing the range to between 4% and 4.5%, with a bias towards the upper half of this range. For net G&A, we are lowering the range to between $218 million and $228 million to reflect the reclassification I just mentioned. 
Related to FX. Our 2016 earnings remain well insulated from foreign currency fluctuations as over 95% are hedged. We continue to expect to generate $1 billion of total proceeds in excess of our capital needs in 2016. This consists of $400 million in net deployment proceeds, $198 million of cash that we already received from the completion of the Facebook installment sale and $400 million from the ownership rebalancing in our USLF and PTELF ventures, which we will receive in a few weeks.
Further, we like what we are seeing in the disposition market and are likely to increase our volume. So while operating conditions are stronger than we expected, we are not increasing our core FFO given the potential dilution from increased dispositions. Therefore, we are maintaining our 2016 core FFO guidance between $2.50 and $2.60 per share. This includes $0.17 to $0.19 per share of promotes, which will recognize in the second half of this year. If we assume normalized annual net promotes of $0.05 per share, our core FFO for 2016 would range between $2.38 to $2.46 per share. 
Core FFO will not be evenly distributed for the balance of the year, given the timing of our asset sales and venture rebalancing. As a result, we expect core FFO to be $0.03 or $0.04 lower in the second quarter, followed by an acceleration in the back half of the year from promote income. 
In closing, we are off to a really good start. Our focus for the rest of the 2016 is simply about capturing the significant spreads between in-place and market rents, generating profitable returns by putting our land bank to work and continuing to strengthen our balance sheet. 
With that, I'll turn it over to the operator for questions.

componenttext: Hamid, I guess, I was just wondering if you could talk a little bit about the development business and what you're seeing. Obviously, the fundamentals continue to be stronger than maybe you've expected. I know you didn't have a huge start figure in the first quarter, but I'm just wondering if you sort of look out for the balance of the year, was the risk to the starts number to the upside or to the downside? How do you sort of assess that at this point? And what are your tenants sort of looking for today?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Steve, I think the risk is to the upside because pretty much everything that we're likely to do, we know about. So by definition, if some build-to-suit walks in the door or something happens, it's going to be on the upside, because pretty much everything
componenttext: Steve, I think the risk is to the upside because pretty much everything that we're likely to do, we know about. So by definition, if some build-to-suit walks in the door or something happens, it's going to be on the upside, because pretty much everything is baked. The other thing I would comment on generally, development start volume is that we're basically doing the same or a little bit more than last year except for Brazil. So with obvious reasons, we're not developing a whole lot of new product in Brazil. So I think people have gotten too excited in terms of our guidance being a little bit down on development starts. I don't think you can read that much into that anyway.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Hamid, as we think about demand for industrial space, we spent a lot of time thinking about inventory levels given the historical correlation between absorption and inventories. And then I look at what's been going on with inventory to sales ratios lately
componenttext: Hamid, as we think about demand for industrial space, we spent a lot of time thinking about inventory levels given the historical correlation between absorption and inventories. And then I look at what's been going on with inventory to sales ratios lately, and I say lately, it's been ramping the last couple of years, but over the last year or 2, it's been ramping quite significantly. How do you think inventory to sales ratios are going to play out here going forward? Do you think we're going to see a bit more, I guess, modest inventory growth given what's going on in the economy? And how does that play out in terms of demand for your space?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Ross, that's a very good question. And I think the answer is too soon to know for sure. But it appears that that the secular decline in inventory to sales ratio that all of you are used to see in our materials going back, I don't know, 15 years or somethi
componenttext: Ross, that's a very good question. And I think the answer is too soon to know for sure. But it appears that that the secular decline in inventory to sales ratio that all of you are used to see in our materials going back, I don't know, 15 years or something, really has reversed in the last 3 years. And there are lots of explanations for it. But the most credible one I think is the one that as more sales shift to e-commerce, there are more skews and there's a need to keep more inventory around. And as a result, there may be a secular shift. If that's the case, that's an unexpected windfall to demand for industrial space. We have not built our business with that expectation. But that will be a nice surprise if it happens and if it has legs forever. So too soon to tell for sure, but I think the early signs are really good.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016

componenttext: Your next question comes from Ki Bin Kim from SunTrust.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: So going back to your opening comments, Hamid, you talked about the $3.5 billion of onetime funding sources, and how you're funding your -- you're going to be self-funding for the next 5 years of activity. And that's been a pretty consistent message comin
componenttext: So going back to your opening comments, Hamid, you talked about the $3.5 billion of onetime funding sources, and how you're funding your -- you're going to be self-funding for the next 5 years of activity. And that's been a pretty consistent message coming from you guys lately. But I guess, the equation to issue equity or not issue equity and how to fund that activity is a different equation at $40 versus $45 stock price. Could you just talk about how you think about that as your stock price has changed? Or is it still that $3.5 billion is -- is that still your primary source how you want to fund the business?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Look, I'm not going to sit here and say that we will never do equity if the stock price is at $60 or $70 or something like that. We'd be foolish not to do that because that clearly would be higher than our NAV. But our view of NAV, we've been pretty open
componenttext: Look, I'm not going to sit here and say that we will never do equity if the stock price is at $60 or $70 or something like that. We'd be foolish not to do that because that clearly would be higher than our NAV. But our view of NAV, we've been pretty open about it, is $46, $47 a share, that doesn't really include the value for development business. And I guess, there's a long debate as to whether that business is worth a 1 multiple or a 10 multiple. I can tell you, it's not worth the 15 or 20 multiple that people were valuing it at 2007, that's for sure. But it's worth something. It's worth at least a homebuilder. I think it's worth $3 or $5 a share pretty easily if you look at it as a homebuilder. So you add up all that stuff, the number is around high 40s, low 50s kind of -- for the way I look at our NAV. So I don't even think about it. So I don't think the equation has changed between $40 and $45 because we're still way below where I think the value of the company is. But you got to look at equity in the context of other investment opportunities. If some portfolio comes up on to market or -- I don't think that's going to happen, but if something happens where we have an advantage to buy $45 of NAV at $20, we may take advantage of that. But I don't think that's going to happen. And we're not an issuer of equity. And I think it is a complete waste of time for people to spend energy thinking about that issue at these kinds of numbers.
