headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: You guys have talked about getting your land balance down to about $1 billion or under. Some of that obviously involves monetizing lands through development. But -- it also involves disposing of land. So my question is, have you seen any movement in land
componenttext: You guys have talked about getting your land balance down to about $1 billion or under. Some of that obviously involves monetizing lands through development. But -- it also involves disposing of land. So my question is, have you seen any movement in land values over the past 6 months or so, especially as you and some of your public peers have become a little bit more conservative with respect to the expected starts this year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: I think land values in terms of good developable land that's near term developable has gone up as rents have gone up. And it's very hard to find good land in the right markets. Entitlement costs are going up. Infrastructure costs are going up. Communities
componenttext: I think land values in terms of good developable land that's near term developable has gone up as rents have gone up. And it's very hard to find good land in the right markets. Entitlement costs are going up. Infrastructure costs are going up. Communities are getting tougher on land. So general trend in land values has been up. I would say, among our many, many parcels, every quarter we value our land using a land residual analysis. And I would say by and large, the trends has been up. There are, I would say, 3 or 4 parcels that of a very large number may be down, but the general trend is up. But it's not up as much as it would've been a year ago or 2 years ago. The pace of land value growth has moderated. The other thing I would point out is that, yes, our land bank is about $1.5 billion for book value, but the market value of that, in our view, again, based on pretty robust analysis is approaching $2 billion, maybe in the low $2 billion range. So in terms of what we can work our land bank down is not $0.5 billion down to $1 billion, it's like $1 billion down to $1 billion in terms of market value because the market value land is what we were targeting for. So we've got quite a bit of liquidity that could come out of the land bank to add to that $3.5 billion that we've talked about.

componenttext: Okay, Juan. This is Tom. I'll start. The decline -- the benefit we got from the lower occupancy expenses in Q1 this year was really a function of Q1 of '15 being higher than normal. So if you go back and you look at the increase if Q1 of '15, I think it was around 7%. componenttextpreview: First, just a couple of portfolio-specific questions. Could you comment on the occupancy declines in Houston, in Pennsylvania? And then secondly, perhaps you can touch -- perhaps provide e-commerce update and just if you can relay your experiences with yo
componenttext: First, just a couple of portfolio-specific questions. Could you comment on the occupancy declines in Houston, in Pennsylvania? And then secondly, perhaps you can touch -- perhaps provide e-commerce update and just if you can relay your experiences with your customers in terms of how they accommodate e-commerce growth during the holiday season, whether they see any changes in their supply chain as a result?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Eric, it's Gene, I'll start with that at least. Well, obviously, Houston and Pennsylvania are 2 markets that we've called out as markets we're concerned about. Houston, pretty obvious reasons why. And Pennsylvania is sort of a combination of a spike in su
componenttext: Eric, it's Gene, I'll start with that at least. Well, obviously, Houston and Pennsylvania are 2 markets that we've called out as markets we're concerned about. Houston, pretty obvious reasons why. And Pennsylvania is sort of a combination of a spike in supply and demand tailing off. But I wouldn't draw any conclusions, Eric, about the specific adjustments and vacancy in those markets. I don't think that's going to continue for a long time. I think in both cases, we're going to end up in the sort of mid-90s. But let me say a couple of other things about both of them. So Houston has been on our watch list. Vacancy was up a little bit over the quarter and it has 8 million square feet under construction. We're defensive there and I think we've been saying that for a while. While the macro headwind obviously persists, we're almost 96% leased. The pipe is 50% preleased and there's still a 6% vacancy rate in Houston. And Houston isn't creating a lot of jobs, but it's net positive, not negative, at this point in time. And then in terms of Pennsylvania, probably we're a little more cautious in terms of Pennsylvania at this point in time. To your point on e-commerce trends. Eric, we don't see any new trends coming out of this prior season. I think that everybody participating in this space is still desperately trying to figure out the supply chain both the last mile, which everybody is talking about these days all the way to the origin of the product because different participants handle it differently. So we don't really have anything new for you right now. I don't know, Gary, if you see anything different in your opinion.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: And I'd just say that there are 2 trends that have occurred over the last 2 years, 2 important customer segments. One is automotive and the other is e-commerce. And the e-commerce side of the equation, isn't a seasonal thing. You sort of pose your questio
componenttext: And I'd just say that there are 2 trends that have occurred over the last 2 years, 2 important customer segments. One is automotive and the other is e-commerce. And the e-commerce side of the equation, isn't a seasonal thing. You sort of pose your question in terms of seasonality. It's really a structural change I think in the way companies are doing business today. And if you look at our own portfolio as an example, 2 or 3 years ago, it was about 5% of our total portfolio; today, it's doubled that. So it's clearly an important driver and one that I wouldn't think about just in terms of a seasonal-type trend.

componenttextpreview: Hamid, if we can just turn to the comment you made in the press release and then repeated on the call about sort of trends exceeding underlying economies. Are the economies performing sort of at your expectations and trends are just that much better? Are
componenttext: Hamid, if we can just turn to the comment you made in the press release and then repeated on the call about sort of trends exceeding underlying economies. Are the economies performing sort of at your expectations and trends are just that much better? Are you seeing a slowing and trends are really kind of where you've expected but the economies are not?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Manny, my take on the economies and I'm really out of my depth of expertise here, but seems to me that the U.S. economy is sort of a mid to high 2% grow or minus energy. So that means it's a 1.5% to 2% grower. And so the trends that affect our business, r
componenttext: Manny, my take on the economies and I'm really out of my depth of expertise here, but seems to me that the U.S. economy is sort of a mid to high 2% grow or minus energy. So that means it's a 1.5% to 2% grower. And so the trends that affect our business, remember energy doesn't -- goes through pipelines, it doesn't go through warehouses. The energy pricing generally being lower has led to better consumption numbers. And more of that consumption is shifting to the e-commerce channel, which is more space intensive. So those 2 things have made demand for our product better than they would have been based on the overall economic numbers. On top of that, this issue that I talked about earlier, which is the inventory to sales ratio is turning up, which may be a third factor or you may look at it as part of the second factor, which is e-commerce. I don't know. One of those 2. So there are either 2 or 3 factors that are making the -- our demand drivers for our business better than the underlying economy. That's my take of it. I don't know for sure, but we'll see. But that's what I think is going on.

componenttextpreview: My question has to do with international markets. Obviously, you guys have visibility into international markets more so than a lot of other industrial landlords out there. Just wondering if you could comment on trends and fundamentals in both Europe and
componenttext: My question has to do with international markets. Obviously, you guys have visibility into international markets more so than a lot of other industrial landlords out there. Just wondering if you could comment on trends and fundamentals in both Europe and Asia, and then if you're seeing any movement in cap rates as well.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes. Let's start in Europe. Cap rates are generally flat for the last couple of quarters. Our expectation there though that you can see another 15 to 30 basis points this year. Trends are good. For the first time, we're viewing Europe as a potential tailw
componenttext: Yes. Let's start in Europe. Cap rates are generally flat for the last couple of quarters. Our expectation there though that you can see another 15 to 30 basis points this year. Trends are good. For the first time, we're viewing Europe as a potential tailwind to the company. The outlook, when you're looking at market vacancies as a whole, is that vacancies, not occupancy, vacancies will drop 60 basis points. So we'll be at somewhere around market vacancy is about 5.8%, which is nearing sort of U.S. level, so we expect Europe to perform well on a go-forward basis. And in Asia, the markets there I think are performing well. Japan is sitting there at about 96.3% occupied, and we're seeing good net absorption. So Japan is performing well. China is a business that I think some have concern. It's a small business for us, but one that again is performing pretty well. We're at about 92% occupied in our overall portfolio. But if you look at the supplemental, you'll see that there is a lease to occupied spread of about 200 basis points. So you should expect occupancies in China to trend up. The other comment I'd make about China is that we've done about 2 million square feet of development leasing this quarter, which is about 30% of the total leasing for the quarter for the company. So it's performing pretty well. So net-net, I'd say that international markets are performing to expectation and will become a tailwind.

componenttext: Just a question on leverage levels and uses of cash. There was a modest sequential decline in net debt from the fourth quarter, but it looks like you've already realized over half of that $1 billion you're guiding to, for proceeds for the full year. So I just want to know if there's something else beyond development that we should be thinking about as a substantial use of cash in the quarter? And then also whether we should continue to expect net proceeds deployed to reduce net debt over the remainder of the year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q1 2016 Earnings Call, Apr 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Brad, it's Tom. So I'll take those questions. First, on LTV. You're right, LTV, you would have appeared, didn't decline enough based on our activity for the quarter and what's happening is it's really a function of weakening of the dollar and the strength
componenttext: Brad, it's Tom. So I'll take those questions. First, on LTV. You're right, LTV, you would have appeared, didn't decline enough based on our activity for the quarter and what's happening is it's really a function of weakening of the dollar and the strengthening of the yen and the euro. And there's a denominator effect that I will explain. So when you think about about half of our debts in yen and euro, but only about 25% of our assets are. So when the yen and the euro increase against that liability, that debt, that increase took our debt levels up in U.S. dollar terms by about $300 million. But we didn't have the same $300 million increase in our denominator because only 25% of our assets are in euro and yen. So there's a denominator effect and that impacted leverage by about 70 basis points this quarter. So you really -- economically, we had about 100 basis points decline this quarter, a little over actually. But that's FX noise. On your point about deployment proceeds for the rest of the year and how we're going to use that $1 billion of cash, we're going to look at our debt stack and we're going to determine if there is debt where we can economically or frictionlessly pay that off. We do have a multicurrency term loan that's out there that matures in a couple of years that would fit that bill. We always look at bond maturities to see if there's economically, it makes sense to do that or we'll sit on cash. But I would tell you when you look at our guidance, either the debt that we have to pay off is extremely low-rate debt. So it doesn't have a significant impact on our results for the rest of the year.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our second quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CE
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our second quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and market environment; Gary Anderson, our CEO of Europe and Asia, who will provide an update on our European and U.K. businesses; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance.
Also joining us for today's call are Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly and Diana Scott.
Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings.
Additionally, our second quarter press release and supplemental do contain financial measures such as FFO and EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures. And in accordance to Reg G, we have provided a reconciliation to those measures. With that, I'll turn the call over to Hamid and we'll get started.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. We posted another reported good quarter with positive [indiscernible] at almost 18% while maintaining high occupancies. Our core FFO per share grew 15%. Our capital deployment and monetization activities were abo
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. We posted another reported good quarter with positive [indiscernible] at almost 18% while maintaining high occupancies. Our core FFO per share grew 15%. Our capital deployment and monetization activities were above expectations as we continue to strengthen our balance sheet. In our strategic capital business, we have ample fresh commitment from investors and are well positioned to take advantage of any market opportunities that may present themselves. All in all, the last 6 months have been the best in our company's history. We understand though that some of you are concern about our exposure to Europe generally and to the U.K. specifically. So far, however, the impact of Brexit on our operations has been minimal. Our U.K. customers served mostly domestic consumers and we believe the decision to leave the EU will not materially change the buying habits of 65 million people. We also -- we're also confident in our overall European business. E-commerce and supply chain reconfiguration continue as big drivers of demand for our product. The Class A market is where the action and where our portfolio is focused. Any modest decline in GDP growth with -- in all likelihood be offset by the need to carry slightly higher inventories. In fact, our only concern in Europe is in Poland where a few merchant developers are overbuilding the market by offering rental and of up to 40% and commencing new investors to capitalize artificially inflated headline rents. We don't see this anywhere else in Europe. Surely, there'll be more mixed news coming out of Europe and that will lead to continued market volatility. Whether it's bank failures or constitutional reforms in Italy, or elections in France and The Netherlands, we expect policymakers to keep global interest rates lower for longer. In time, this will translate into support for lower cap rate across Europe. We're confident in the resilience of the logistics real estate business, but we remain vigilant and on the lookout for any signs of trouble. 
Before we turn the call to Tom, Gary Anderson, our CEO of Europe and Asia, will share some underground facts from our business in Europe. You'll hear from him in a moment. 
Elsewhere around the globe, market conditions remain strong and steady. Overall, the supply and demand increase in great shape, with all-time low vacancy rates. Demand is driven by steady growth and consumption, e-commerce and supply chain monetization. In the U.S., rents are up again sharply and we expect absorption will again exceed new supply for the year. In Japan, new supply from development is being absorbed and cap rates continue to compress while occupancy and rents are up in China. Even in our softness market in Brazil, where are 100% leased, but rents there are down about 10% from the peak. Looking across our markets, we only see a few locations of excess supply, specifically Houston, Columbus and as I mentioned earlier, parts of Poland. In these lower markets, private developers and their institutional capital partners are delivering more products than the market can absorb. Other than these few exceptions, our markets are in very good shape. In conclusion, we worked hard to position our company for success and are excited about the prospects for the coming years. Let me now to turn the call over to Gary.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid, and good morning. The European market perform very well in the first half of 2016 with demand outpacing supply. Market vacancy in Europe is currently 6%, down 60 basis points year-over-year and is currently projected to end the year at 5.8%
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid, and good morning. The European market perform very well in the first half of 2016 with demand outpacing supply. Market vacancy in Europe is currently 6%, down 60 basis points year-over-year and is currently projected to end the year at 5.8%. The Prologis portfolio outperformed the market and delivered some of our strongest results on record. Occupancy in our European portfolio is 95.6%, up 130 basis points year-over-year and 70 basis points quarter-over-quarter. The U.K. led all regions at 98.8% occupied and today, the 22.4 million-square-foot operating pool [ph] in the U.K. is 100% leased. Rent change on roll for the quarter totaled 5.1% in Europe with all regions delivering positive results and was led by the U.K. at 17.6%. I'd like to turn now to our activity post-Brexit and present simply the facts as we see them on the ground from June 23, the date of the vote, through today. Let's begin with leasing. We've completed 56 transactions in Europe totaling just under 4.9 million square feet with 8% positive rent change. The U.K. portion is 1.3 million square feet with 24% rent change during that same post-Brexit period. Demand in Europe still appears to be broad-based and continues to have an emphasis on the automotive and e-commerce sectors. We've completed leases post-Brexit, with many names you'll know including DHL, Schneider Electric, Jaguar, Land Rover, Marks & Spencer, and Ali Baba. Risk associated with our U.K. NOI has been minimized. Today, the U.K. portfolio is 100% leased, has a weighted average lease term of 8 years, has only 11% of leases expiring over the next 18 months and has in-place rates that are roughly 10% below market. Let's now turn to Europe development activity. We've had a very prudent approach to development in Europe with a heavy emphasis on build-to-suits. Today, we have a 6.2 million square foot development portfolio in Europe, which is 60% leased and is approximately 1,000 basis points ahead of our underwriting. The U.K. portion of our development portfolio totals 1.9 million square feet and is 850 basis points ahead of our underwriting. We also expect to execute 2 leases totaling about 570,000 square feet imminently and have good activity on the balance of our U.K. developments. The only exception is a 317,000 square-foot building in London Gateway where there has been little activity even before Brexit. Turning to capital markets and building sales. We sold a 3 billion [ph] portfolio in the U.K. during the second quarter and that transaction closed as planned on June 21, 2 days before the referendum vote. We also began negotiating the sale of EUR 100 million plus French portfolio pre-Brexit and concluded discussions on Friday of last week with no change to our pricing. The buyers are now under contract with a 10% nonrefundable deposit. There's also been some non-Prologis activity to report in the U.K. that underscore solid pricing for logistics assets. 103,000 square-foot building leased to DHL in Birmingham with a 10-year term closed on July 1, at a 4.8% stabilized cap rate and another 176,000 square-foot building let to Amazon for 10 years in Manchester is expected to close at about the same level in the next few days. In addition, our U.K. retail fund has about GBP 50 million of British Telecom logistics deal to market and as buyers transact in just 5 working days. There are reportedly more than 10 bidders at about a 5% stabilize cap rate, probably 15 to 20 basis points higher than we would normally expect but a very small discount when you consider the timescale and lack of due diligence. Beyond that, we're hearing rumors that certain retail funds may bring assets the market to create liquidity and we will monitor those for opportunity. In general, values in the U.K. are driven by lease length and location, so you shouldn't expect to see any meaningful value change in the Prologis U.K. portfolio given our current lease length location and interest rates that are widely believed to be going lower for longer. 
Lastly, let's turn to our funds. Values are up 70 basis points this quarter in our European fronts and incremental leasing and cap rate compression on the continent, but any of these of are flat to slightly down given the negative impact of lower interest rates on debt mark-to-market and FX. While we don't expect to see significant investment activity during the summer months and as a result, we don't expect to see much change in fund values, here is what we can tell you as of today. Our open-end fund has a EUR 400 million equity [indiscernible], its largest ever. We have closed 70 million in new equity commitments in PTELF as planned on June 30, again, post-Brexit from a Swiss capital source. Our open funds in Europe are approximately 30% levered and our JVs are 0% levered, so we have plenty of capital to take advantage of the right opportunity should they arise. On June 30, we had 1 secondary trade occur in our PELP 2 vehicle. It was a EUR 16 million trade at par between a fund that was expiring and an existing PELP 2 investor. The at par trade validates our current fund valuations. To date, we have had no formal redemption requests but have heard some noise about 2 Sterling investors with investment totaling about EUR 45 million that may pursue secondary trades. So let me quickly summarize. Leasing volume and rents appears to be holding -- appeared to be holding up well. On the development front, we are significantly ahead of our underwritten lease-up, new supply is generally in check and we expect to maintain a high build-to-suit percentage this year. While we can't speak to U.K. office or retail, which have their issues, high-quality logistic assets appear to be trading at valuation. And with respect to Prologis we are in great shape with record Qs and capacity to take advantage of any opportunities that present themselves. With that, let me turn it over to Tom to take us through the rest of the quarter.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Gary. For the second quarter, we generated core FFO of $0.60 per share, exceeding our forecast due to better-than expected real estate operations and higher asset management fees. Global occupancy was 96.1% for the quarter, up 70 basis points year
componenttext:
Thanks, Gary. For the second quarter, we generated core FFO of $0.60 per share, exceeding our forecast due to better-than expected real estate operations and higher asset management fees. Global occupancy was 96.1% for the quarter, up 70 basis points year-over-year. We set another quarterly leasing record at 49 million square feet, including more than 9 million square feet of development leasing. Our share of net effective rent change on rollover was [ph] 17.8%, led by the U.S. of 23.5%. Our share of same-store NOI increased 6.1% with the U.S. leading the way at 7.5%. This is the last quarter that will be impacted by the burn-off of merger lease intangible amortization. Excluding this impact, our share same-store NOI growth for the quarter would have been 5%. For the first half of 2016, development stabilizations were $1.1 billion with an estimated weighted average margin of over 26%. Development starts totaled $658 million with an estimated weighted average margin of over 18%. Build-to-suits comprised almost half of our year-to-date starts. Dispositions and contributions totaled $1.2 billion. In terms of total capital proceeds, we've already closed or have under hard contract about 70% of our original full year guidance. 
Turning to capital markets, our leverage at quarter end was 37% on a book basis and 30.6% based on market capitalization. Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains, was 5.6x. Our liquidity, which we defined as our undrawn line capacity and available consolidated cash, reached the highest level in our history this quarter. Turning to guidance now for 2016. I'll just cover the material changes so for compete detail, refer to Page 5 of our supplemental. Due to stronger operating fundamentals, we're increasing our share same-store NOI range to between 4.75% and 5.25%. In light of our progress year-to-date and investor interest, we're increasing our share of disposition and contribution volume to between $2.3 billion and $2.8 billion, an increase of $300 million at the midpoint. We will complete an additional ownership rebalancing in our USLF and PTELF ventures for a total of $200 million. This is on top of the $400 million we completed earlier this year. We're also raising the midpoint of our share development starts by $200 million for a range of $1.7 billion $2 billion. We expect our full year build-to-suit percentage to be higher than the 44% we did last year. The net results of our deployment changes is that we now expect to generate $1.3 billion of total proceeds in excess of our capital needs, up $300 million from prior guidance. We will use a portion of the net proceeds to retire debt, with a balance further building up our cash reserves. We expect to end the year with liquidity at about $4 billion and booked leverage below 35%. Related to FX, our 2016 and 2017 estimated quarter earnings are fully hedged relative to the U.S. dollar and we have already hedged about half of 2018. 
Putting this all together, our 2016 core FFO, excluding promotes, is higher by $0.03 cents due to better than forecasted operations and fees partially offset by the dilution from an increase and acceleration of the dispositions, contributions and fund rebalancing. In other words, core earnings are higher while at the same time significantly increasing our cash reserves. We expect 2016 core FFO, including promotes, to range between $2.52 and $2.58 per share maintaining our $2.55 midpoint. Our promote range is now $0.14 to $0.16 a share, down $0.03 at the midpoint. The decline in the promotes is primarily due to negative debt mark-to-market and FX movements where the pound weakening against the euro. The promote midpoint assumes that asset values remain unchanged with June 30 appraisals and FX rates remain at current levels. To be clear, asset values in Europe have not declined. In fact the appraised if our assets European ventures increased 70 basis points in the second quarter led by the U.K. at 100 basis points. To wrap up, we expect continued strong NOI growth as we harvest the GAAP between in-place and market rents. We're maintaining strong double-digit core FFO growth in 2016 while at the same time further strengthening our balance sheet and building liquidity. Our financial position has never been stronger and we'll continue to improve by year-end as we generate additional proceeds from net deployment. With that, I'll turn it over to the operator for your questions.

componenttextpreview: Just question about the development starts. We saw a change or a shift in the U.S. side of the composition of the starts Q-over-Q and that's sort of expected may be seasonality-related. But we also saw an increase in building in China, as far as the rest
componenttext: Just question about the development starts. We saw a change or a shift in the U.S. side of the composition of the starts Q-over-Q and that's sort of expected may be seasonality-related. But we also saw an increase in building in China, as far as the rest of the world is concerned. Can you comment on whether this is a response to lower spec starts, particularly in the U.K. and in the EU in general? And as a follow-up to China, I guess, what should we expect? Should we expect the continued shift towards Asia going forward given that the opportunities in one of the strongest U.K. markets are limited?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Let me take it, it's Gary. First of all, we don't try to adjust 1 place to the other 1 geography to the other, we simply take what's given. If there's a good opportunity to develop at a reasonable margin, we'll take it. With respect to China specifically,
componenttext: Let me take it, it's Gary. First of all, we don't try to adjust 1 place to the other 1 geography to the other, we simply take what's given. If there's a good opportunity to develop at a reasonable margin, we'll take it. With respect to China specifically, we're building a business there really in the 4 key markets. And we see acceleration in our business on the development side because that is a development business there coming in China. So we perhaps should have signaled that we would have seen increasing development starts. It has been building candidly over the last several years. And I would expect it to continue to build in China to a point. But again, our focus is going to be only on 4 key markets in China and we'll take what the market gives us.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: This is related to, I guess, the Brexit campaign. So global trade is significantly so in the last several years and there's a lot more protection retort coming out off politics. My question, do you have any thoughts on how this global trade flow down, whe
componenttext: This is related to, I guess, the Brexit campaign. So global trade is significantly so in the last several years and there's a lot more protection retort coming out off politics. My question, do you have any thoughts on how this global trade flow down, whether it's through politics or naturally? How about in warehouse demand for your portfolio over time and have your customers discuss or make contingency plans in regards to some of these events?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, global trade, which used to run at the about 3X the sum of domestic GDP has slowed down to about 1.2, 1.3x the size of the pace of global domestic GDP. It's still going faster, but as global trade represents the larger and larger percentage of domest
componenttext: Yes, global trade, which used to run at the about 3X the sum of domestic GDP has slowed down to about 1.2, 1.3x the size of the pace of global domestic GDP. It's still going faster, but as global trade represents the larger and larger percentage of domestic GDP, the math just drives you there. Because when global trade was only 2% of the total GDP, it has a lot of opportunity to grow, but once it's reached the saturation level, it's tough to have it grow at the same levels. So part of it is just math and nothing else. Part of it has to do with definitely protectionism and also some exchange rate consideration that affect that patterns of global trade. If a global trade is curtailed, which we don't think it's going to be the case, we think around every election, there's a lot of talk protection event. But people know that the people that want protectionism are the very people that actually get hurt by it in the long term. We think notwithstanding the talk around the election season is going to be very little. In fact, we think that CPP is going to go forward and maybe great opportunities in the other direction. So but let's assume for a moment that we're all wrong and depositions will get in the way of global trading. Well, you just have to carry more inventory because you're not sourcing from as many places. The big driver is -- the big drivers of demand though are consumption, fueled by e-commerce and reconfiguration of the supply chain. Those are the real biggies now that global trade has reached the saturation point.

And then separately, just we've talked in the past about may be cap rate compression stabilizing in Europe and it sounds like now post-Brexit, that may not necessarily be the case in just your views of when rent growth start to materialize in there in a significant manner?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: So Greg, it's Gene. I will start with the U.S. and I'm sure Gary will comment on what's happening with Europe. But we basically, continue to get more bullish as we get each quarter behind us and we're surprised to the upside on what the fundamentals look
componenttext: So Greg, it's Gene. I will start with the U.S. and I'm sure Gary will comment on what's happening with Europe. But we basically, continue to get more bullish as we get each quarter behind us and we're surprised to the upside on what the fundamentals look like in the U.S. and I would include Mexico in that at this point as well. So I think we're probably talking about a 5 or something next year and I think we're going to do better than that. And as I said on the last call, I think equilibrium in the U.S. markets is probably sometime in '17. And again, I'd remind you, when we reach equilibrium will be an all time low, vacancy rates and you still have plenty of room to push rents. So I'm probably slightly more bullish than I have been in the past in the U.S.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Let me add something to that. I mean we can spectate what market rental growth will be, but the mark-to-market the leases right now, as we said, with no further rental growth will be 15%. And if you just assume no further growth from here and you realized
componenttext: Let me add something to that. I mean we can spectate what market rental growth will be, but the mark-to-market the leases right now, as we said, with no further rental growth will be 15%. And if you just assume no further growth from here and you realized that over the next 4 years, the 15% mark-to-market, that gets you pretty close to 4% same-store growth with 0 additional rental growth. So it's not as if it takes a lot of imagination to get to strong same-store growth numbers in the U.S, the mark-to-market is the driver. Gary?

componenttext: Just on cap rates. The 4 Brexit we were projecting sort of 15 to 20 -- 15 to 30 basis points over the next 12 months on the continent relatively flat in the U.K. But look, I mean, the ECB and the Bank of England are under a lot of pressure. It's why we believe that interest rates are going to go lower. So obviously, that has downward implications potentially on cap rates.

I guess, at this point, would you be more inclined to increase your investments in Europe and specifically in the U.K.? Or decrease it at this point?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: We're not looking to decrease -- first of all, we didn't hear the first part of your question, but I think based on the last part, I can just [indiscernible]. Look, our business is just a real estate business and we're not a hedge fund. We don't make deci
componenttext: We're not looking to decrease -- first of all, we didn't hear the first part of your question, but I think based on the last part, I can just [indiscernible]. Look, our business is just a real estate business and we're not a hedge fund. We don't make decisions minute by minute. This is a long-term business. We got a good allocation, appropriate allocation to Europe. A lot of the stuff is based on long-term prospects for economic growth -- economic and population growth. If basically, we are invested the way we are across the world for a reason. Over time, the only portfolio shift that we imagine has nothing to do with Brexit. We probably want to be a little heavier in Asia and a little lighter in Europe, but fundamentally on our allocations, regardless of Brexit, are where we want them to be. So the big dial that we use in terms of managing our own allocation is our share of our private capital vehicles. That's really the way we managed the business from our capital exposure. We like our scale in Europe because we're dominant player there and have the best portfolio. And we really like that market position and what it means in terms of what we can do with customers. So a long-winded answer of saying that we like our hand, we like our position in the U.K, we're willing to -- we think that the U.K.'s going to continue to best market in Europe actually in the next 10 years. And you might think in the short term, but the long-term dynamics are quite interesting. So we're good where we are. Now, if opportunities arise and people start doing stupid things, we would be delighted to take advantage of those things. I don't think it will happen, I think by and large, European real estate is in strong institutional hands. There's not a lot of leverage in the system, notwithstanding the headlines that you hear about some of these funds. And there may be pressure, by the way, on financial center type office buildings in the U.K. But in our product type, we think there are more buyers than sellers of the quality product that we have. So we don't think of those distressed opportunities are going to materialize, but if they do, we're prepared to take advantage of that.

componenttextpreview: One trade part question. Someone told me a while ago that dividends now matter and we noticed that you increase your net income, net earnings as range to a 170 to 190. Talk about why that does for your dividend. Second part of the question is, are you thi
componenttext: One trade part question. Someone told me a while ago that dividends now matter and we noticed that you increase your net income, net earnings as range to a 170 to 190. Talk about why that does for your dividend. Second part of the question is, are you thinking about any other markets globally given that you've got an abundance of cash? And the third, can you talk a little bit about land prices in a tighter industrial markets and how that's affecting replacement cost rents?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: John, I think that the first one on dividends. Yes, we did see an increase in our EPS this quarter. It was a combination of 2 things, one just higher realized development gains and also just higher disposition activity, what we would call nondevelopment g
componenttext: John, I think that the first one on dividends. Yes, we did see an increase in our EPS this quarter. It was a combination of 2 things, one just higher realized development gains and also just higher disposition activity, what we would call nondevelopment gains, and non-FFO gains of operating profit just increasing our disposition activity, that's what's driving that. No change in our dividend. We're happy with where our payout ratio is, our payout ratio right now. Based on our AFFO, is about 68%. We're comfortable with where that is and we've obviously had extreme dividend growth over the last several years. But we see the dividend holding where it is this year.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Hey, John, the dividend has been up 50% over the last, I think, 2 years and change [ph] years from about 12 to about 68. I would be surprised if the dividend rate doesn't grow by multiples of inflation going forward. I think -- we think our growth is goin
componenttext: Hey, John, the dividend has been up 50% over the last, I think, 2 years and change [ph] years from about 12 to about 68. I would be surprised if the dividend rate doesn't grow by multiples of inflation going forward. I think -- we think our growth is going to be pretty strong and we've got good leverage coming through G&A, which is not going near, we -- it's actually flat compared to our operating earnings. So I think we've got good leverage to grow our dividend above industry rates, pretty clear about that. We are not planning to go to any new markets. In fact, we're in the process of completing our strategic plan vision 2020. And in it, it doesn't contemplate going into any new markets. It's totally based on deepening our presence in the markets we're already in. And with respect to land and replacement cost, I think land in the U.S. has appreciated quite a bit. And I think the constraints on land and entitlements are significant. And we'll continue to put pressure on some of the most desirable markets in the U.S. like California, and Pacific Northwest and Miami and the like. The markets spend are supply-constrained, I think, there's very little land and very tough to get it to entitled. So I think replacement costs, rent numbers are going up and up in the U.S. I think the land prices have recovered in Europe, but we don't see them zooming ahead because the rents are still relatively slow growing in Europe. They're growing, but they're slow-growing than the U.S. So then as recovered but it's not zooming ahead. In the U.S., land is pretty expensive.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: The only other thing I would add is Asia. It's probably one of more interesting markets with respect to land. Somebody asked the question earlier about our development volumes in China and, obviously, they're increasing. But each incremental piece of land
componenttext: The only other thing I would add is Asia. It's probably one of more interesting markets with respect to land. Somebody asked the question earlier about our development volumes in China and, obviously, they're increasing. But each incremental piece of land that we buy in China, even if it's phase 2, is incrementally more expensive than the land that we acquired right next-door. And as a result, you're seeing market rent growth there continuing at 4% to 5% range depending on what submarket you're talking about. And in Japan, probably the most expressive land market in the world, and the other thing that's impacting the replacement costs rents are construction costs. And our team expect that the back half of this year are going to start seeing construction cost rise again as we approach the 2020 Olympics and construction resources become scarce. So I think Asia is a pretty interesting place with respect to the land market.

componenttext: I wanted to take a minute to kind of focused on the smaller unit size portion of your portfolio, roughly 1/3 of your portfolio is 100 -- under 100,000 square feet, and that also represents the lowest occupancy of the portfolio at around 94%. Just wondering if you could provide any update on what you're seeing in terms of tenant health in that segment and trends broadly both in the U.S. and Europe?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Tom, it's Gene. I'll talk about the U.S. So this segment, as you know, if you followed us over the last several years has really recovered. I think we have a high rate for occupancy under 100,000 square feet coming out of our merger. And now that's 94%, s
componenttext: Tom, it's Gene. I'll talk about the U.S. So this segment, as you know, if you followed us over the last several years has really recovered. I think we have a high rate for occupancy under 100,000 square feet coming out of our merger. And now that's 94%, sort of 95% in that range. And you're probably not going to see those size increments move a heck lot higher because you have many more spaces, you have a naturally, shorter lease terms and more role. And I'd say that's pretty full. In fact, historically, we could take a look at this. I'm not sure that segment where it gets much higher than that. But having said that, the demand is good, you're going to see us bounce around quarter-to-quarter, but demand is going from those tenants. And probably this single most important customer segments is home building. And that really hasn't returned. If it does, perhaps it pushes a little bit more but we're not concerned about it in terms of where we're at. We're probably sort of topped out. And Gary?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, with respect to Europe. This is a place that we've see -- the thing that we talked about in past calls definitely an opportunity for us make progress in Europe. We're currently across the whole of Europe, about 91% occupied in small spaces. And again
componenttext: Yes, with respect to Europe. This is a place that we've see -- the thing that we talked about in past calls definitely an opportunity for us make progress in Europe. We're currently across the whole of Europe, about 91% occupied in small spaces. And again, we look at that in terms of small business formation and the pace that we've like the most is in Southern Europe where candidly you had the least amount of small business formation. But we have been focused on that segment even in Southern Europe and if you look, we have probably gained 1,200 or 1,400 basis points over the last year in our Southern European portfolio. So this is an area of focus and one where we think opportunities lie certainly in Europe.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: This is Tom. I would just add that I think the segment has the most NOI upside. It's the last to recover, spaces are generally the most they have the highest rates per square foot. And I think now that you're seeing, as Gene said, the space stabilizing, I
componenttext: This is Tom. I would just add that I think the segment has the most NOI upside. It's the last to recover, spaces are generally the most they have the highest rates per square foot. And I think now that you're seeing, as Gene said, the space stabilizing, I think that's going to allow us to push rents. It's got a lot more to catch up so I think a lot of NOI tailwind from this segment, as well as just Gene talked about, home building really not driving that but, clearly, e-commerce is moving into that space and will be a big driver. And again I think that's just more NOI upside for us.

componenttext: If we just go back to sort of your answer on comment earlier on equity, what would make you be more open to issuing equity? What would be the type of deal? What would be the pricing? If -- let's just think out loud for a second. And if you were to do some KTR today, versus when you got that completed, would there be an equity component now with your stock sort of where it is? Or are you against equity for other reasons?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: It's not a religious belief. I believe in equity when there's a good use for capital deployment and -- so it's not, a lot of people thought that we needed equity for balance sheet purposes to achieve our A rating. And unfortunately they are wrong. And I d
componenttext: It's not a religious belief. I believe in equity when there's a good use for capital deployment and -- so it's not, a lot of people thought that we needed equity for balance sheet purposes to achieve our A rating. And unfortunately they are wrong. And I do know we were very clear that we didn't. And we have liquidity from journal sources, rebalancing none strategic asset sales and the like. To fund our business going forward, our development business going forward for 5, 6, 7 years on a normal steady-state scenario. The only thing that's not in that plan is an opportunistic long, large acquisition and that, if we run into those and we do -- we're going to hibernation for a couple of years and once in a while we go out and do something big and then go back in hibernation. We don't have a capital plan that's contemplates that and those types of this but if there are 2 materialize, that's when we would take a look at equity along with other sources. But I can tell you we got a lot of liquidity right now between lines totaling $3.5 billion and the cash that will build up to about $1 billion in the balance sheet. I mean, we got over $4 billion of liquidity. So -- and we like our currency. I mean, I think yes, we are finally trading at the NAV of our underlying real estate. But still the market isn't paying us for development platform, which creates $400 million to $500 million NAV by clockwork every year. So long-winded answer but equity is not the first place we would look to fund even strategic transaction. There are other places we can go to do that, including private capital and our liquidity resources.

componenttext: Most of my questions have been asked. I guess, Hamid, just kind of big picture, I mean, everything seems to be going very well in the business and you guys are even more optimistic today than may be you are 6 months ago. I guess, what are the potential storm clouds that you're watching that would cause you to undertake development starts down or to get more cautious on the rent growth or NOI growth over the next 8, 12 to 24 months?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Steve, I think it's things outside the real estate market. I mean, we are living in a pretty difficult geopolitical environment and there are some domestic issues going are that are concerning that could have slow to the economy. So those kinds of things
componenttext: Steve, I think it's things outside the real estate market. I mean, we are living in a pretty difficult geopolitical environment and there are some domestic issues going are that are concerning that could have slow to the economy. So those kinds of things argued we're having a prudent capital structure so that we can go through in a scenario and maybe even capitalize in some other opportunities that come up in those kinds of scenarios, which is not the position we're in, in the last cycle. So we have learned our lessons and I think we're adequately prepared for those types of situations. But I don't really see anything on the real estate markets that concern me. Remember, demand was never and still is not spectacular. I think demand on the 10-point scale is a 6. I just think supplies kind of 4 to 5. And that's what's been keeping the market healthy. So it's really the other stuff, the geopolitical and domestic political issues and all of the stuff that we read about on the news and watch on TV, very concerned about those.

componenttext: One way to think about the -- kind of risking a development program is if you take all your vacant development, no matter what condition it's in, what percentage of your overall portfolio development and operating, what does that represent? And over the last couple of years, when we've really sort of ramp our development up, we've been between 4% and 5%. And as of this quarter, 3.5%. So we're -- I think fairly derisk on that front. And then if you look at it starts in the U.S. for example, and this gets to the customer dialogue, we're 89% pre-leased on the starts this quarter because we had effectively 6 build-to-suits and pre-leased deals. And that's a result of lots and lots of customer dialogue that's taking place over a couple of years at this point. But most of our customers, today their focus how do they plan for the future. Most of them are in the midst of the supply chain reconfiguration of some type. And the markets are so tight. They have to plan, the have to engage those long-term planning. And so I think actually that the nature of that dialogue is shifted dramatically. It hasn't shifted just in the last quarter, it's taking some weird of time. That's why you see lease terms are significantly longer than they were a couple of years ago. And we'd like to think of these discussions are strategic versus transactional. So I think that actually is a pretty significant change we've seen.

componenttext: The only thing I would ask to that is that I've been doing this for over 30 years and I have never seen an environment where customers have been as willing to share with us their future plans for growth and asking us to build more product. I mean, literally, they're asking us to build more spec product and they are coming ahead and telling us where their needs are. And they used to play their cards pretty close to best. Now part of this may be strategic level dialogue that we've created with them I mean, would some of these customers we have 30, 40, 50, 60 leases. You can engage in meaningful dialogue when you have that kind of customer connectivity. Whether if you have random portfolio or may be customers sprinkled in 3 locations, they think all of you more as a vendor than a partner. So I think the business is finally getting to the scale. Not only because of its size, but also because of its focus on the key markets that the dialogue is becoming more and more strategic and that's what we work very hard to create. So we're very encouraged by that. And look to take advantage of it. It manifest itself in very high volumes of build-to-suits, not because we want it to be that way, but because it turns out that way that people want to lock up spec capacity ahead of time. So a lot of these are spec-to-suit or buildings we're going to build anyway that get leased up on a build-to-suit basis before we start, we're minor modifications. It's a good place to be.

componenttext: So Michael, you remember this because you were there and actually asked some good questions then. Back in 2012, when we laid out at that crazy scenario that of 25% rental growth in the U.S., we have blown through that. And remember there was another phase after that, which is where would market trends go when replacement costs recovered, when construction cost recovered, working for nothing then and when can cost recovered. That's whole another acceleration of replacement cost, which is really pushing rent to go back to that time more like 35% from that time. So we've been surprised by that last [ph] 10%, we thought we are bringing pretty aggressive youth that guys thought all of you we were crazy the market does turn out to be much more -- we were all very conservative in retrospect and the market blown past that because the replacement cost blown past that. And we should be really surprised because nominal rent today are only a few percent higher than what they were in 2000. We had a dry period of 10 to 15 years of very little nominal rental growth and now we're finally getting back to nominal rents that we got in the early 2000. On a real basis, we're still 35% below where we should be. I'm not saying we're going to have 35% more rental growth, don't get me wrong, but I'm just saying nominally, where we were 15 years ago we shouldn't be surprised. But I think when you were in that were all-in the depths of 2012, none of us had enough vision to project 35%, 40% rental growth but that's what's happening.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our second quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com, under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and C
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our second quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com, under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and market environment; Gary Anderson, our CEO of Europe and Asia, who will provide an update on our European and U.K. businesses; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance.
Also joining us for today's call are Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly and Diana Scott.
Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings.
Additionally, our second quarter results press release and supplemental do contain financial measures such as FFO and EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures. And in accordance to Reg G, we have provided a reconciliation to those measures. 
With that, I'll turn the call over to Hamid and we'll get started.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. We posted another great quarter with positive rent change at almost 18% while maintaining high occupancies. Our core FFO per share grew 15%. Our capital deployment and monetization activities were above expectati
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. We posted another great quarter with positive rent change at almost 18% while maintaining high occupancies. Our core FFO per share grew 15%. Our capital deployment and monetization activities were above expectations as we continue to strengthen our balance sheet. In our strategic capital business, we have ample fresh commitment from investors and are well positioned to take advantage of any market opportunities that may present themselves. 
All in all, the last 6 months have been the best in our company's history. We understand, though, that some of you are concern about our exposure to Europe generally and to the U.K., specifically. So far, however, the impact of Brexit on our operations has been minimal. Our U.K. customers served mostly domestic consumers, and we believe the decision to leave the EU will not materially change the buying habits of 65 million people. We're also confident in our overall European business. E-commerce and supply chain reconfiguration continue as big drivers of demand for our product. The Class A market is where the action is and where our portfolio is focused. Any modest decline in GDP growth with -- in all likelihood, be offset by the need to carry slightly higher inventories. In fact, our only concern in Europe is in Poland, where a few merchant developers are overbuilding the market by offering rental incentives of up to 40% and commencing new investors to capitalize artificially inflated headline rents. We don't see this anywhere else in Europe. Surely, there'll be more mixed news coming out of Europe and that will lead to continued market volatility. 
Whether it's bank failures or constitutional reforms in Italy, or elections in France and The Netherlands, we expect policymakers to keep global interest rates lower for longer. In time, this will translate into support for lower cap rate across Europe. We're confident in the resilience of the logistics real estate business, but we remain vigilant and on the lookout for any signs of trouble. 
Before we turn the call to Tom, Gary Anderson, our CEO of Europe and Asia, will share some underground facts from our business in Europe. You'll hear from him in a moment. 
Elsewhere around the globe, market conditions remain strong and steady. Overall, the supply and demand proves in great shape, with all-time low vacancy rates. Demand is driven by steady growth and consumption, e-commerce and supply chain monetization. 
In the U.S., rents are up again sharply, and we expect net absorption will again exceed new supply for the year. In Japan, new supply from development is being absorbed, and cap rates continue to compress while occupancy and rents are up in China. Even in our softness market, Brazil were 100% leased, but rents there are down about 10% from the peak. 
Looking across our markets, we only see a few locations of excess supply, specifically Houston, Columbus, and I -- as I mentioned earlier, parts of Poland. In these lower-barrier markets, private developers and their institutional capital partners are delivering more products than the market can absorb. Other than these few exceptions, our markets are in very good shape. 
In conclusion, we've worked hard to position our company for success and are excited about the prospects for the coming years. Let me now to turn the call over to Gary.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid, and good morning. The European market performed very well in the first half of 2016 with demand outpacing supply. Market vacancy in Europe is currently 6%, down 60 basis points year-over-year and is currently projected to end the year at 5.
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid, and good morning. The European market performed very well in the first half of 2016 with demand outpacing supply. Market vacancy in Europe is currently 6%, down 60 basis points year-over-year and is currently projected to end the year at 5.8%. The Prologis portfolio outperformed the market and delivered some of our strongest results on record. Occupancy in our European portfolio is 95.6%, up 130 basis points year-over-year and 70 basis points quarter-over-quarter. The U.K. led all regions at 98.8% occupied and today, the 22.4 million-square-foot operating pool in the U.K. is 100% leased. 
Rent change on roll for the quarter totaled 5.1% in Europe with all regions delivering positive results and was led by the U.K. at 17.6%. 
I'd like to turn now to our activity post-Brexit and present simply the facts as we see them on the ground from June 23, the date of the vote, through today. 
Let's begin with leasing. We've completed 56 transactions in Europe totaling just under 4.9 million square feet with 8% positive rent change. The U.K. portion is 1.3 million square feet with 24% rent change during that same post-Brexit period. Demand in Europe still appears to be broad-based and continues to have an emphasis on the automotive and e-commerce sectors. We've completed leases post-Brexit, with many names you'll know, including DHL, Schneider Electric, Jaguar Land Rover, Marks & Spencer and Alibaba. 
Risk associated with our U.K. NOI has been minimized. Today, the U.K. portfolio is 100% leased, has a weighted average lease term of 8 years, has only 11% of leases expiring over the next 18 months and has in-place rents that are roughly 10% below market. 
Let's now turn to Europe development activity. We've had a very prudent approach to development in Europe with a heavy emphasis on build-to-suit. Today, we have a 6.2 million-square-foot development portfolio in Europe, which is 60% leased and is approximately 1,000 basis points ahead of our underwriting. The U.K. portion of our development portfolio totals 1.9 million square feet and is 850 basis points ahead of our underwriting. We also expect to execute 2 leases totaling about 570,000 square feet imminently and have good activity on the balance of our U.K. developments. The only exception is a 317,000 square-foot building in London Gateway, where there has been little activity even before Brexit. 
Turning to capital markets and building sales. We sold a 3-building portfolio in the U.K. during the second quarter, and that transaction closed as planned on June 21, 2 days before the referendum vote. We also began negotiating the sale of EUR 100 million-plus French portfolio pre-Brexit and concluded discussions on Friday of last week with no change to our pricing. The buyers are now under contract with a 10% nonrefundable deposit. 
There has also been some non-Prologis activity to report in the U.K. that underscore solid pricing for logistics assets. 103,000 square-foot building leased to DHL in Birmingham with a 10-year term closed on July 1, at a 4.8% stabilized cap rate, and another 176,000 square-foot building let to Amazon for 10 years in Manchester is expected to close at about the same level in the next few days. 
In addition, our U.K. retail fund has brought a GBP 50 million British Telecom logistics deal to market, and as [indiscernible] buyers transact in just 5 working days. There are reportedly more than 10 bidders at about a 5% stabilize cap rate, probably 15 to 20 basis points higher than we would normally expect but a very small discount when you consider the timescale and lack of due diligence. Beyond that, we're hearing rumors that certain retail funds may bring assets to market to create liquidity, and we will monitor those for opportunity. 
In general, values in the U.K. are driven by lease length and location, so you shouldn't expect to see any meaningful value change in the Prologis U.K. portfolio given our current lease length location and interest rates that are widely believed to be going lower for longer. 
Lastly, let's turn to our funds. Values are up 70 basis points this quarter in our European funds on incremental leasing and cap rate compression on the continent, but any of these are flat to slightly down given the negative impact of lower interest rates on debt mark-to-market and FX. 
While we don't expect to see significant investment activity during the summer months, and as a result, we don't expect to see much change in fund values, here is what we can tell you as of today. 
Our open-end fund PTELF has a EUR 400 million equity queue, its largest ever. We have closed EUR 70 million in new equity commitments in PTELF as planned on June 30, again, post-Brexit, from a Swiss capital source. Our open funds in Europe are approximately 30% levered, and our JVs are 0% levered, so we have plenty of capital to take advantage of the right opportunity, should they arise. 
On June 30, we had one secondary trade occur in our PEPF II vehicle. It was a EUR 16 million trade at par between a fund that was expiring and an existing PEPF II investor. The at-par trade validates our current fund valuations. 
To date, we have had no formal redemption requests but have heard some noise about 2 Sterling investors with investment totaling about EUR 45 million that may pursue secondary trades. 
So let me quickly summarize. Leasing volume and rent appear to be holding up well. On the development front, we are significantly ahead of our underwritten lease-up, new supply is generally in check and we expect to maintain a high build-to-suit percentage this year. 
While we can't speak to U.K. office or retail, which have their issues, high-quality logistic assets appear to be trading at valuation. And with respect to Prologis funds, we are in great shape with record queues and capacity to take advantage of any opportunities that present themselves. 
With that, let me turn it over to Tom to take us through the rest of the quarter.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Gary. For the second quarter, we generated core FFO of $0.60 per share, exceeding our forecast due to better-than-expected real estate operations and higher asset management fees. Global occupancy was 96.1% for the quarter, up 70 basis points ye
componenttext:
Thanks, Gary. For the second quarter, we generated core FFO of $0.60 per share, exceeding our forecast due to better-than-expected real estate operations and higher asset management fees. 
Global occupancy was 96.1% for the quarter, up 70 basis points year-over-year. We set another quarterly leasing record at 49 million square feet, including more than 9 million square feet of development leasing. 
Our share of net effective rent change on rollover was 17.8%, led by the U.S. of 23.5%. Our share of same-store NOI increased 6.1%, with U.S. leading the way at 7.5%. This is the last quarter that will be impacted by the burn-off of merger lease intangible amortization. Excluding this impact, our share same-store NOI growth for the quarter would have been 5%. 
For the first half of 2016, development stabilizations were $1.1 billion with an estimated weighted average margin of over 26%. Development starts totaled $658 million with an estimated weighted average margin of over 18%. Build-to-suits comprised almost half of our year-to-date starts. Dispositions and contributions totaled $1.2 billion. 
In terms of total capital proceeds, we've already closed or have under hard contract about 70% of our original full year guidance. 
Turning to capital markets, our leverage at quarter end was 37% on a book basis and 30.6% based on market capitalization. Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains, was 5.6x. Our liquidity, which we defined as our undrawn line capacity and available consolidated cash, reached the highest level in our history this quarter. 
Turning to guidance now for 2016. I'll just cover the material changes so for compete detail, refer to Page 5 of our supplemental. 
Due to stronger operating fundamentals, we're increasing our share same-store NOI range to between 4.75% and 5.25%. In light of our progress year-to-date and investor interest, we're increasing our share of disposition and contribution volume to between $2.3 billion and $2.8 billion, an increase of $300 million at the midpoint. We will complete an additional ownership rebalancing in our USLF and PTELF ventures for a total of $200 million. This is on top of the $400 million we completed earlier this year. We're also raising the midpoint of our share development starts by $200 million for a range of $1.7 billion to $2 billion. We expect our full year build-to-suit percentage to be higher than the 44% we did last year. 
The net result of our deployment changes is that we now expect to generate $1.3 billion of total proceeds in excess of our capital needs, up $300 million from prior guidance. We will use a portion of the net proceeds to retire debt, with a balance further building up our cash reserves. We expect to end the year with liquidity at about $4 billion and booked leverage below 35%. 
Related to FX, our 2016 and 2017 estimated quarter earnings are fully hedged relative to the U.S. dollar, and we have already hedged about half of 2018. 
Putting this all together, our 2016 core FFO, excluding promotes, is higher by $0.03 cents due to better-than-forecasted operations and fees, partially offset by the dilution from an increase and acceleration of the dispositions, contributions and fund rebalancing. In other words, core earnings are higher while, at the same time, significantly increasing our cash reserves. We expect 2016 core FFO, including promotes, to range between $2.52 and $2.58 per share, maintaining our $2.55 midpoint. Our promote range is now $0.14 to $0.16 a share, down $0.03 at the midpoint. The decline in the promotes is primarily due to negative debt mark-to-market and FX movements from the pound weakening against the euro. The promote midpoint assumes that asset values remain unchanged with June 30 appraisals and FX rates remain at current levels. To be clear, asset values in Europe have not declined. In fact, the appraised if our assets in our European ventures increased 70 basis points in the second quarter led by the U.K. at 100 basis points. 
To wrap up, we expect continued strong NOI growth as we harvest the GAAP between in-place and market rents. We're maintaining strong double-digit core FFO growth in 2016 while, at the same time, further strengthening our balance sheet and building liquidity. Our financial position has never been stronger, and we'll continue to improve by year-end as we generate additional proceeds from net deployment. 
With that, I'll turn it to -- over to the operator for your questions.

componenttext: This is related to, I guess, the Brexit campaign. So global trade is significantly slow in the last several years, and there's a lot more protection as retort coming out off politics. So my question is, do you have any thoughts on how this global trade slowdown, whether it's through politics or naturally, how that [indiscernible] warehouse demand for your portfolio over time? And have your customers discussed or they made contingency plans in regard to some of these events?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes. Global trade, which used to run at the about 3X the sum of domestic GDP, has slowed down to about 1.2, 1.3x the size -- the pace of global domestic GDP. It's still going a little bit faster, but as global trade represents a larger and larger percenta
componenttext: Yes. Global trade, which used to run at the about 3X the sum of domestic GDP, has slowed down to about 1.2, 1.3x the size -- the pace of global domestic GDP. It's still going a little bit faster, but as global trade represents a larger and larger percentage of domestic GDP, the math just drives you there. Because when global trade was only 2% of total GDP, it has a lot of opportunity to grow. But once it's reached the saturation level, it's tough to have it grow at the same levels. So part of it is just math and nothing else. Part of it has to do with definitely protectionism and also some exchange rate considerations that affect that patterns of global trade. If global trade is curtailed, which we don't think is going to be the case, we think around every election, there's a lot of talk of protectionism but people know that the people that want protectionism are the very people that actually get hurt by it in the long term. We think notwithstanding the talk around the election season is going to be very little. In fact, we think that CPP is going to go forward and maybe great opportunities in the other direction. So -- but let's assume for a moment that we're all wrong in global and the partitions will get in the way of global trading. Well, you just have to carry more inventory because you're not sourcing to get it from as many places. The big driver is -- the big drivers of demand, though, are consumption fueled by e-commerce and reconfiguration of the supply chain. Those are the real biggies now that global trade has reached the saturation point.

componenttext: Yes. So Greg, it's Gene. I will start with the U.S., and I'm sure Gary will comment on what's happening with Europe. So I'm probably slightly more bullish than I had been in the past in the U.S.

componenttext: Well, let me add something to that. headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: We're not looking to decrease -- first of all, we didn't hear the first part of your question, but I think based on the last part, I can get the gist of where you're going. Look, our business is just a real estate business, and we're not a hedge fund. We
componenttext:
We're not looking to decrease -- first of all, we didn't hear the first part of your question, but I think based on the last part, I can get the gist of where you're going. Look, our business is just a real estate business, and we're not a hedge fund. We don't make decisions minute-by-minute. This is a long-term business. We've got a good allocation, appropriate allocation to Europe. A lot of these stuff is based on long-term prospects for economic and population growth. If basically, the -- we are invested the way we are across the world for a reason. Over time, the only portfolio shift that we imagine has nothing to do with Brexit. We probably want to be a little heavier in Asia and a little lighter in Europe, but fundamentally, our allocations, regardless of Brexit, are where we want them to be. So the big dial that we use in terms of managing our own allocation is our share of our private capital vehicles. That's really the way we managed the business from our capital exposure. We like our scale in Europe because we're the dominant player there and have the best portfolio. And we really like that market position and what it means in terms of what we can do with customers. 
So long-winded answer of saying that we like our hand, we like our position in the U.K, we're willing to -- we think that the U.K. is going to continue to best market in Europe, actually, in the next 10 years. It might take a pause in the short term, but the long-term dynamics of it are quite interesting. 
So we're good where we are. 
Now if opportunities arise and people start doing stupid things, we would be delighted to take advantage of those things. I don't think it will happen. I think by and large, European real estate is in strong institutional hands. There's not a lot of leverage in the system, notwithstanding the headlines that you hear about some of these open-end funds. And there may be pressure, by the way, on financial center-type office buildings in the U.K. But in our product type, we think there are more buyers than sellers of the quality product that we have. So we don't think those distressed opportunities are going to materialize, but if they do, we're prepared to take advantage of that.
