componenttext: One 3-part question. Someone told me a while ago that dividends now matter, and we noticed that you increased your net income -- net earnings as range to $1.70 to $1.90. Talk about what that does for your dividend. Second part of the question is, are you thinking about any other markets globally given that you've got an abundance of cash? And then third, can you talk a little bit about land prices in the tighter industrial markets and how that's affecting replacement cost rents?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: John, I'll take the first one on dividends. Yes, we did see an increase in our EPS this quarter. It was a combination of 2 things, one just higher realized development gains and also just higher disposition activity, what we would call nondevelopment gain
componenttext: John, I'll take the first one on dividends. Yes, we did see an increase in our EPS this quarter. It was a combination of 2 things, one just higher realized development gains and also just higher disposition activity, what we would call nondevelopment gains, non-FFO gains of operating property just increasing our disposition activity, that's what's driving that. No change in our dividend. We're happy with where our payout ratio is, our payout ratio right now. Based on our AFFO, is about 68%. We're comfortable with where that is and we've obviously had extremely good dividend growth over the last several years. But we see the dividend holding where it is this year.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Hey, John, the dividend has been up 50% over the last, I think, 2-and-change years from about 12 to about 68. I would be surprised if the dividend rate doesn't grow by multiples of inflation going forward. I think we're -- we think our FFO growth is going
componenttext: Hey, John, the dividend has been up 50% over the last, I think, 2-and-change years from about 12 to about 68. I would be surprised if the dividend rate doesn't grow by multiples of inflation going forward. I think we're -- we think our FFO growth is going to be pretty strong and we've got good leverage coming through G&A, which is not going nearly as fast. It's actually flat compared to our operating earnings. So I think we've got good leverage to grow our dividend above industry rates, pretty clear about that. We are not planning to go to any new markets. In fact, we're in the process of completing our strategic plan vision 2020. And in it, it doesn't contemplate going into any new markets. It's totally based on deepening our presence in the markets we're already in. And with respect to land and replacement cost, I think land in the U.S. has appreciated quite a bit. And I think the constraints on land and its entitlements are significant. And we'll continue to put pressure on some of the most desirable markets in the U.S. like California in the Pacific Northwest and Miami and the like. The markets that are supply-constrained, I think, there's very little land and very tough to get it entitled. So I think replacement costs, rent numbers are going up and up in the U.S. I think land prices have recovered in Europe, but we don't see them zooming ahead because the rents are still relatively slow growing in Europe. They're growing, but they're much slower growing than the U.S. So land has recovered but it's not zooming ahead. In the U.S., land is pretty expensive.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: The only other thing I would add is Asia. It's probably one of more interesting markets with respect to land. Somebody asked the question earlier about our development volumes in China and, obviously, they're increasing. But each incremental piece of land
componenttext: The only other thing I would add is Asia. It's probably one of more interesting markets with respect to land. Somebody asked the question earlier about our development volumes in China and, obviously, they're increasing. But each incremental piece of land that we buy in China, even if it's phase 2, is incrementally more expensive than the land that we just acquired right next door. And as a result, you're seeing market rent growth there continuing at 4% to 5% range depending on what submarket you're talking about. And in Japan, probably the most expressive land market in the world, and the other thing that's impacting replacement costs rents are construction costs. Then our teams expect that the back half of this year we're going to start to see construction cost rise again as we approach the 2020 Olympics and construction resources become scarce. So I think Asia is a pretty interesting place with respect to the land market.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, Tom. It's Gene. I'll talk about the U.S. So this segment, as you know, if you followed us over the last several years has really recovered. I think we have a high haste for occupancy under 100,000 square feet coming out of our merger. And now that's
componenttext: Yes, Tom. It's Gene. I'll talk about the U.S. So this segment, as you know, if you followed us over the last several years has really recovered. I think we have a high haste for occupancy under 100,000 square feet coming out of our merger. And now that's 94%, sort of 95% in that range. And you're probably not going to see those size increments move a heck of a lot higher because you have many more spaces, you have naturally shorter lease terms and more role. And I'd say that's pretty full. In fact, historically and we could take a look at this. I'm not sure that segment really gets much higher than that. But having said that, the demand is good, you're going to see us bounce around quarter-to-quarter, but demand is good from those tenants. And probably the single most important customer segment is home building. And that really hasn't returned. If it does, perhaps it pushes a little bit more but we're not concerned about it in terms of where we're at. We're probably sort of topped out. And Gary?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, with respect to Europe. This is a place that we've -- this unit size thing is the place, I think, we talked about on past calls. There's definitely an opportunity for us to make progress in Europe. We're currently across the whole of Europe, about 91
componenttext: Yes, with respect to Europe. This is a place that we've -- this unit size thing is the place, I think, we talked about on past calls. There's definitely an opportunity for us to make progress in Europe. We're currently across the whole of Europe, about 91% occupied in small spaces. And again, we look at that in terms of small business formation and the place that we've liked the most is in Southern Europe where candidly you've had the least amount of small business formation. But we have been focused on that segment even in Southern Europe and if you look, we've probably gained 1,200 or 1,400 basis points over the last year in our Southern European portfolio. So it is an area of focus and one where we think opportunities lie certainly in Europe.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: This is Tom. I would just add that I think this segment has the most NOI upside. It's the last to recover, these spaces are generally the most infill, they have the highest rents per square foot. And I think now that you're seeing, as Gene said, these spa
componenttext: This is Tom. I would just add that I think this segment has the most NOI upside. It's the last to recover, these spaces are generally the most infill, they have the highest rents per square foot. And I think now that you're seeing, as Gene said, these spaces stabilizing, I think that's going to allow us to push rent. It's got a little more to catch up so I think a lot of NOI tailwind from this segment, as well as just -- as Gene talked about, home building really not driving that but, clearly, e-commerce is moving into that space and will be a big driver. And again, I think that's just more NOI upside for us.

componenttextpreview: Hamid, if we just go back to sort of your answer -- your comment earlier on equity, what would make you be more open to issuing equity? Would it be the type of deal? Would it be a pricing? If -- let's just think out loud for a second. And if you were to d
componenttext: Hamid, if we just go back to sort of your answer -- your comment earlier on equity, what would make you be more open to issuing equity? Would it be the type of deal? Would it be a pricing? If -- let's just think out loud for a second. And if you were to do something like a KTR today, versus when you got that completed, would there be an equity component now with your stock sort of where it is? Or are you against equity for other reasons?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: No. Look, it's not a religious belief. I mean, I believe in equity when there's a good use for capital deployment and all that. So it's not, a lot of people thought that we needed equity for balance sheet purposes to achieve our A rating. And unfortunatel
componenttext: No. Look, it's not a religious belief. I mean, I believe in equity when there's a good use for capital deployment and all that. So it's not, a lot of people thought that we needed equity for balance sheet purposes to achieve our A rating. And unfortunately they were wrong. And I don't know -- we were very clear that we didn't. And we have liquidity from internal sources, fund rebalancing none strategic asset sales and the like for to fund our business going forward, our development business going forward for 5, 6, 7 years on a normal steady-state scenario. The only thing that's not in that plan is an opportunistic long, large acquisition and that, if we run into those and we do -- we go into a hibernation for a couple of years and once in a while we come out and do something big and then go back into hibernation. We don't have a capital plan that contemplates that -- those types of deals but if they were to materialize, that's when we would take a look at equity along with other sources. But I can tell you we got a lot of liquidity right now between lines totaling $3.5 billion and the cash that will build up to about $1 billion in the balance sheet. I mean, we got over $4 billion of liquidity. So -- and we like our currency. I mean, I think yes, we are now finally trading at the NAV of our underlying real estate. But still the market isn't paying us for our development platform, which creates $400 million to $500 million NAV like clockwork every year. So long-winded answer but equity is not the first place we would look to fund even a strategic transaction. There are other places we can go to do that, including private capital and our liquidity resources.

componenttext: Steve, I think it's things outside the real estate market. So those kinds, I'll argue, we're having as prudent capital structure so that we can -- you can go through any scenario and maybe even capitalize on some other opportunities that come up in those kinds of scenarios, which is not a position we're in, in the last cycle. So we have learned our lessons and I think we're adequately prepared for those types of situations. But I don't really see anything on the real estate markets that concern me. Remember, demand was never and still is not spectacular. I think demand on the 10-point scale is a 6. I just think supply is kind of the 4 to 5. And that's what's been keeping the markets healthy. So it's really the other stuff, the geopolitical and domestic political issues and all the stuff that we read about in newspapers and watch on TV, very concerned about those.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Dave, let me start with that. One way to think about the -- kind of risking new development program is if you take all your vacant development, no matter what condition it's in, what percentage of your overall portfolio development and operating, what doe
componenttext: Dave, let me start with that. One way to think about the -- kind of risking new development program is if you take all your vacant development, no matter what condition it's in, what percentage of your overall portfolio development and operating, what does that represent? And over the last couple of years, when we've really sort of ramp our development up, we've been between 4% and 5%. And as of this quarter, it's 3.5%. So we're -- I think fairly derisk on that front. And then if you look at -- you look at starts on the U.S. for example, and this gets to the customer dialogue, we're 89% pre-leased on the starts this quarter because we had effectively 6 build-to-suits or pre-leased deals. And that's a result of lots and lots of customer dialogue that's taking place over a couple of years at this point. But most of our customers, today their focus is on how do they plan for the future. Most of them are in the midst of a supply chain reconfiguration of some type. And the markets are so tight. They have to plan, they have to engage with us more in long-term planning. And so I think actually that the nature of that dialogue is shifted dramatically. It hasn't shifted just in the last quarter, it's taking some period of time but that's why you see lease terms are significantly longer than they were a couple of years ago. And we'd like to think these discussions are strategic versus transactional. So I think that actually is a pretty significant change that we've seen.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, the only thing I would ask to that is that I've been doing this for over 30 years and I have never seen an environment where customers have been as willing to share with us their future plans for growth and asking us to build more product. I mean, li
componenttext: Yes, the only thing I would ask to that is that I've been doing this for over 30 years and I have never seen an environment where customers have been as willing to share with us their future plans for growth and asking us to build more product. I mean, literally, they're asking us to build more spec product and they are coming ahead and telling us where their needs are. And they used to play their cards pretty close to their vest. Now part of this may be just that level of strategic dialogue that we've created with them I mean, with some of these customers we have 30, 40, 50, 60 leases. You can engage in meaningful dialogue when you have that kind of customer connectivity; whereas if you have random portfolio and may be the customer sprinkled in 3 locations, they think of you more as a vendor than a partner. So I think the business is finally getting to the scale. Not only because of its size, but also because of its focus on the key markets that the dialogue is becoming more and more strategic and that's what we work very hard to create. So we're very encouraged by all that. And look to take advantage of it. It manifest itself in very high volumes of build-to-suits, not because we want it to be that way, but because it turns out that way that people want to lock up spec capacity ahead of time. So a lot of these are spec-to-suit or buildings we're going to build anyway that get leased up on a build-to-suit basis before we start with minor modifications. It's a good place to be.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: So Michael, you'll remember this because you were there and actually you asked us some good questions then. Back in 2012, when we laid out that crazy scenario of 25% rental growth in the U.S., we've blown through that. And remember there was another phase
componenttext: So Michael, you'll remember this because you were there and actually you asked us some good questions then. Back in 2012, when we laid out that crazy scenario of 25% rental growth in the U.S., we've blown through that. And remember there was another phase after that, which is where would market rents go when replacement costs recovered, when construction cost recovered because everybody was working for nothing then and when land cost recovered. That's a whole another acceleration of replacement cost, which is really pushing rent, if you go back to that time more like 35% from that time. So we've been surprised by that last 10%, we thought we're being pretty aggressive. You guys thought all of you -- we were crazy. The market it turned out to be much more -- we were all very conservative in retrospect and the market has blown past that because replacement cost that's blown past that. And we shouldn't really be surprised because nominal rent today are only a few percent higher than what they were in 2000. We had a dry period of 10 to 15 years of very little nominal rental growth and now we're finally getting back to nominal rents that we got in the early 2000. On a real basis, we're still 35% below where we should be. I'm not saying we're going to have 35% more rental growth, don't get me wrong, but I'm just saying nominally, where we were 15 years ago we shouldn't be this surprised. But I guess when you were in the depth -- we were all in the depths of 2012, none of us had enough vision to project 35%, 40% rental growth but that's what's happening.

componenttext: Yes, sure Eric, it's Gene. And you're correct about Houston, that's where the supply is. Our portfolio is primarily Northwest and it's pretty built out, there isn't a lot of supply. But if you look at the raw numbers in Houston, it is an overbuilt condition, it still has positive absorption, which probably surprises a lot of people. But it is overbuilt. Other markets that we've called out Columbus, again not a horrendous situation but they have excess of client and a forward pipeline that concerns us. And otherwise, we look at this all the time as you know, other markets just don't scream bad at this point. Dallas has a lot of construction going on and Dallas has a forward supply scenario that has us sort of cautious. But again, a lot of that's in South Dallas, most of our development, most of our portfolio is around the airport in the north now. So I could go on about other markets but the reality is that we're in pretty good shape in these markets in the U.S. And there's something else I'd point out, Eric, and this is worth noting and watching going forward. We've called out a couple of markets historically over last several quarters Indianapolis is one of them, Central and Eastern Pennsylvania. And what's happened and frankly, I haven't seen this happen before in my career is we -- markets got closed doing over building situation or maybe a little over the line and they've corrected. So both of those markets are actually -- they've taken the foot of the gas, they'd lowered the supply level and they've made corrections. And there's a couple of other markets but New Jersey would also fall on that category, by the way, that's really, really good to see. And again we got to watch this every day. But we continue to be very pleased with the overall discipline.

componenttextpreview: Yes, Eric. The only thing I would add to what Gene said is that the only place I see around the world where truly stupid things are happening is Poland. I mean, it is irresponsible with a capital. And you've got literally people signing leases on build-to
componenttext: Yes, Eric. The only thing I would add to what Gene said is that the only place I see around the world where truly stupid things are happening is Poland. I mean, it is irresponsible with a capital. And you've got literally people signing leases on build-to-suits with face rents that they then discount with 3 years of free rents on a 10-year lease. And there's some investor that comes up and buys it at the cap rate that they think is the cap rate. And they do it with site letters and all kinds of games that are really not good for our industry's reputation. And we're concerned about that and we will speak about that and as I mentioned to you a couple of quarters ago, we have the real stake in making sure that investors are making intelligent decisions. By the way, Poland is before everybody gets all excited, Poland is 2% of our portfolio and this is really only happening in a few locations in Poland. But it is concerning, it sort of reminds me of Dallas in 1997, '98. And some people are going to get burned doing that and then they'll stop. But at the moment that's the only place in the world that worries me.

componenttext: Let me hit development. Development margins have been crazy good and a lot of it has to do with the fact that we are monetizing low, cheap land from the downturn that was impaired and all that. I think at market -- with market land values, our development margins are more normal, they're still high but they're more normal, they're not as crazy high. Remember what we said about development margins? In a steady state market, which we're not in yet, we're better that this. But when the market is totally steady, spec should be around 15 and build-to-suits should be 10 to 12. Right now, we're probably at market 5 points higher in that for both spec and build-to-suit. Good afternoon. My name is Kim, and I'll be your conference operator today. At this time, I would like to welcome everyone to Prologis Second Quarter Earnings Call. [Operator Instructions] 
Ms. Tracy Ward, Senior Vice President, Investor Relations, you may begin your conference.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our second quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com, under Investor Relations.This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and C
componenttext:
Thanks, Kim, and good morning, everyone. Welcome to our second quarter 2016 conference call. The supplemental document is available on our website at prologis.com, under Investor Relations.
This morning, we'll hear from Hamid Moghadam, our Chairman and CEO, who will comment on the company's strategy and market environment; Gary Anderson, our CEO of Europe and Asia, who will provide an update on our European and U.K. businesses; and then from Tom Olinger, our CFO, who will cover results and guidance.
Also joining us for today's call are Mike Curless, Ed Nekritz, Gene Reilly and Diana Scott.
Before we begin our prepared remarks, I'd like to state that this call will contain forward-looking statements under Federal Securities Laws. These statements are based on current expectations, estimates and projections about the market and the industry in which Prologis operates as well as management's beliefs and assumptions. Forward-looking statements are not guarantees of performance, and actual operating results may be affected by a variety of factors. For a list of those factors, please refer to the forward-looking statement notice in our 10-K or SEC filings.
Additionally, our second quarter results press release and supplemental do contain financial measures such as FFO and EBITDA that are non-GAAP measures. And in accordance to Reg G, we have provided a reconciliation to those measures. 
With that, I'll turn the call over to Hamid and we'll get started.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. We posted another great quarter with positive rent change at almost 18% while maintaining high occupancies. Our core FFO per share grew 15%. Our capital deployment and monetization activities were above expectati
componenttext:
Thanks, Tracy, and good morning, everyone. We posted another great quarter with positive rent change at almost 18% while maintaining high occupancies. Our core FFO per share grew 15%. Our capital deployment and monetization activities were above expectations as we continue to strengthen our balance sheet. In our strategic capital business, we have ample fresh commitment from investors and are well positioned to take advantage of any market opportunities that may present themselves. 
All in all, the last 6 months have been the best in our company's history. We understand, though, that some of you are concern about our exposure to Europe generally and to the U.K., specifically. So far, however, the impact of Brexit on our operations has been minimal. Our U.K. customers served mostly domestic consumers, and we believe the decision to leave the EU will not materially change the buying habits of 65 million people. We're also confident in our overall European business. E-commerce and supply chain reconfiguration continue as big drivers of demand for our product. The Class A market is where the action is and where our portfolio is focused. Any modest decline in GDP growth with -- in all likelihood, be offset by the need to carry slightly higher inventories. In fact, our only concern in Europe is in Poland, where a few merchant developers are overbuilding the market by offering rental incentives of up to 40% and commencing new investors to capitalize artificially inflated headline rents. We don't see this anywhere else in Europe. Surely, there'll be more mixed news coming out of Europe and that will lead to continued market volatility. 
Whether it's bank failures or constitutional reforms in Italy, or elections in France and The Netherlands, we expect policymakers to keep global interest rates lower for longer. In time, this will translate into support for lower cap rate across Europe. We're confident in the resilience of the logistics real estate business, but we remain vigilant and on the lookout for any signs of trouble. 
Before we turn the call to Tom, Gary Anderson, our CEO of Europe and Asia, will share some underground facts from our business in Europe. You'll hear from him in a moment. 
Elsewhere around the globe, market conditions remain strong and steady. Overall, the supply and demand proves in great shape, with all-time low vacancy rates. Demand is driven by steady growth and consumption, e-commerce and supply chain monetization. 
In the U.S., rents are up again sharply, and we expect net absorption will again exceed new supply for the year. In Japan, new supply from development is being absorbed, and cap rates continue to compress while occupancy and rents are up in China. Even in our softness market, Brazil were 100% leased, but rents there are down about 10% from the peak. 
Looking across our markets, we only see a few locations of excess supply, specifically Houston, Columbus, and I -- as I mentioned earlier, parts of Poland. In these lower-barrier markets, private developers and their institutional capital partners are delivering more products than the market can absorb. Other than these few exceptions, our markets are in very good shape. 
In conclusion, we've worked hard to position our company for success and are excited about the prospects for the coming years. Let me now to turn the call over to Gary.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Hamid, and good morning. The European market performed very well in the first half of 2016 with demand outpacing supply. Market vacancy in Europe is currently 6%, down 60 basis points year-over-year and is currently projected to end the year at 5.
componenttext:
Thanks, Hamid, and good morning. The European market performed very well in the first half of 2016 with demand outpacing supply. Market vacancy in Europe is currently 6%, down 60 basis points year-over-year and is currently projected to end the year at 5.8%. The Prologis portfolio outperformed the market and delivered some of our strongest results on record. Occupancy in our European portfolio is 95.6%, up 130 basis points year-over-year and 70 basis points quarter-over-quarter. The U.K. led all regions at 98.8% occupied and today, the 22.4 million-square-foot operating pool in the U.K. is 100% leased. 
Rent change on roll for the quarter totaled 5.1% in Europe with all regions delivering positive results and was led by the U.K. at 17.6%. 
I'd like to turn now to our activity post-Brexit and present simply the facts as we see them on the ground from June 23, the day of the vote, through today. 
Let's begin with leasing. We've completed 56 transactions in Europe totaling just under 4.9 million square feet with 8% positive rent change. The U.K. portion is 1.3 million square feet with 24% rent change during that same post-Brexit period. Demand in Europe still appears to be broad-based and continues to have an emphasis on the automotive and e-commerce sectors. We've completed leases post-Brexit, with many names you'll know, including DHL, Schneider Electric, Jaguar Land Rover, Marks & Spencer and Alibaba. 
Risk associated with our U.K. NOI has been minimized. Today, the U.K. portfolio is 100% leased, has a weighted average lease term of 8 years, has only 11% of leases expiring over the next 18 months and has in-place rents that are roughly 10% below market. 
Let's now turn to Europe development activity. We've had a very prudent approach to development in Europe with a heavy emphasis on build-to-suit. Today, we have a 6.2 million-square-foot development portfolio in Europe, which is 60% leased and is approximately 1,000 basis points ahead of our underwriting. The U.K. portion of our development portfolio totals 1.9 million square feet and is 850 basis points ahead of our underwriting. We also expect to execute 2 leases totaling about 570,000 square feet imminently and have good activity on the balance of our U.K. developments. The only exception is a 317,000 square-foot building in London Gateway, where there has been little activity even before Brexit. 
Turning to capital markets and building sales. We sold a 3-building portfolio in the U.K. during the second quarter, and that transaction closed as planned on June 21, 2 days before the referendum vote. We also began negotiating the sale of EUR 100 million-plus French portfolio pre-Brexit and concluded discussions on Friday of last week with no change to our pricing. The buyers are now under contract with a 10% nonrefundable deposit. 
There has also been some non-Prologis activity to report in the U.K. that underscore solid pricing for logistics assets. 103,000 square-foot building leased to DHL in Birmingham with a 10-year term closed on July 1, at a 4.8% stabilized cap rate, and another 176,000 square-foot building lent to Amazon for 10 years in Manchester is expected to close at about the same level in the next few days. 
In addition, a U.K. retail fund has brought a GBP 50 million British Telecom logistics deal to market, and as active buyers transact in just 5 working days, there are reportedly more than 10 bidders at about a 5% stabilize cap rate, probably 15 to 20 basis points higher than we would normally expect but a very small discount when you consider the timescale and lack of due diligence. Beyond that, we're hearing rumors that certain retail funds may bring assets to market to create liquidity, and we will monitor those for opportunity. 
In general, values in the U.K. are driven by lease length and location, so you shouldn't expect to see any meaningful value change in the Prologis U.K. portfolio given our current lease length location and interest rates that are widely believed to be going lower for longer. 
Lastly, let's turn to our funds. Values are up 70 basis points this quarter in our European funds on incremental leasing and cap rate compression on the continent, but any of these are flat to slightly down given the negative impact of lower interest rates on debt mark-to-market and FX. 
While we don't expect to see significant investment activity during the summer months, and as a result, we don't expect to see much change in fund values, here is what we can tell you as of today. 
Our open-end fund PTELF has a EUR 400 million equity queue, its largest ever. We have closed EUR 70 million in new equity commitments in PTELF as planned on June 30, again, post-Brexit, from a Swiss capital source. Our open funds in Europe are approximately 30% levered, and our JVs are 0% levered, so we have plenty of capital to take advantage of the right opportunity, should they arise. 
On June 30, we had one secondary trade occur in our PEPF II vehicle. It was a EUR 16 million trade at par between a fund that was expiring and an existing PEPF II investor. The at-par trade validates our current fund valuations. 
To date, we have had no formal redemption requests but have heard some noise about 2 Sterling investors with investment totaling about EUR 45 million that may pursue secondary trades. 
So let me quickly summarize. Leasing volume and rent appear to be holding up well. On the development front, we are significantly ahead of our underwritten lease-up, new supply is generally in check and we expect to maintain a high build-to-suit percentage this year. 
While we can't speak to U.K. office or retail, which have their issues, high-quality logistic assets appear to be trading at valuation. And with respect to Prologis funds, we are in great shape with record queues and capacity to take advantage of any opportunities that present themselves. 
With that, let me turn it over to Tom to take us through the rest of the quarter.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Thanks, Gary. For the second quarter, we generated core FFO of $0.60 per share, exceeding our forecast due to better-than-expected real estate operations and higher asset management fees. Global occupancy was 96.1% for the quarter, up 70 basis points ye
componenttext:
Thanks, Gary. For the second quarter, we generated core FFO of $0.60 per share, exceeding our forecast due to better-than-expected real estate operations and higher asset management fees. 
Global occupancy was 96.1% for the quarter, up 70 basis points year-over-year. We set another quarterly leasing record at 49 million square feet, including more than 9 million square feet of development leasing. 
Our share of net effective rent change on rollover was 17.8%, led by the U.S. at 23.5%. Our share of same-store NOI increased 6.1%, with U.S. leading the way at 7.5%. This is the last quarter that will be impacted by the burn-off of merger lease intangible amortization. Excluding this impact, our share same-store NOI growth for the quarter would have been 5%. 
For the first half of 2016, development stabilizations were $1.1 billion with an estimated weighted average margin of over 26%. Development starts totaled $658 million with an estimated weighted average margin of over 18%. Build-to-suits comprised almost half of our year-to-date starts. Dispositions and contributions totaled $1.2 billion. 
In terms of total capital proceeds, we've already closed or have under hard contract about 70% of our original full year guidance. 
Turning to capital markets, our leverage at quarter end was 37% on a book basis and 30.6% based on market capitalization. Debt-to-EBITDA, including gains, was 5.6x. Our liquidity, which we defined as our undrawn line capacity and available consolidated cash, reached the highest level in our history this quarter. 
Turning to guidance now for 2016. I'll just cover the material changes so for compete detail, refer to Page 5 of our supplemental. 
Due to stronger operating fundamentals, we're increasing our share same-store NOI range to between 4.75% and 5.25%. In light of our progress year-to-date and investor interest, we're increasing our share of disposition and contribution volume to between $2.3 billion and $2.8 billion, an increase of $300 million at the midpoint. We will complete an additional ownership rebalancing in our USLF and PTELF ventures for a total of $200 million. This is on top of the $400 million we completed earlier this year. We're also raising the midpoint of our share development starts by $200 million for a range of $1.7 billion to $2 billion. We expect our full year build-to-suit percentage to be higher than the 44% we did last year. 
The net result of our deployment changes is that we now expect to generate $1.3 billion of total proceeds in excess of our capital needs, up $300 million from prior guidance. We will use a portion of the net proceeds to retire debt, with a balance further building up our cash reserves. We expect to end the year with liquidity at about $4 billion and booked leverage below 35%. 
Related to FX, our 2016 and 2017 estimated quarter earnings are fully hedged relative to the U.S. dollar, and we have already hedged about half of 2018. 
Putting this all together, our 2016 core FFO, excluding promotes, is higher by $0.03 cents due to better-than-forecasted operations and fees, partially offset by the dilution from an increase and acceleration of the dispositions, contributions and fund rebalancing. In other words, core earnings are higher while, at the same time, significantly increasing our cash reserves. We expect 2016 core FFO, including promotes, to range between $2.52 and $2.58 per share, maintaining our $2.55 midpoint. Our promote range is now $0.14 to $0.16 a share, down $0.03 at the midpoint. The decline in the promotes is primarily due to negative debt mark-to-market and FX movements from the pound weakening against the euro. The promote midpoint assumes that asset values remain unchanged with June 30 appraisals and FX rates remain at current levels. To be clear, asset values in Europe have not declined. In fact, the appraised value of our assets in our European ventures increased 70 basis points in the second quarter led by the U.K. at 100 basis points. 
To wrap up, we expect continued strong NOI growth as we harvest the GAAP between in-place and market rents. We're maintaining strong double-digit core FFO growth in 2016 while, at the same time, further strengthening our balance sheet and building liquidity. Our financial position has never been stronger, and it will continue to improve by year-end as we generate additional proceeds from net deployment. 
With that, I'll turn it to -- over to the operator for your questions.

componenttextpreview: This is related to, I guess, the Brexit campaign. So global trade is significantly slow in the last several years, and there's a lot more protection as retort coming out off politics. So my question is, do you have any thoughts on how this global trade sl
componenttext: This is related to, I guess, the Brexit campaign. So global trade is significantly slow in the last several years, and there's a lot more protection as retort coming out off politics. So my question is, do you have any thoughts on how this global trade slowdown, whether it's through politics or naturally, how that impacts warehouse demand for your portfolio over time? And have your customers discussed or they made contingency plans in regard to some of these events?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes. Global trade, which used to run at the about 3X the sum of domestic GDP, has slowed down to about 1.2, 1.3x the size -- the pace of global domestic GDP. It's still going a little bit faster, but as global trade represents a larger and larger percenta
componenttext: Yes. Global trade, which used to run at the about 3X the sum of domestic GDP, has slowed down to about 1.2, 1.3x the size -- the pace of global domestic GDP. It's still going a little bit faster, but as global trade represents a larger and larger percentage of domestic GDP, the math just drives you there. Because when global trade was only 2% of total GDP, it had a lot of opportunity to grow. But once it's reached the saturation level, it's tough to have it grow at the same levels. So part of it is just math and nothing else. Part of it has to do with definitely protectionism and also some exchange rate considerations that affect that patterns of global trade. If global trade is curtailed, which we don't think is going to be the case, we think around every election, there's a lot of talk of protectionism but people know that the people that want protectionism are the very people that actually get hurt by it in the long term. We think notwithstanding the talk around the election season is going to be very little. In fact, we think that CPP is going to go forward and maybe great opportunities in the other direction. So -- but let's assume for a moment that we're all wrong in global and the politicians will get in the way of global trading. Well, you just have to carry more inventory because you're not sourcing to get it from as many places. The big driver is -- the big drivers of demand, though, are consumption fueled by e-commerce and reconfiguration of the supply chain. Those are the real biggies now that global trade has reached the saturation point.

componenttext: Yes. So Greg, it's Gene. I will start with the U.S., and I'm sure Gary will comment on what's happening with Europe. So I think we are probably talking about a 5 or something next year, and I think we're going to do better than that. And as I said on the last call, I think equilibrium in the U.S. markets is probably some time in '17. And again, I'd remind you, when we reach equilibrium, we'll be an all-time low vacancy rates, and you still have plenty of room to push rents. So I'm probably slightly more bullish than I had been in the past in the U.S.

componenttext: Well, let me add something to that. headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: We're not looking to decrease -- first of all, we didn't hear the first part of your question, but I think based on the last part, I can get the gist of where you're going. Look, our business is just a real estate business, and we're not a hedge fund. We
componenttext:
We're not looking to decrease -- first of all, we didn't hear the first part of your question, but I think based on the last part, I can get the gist of where you're going. Look, our business is just a real estate business, and we're not a hedge fund. We don't make decisions minute-by-minute. This is a long-term business. We've got a good allocation, appropriate allocation to Europe. A lot of this stuff is based on long-term prospects for economic and population growth. If basically, the -- we are invested the way we are across the world for a reason. Over time, the only portfolio shift that we imagine has nothing to do with Brexit. We probably want to be a little heavier in Asia and a little lighter in Europe, but fundamentally, our allocations, regardless of Brexit, are where we want them to be. So the big dial that we use in terms of managing our own allocation is our share of our private capital vehicles. That's really the way we managed the business from our capital exposure. We like our scale in Europe because we're the dominant player there and have the best portfolio. And we really like that market position and what it means in terms of what we can do with customers. 
So long-winded answer of saying that we like our hand, we like our position in the U.K, we're willing to -- we think that the U.K. is going to continue to be the best market in Europe, actually, in the next 10 years. It might take a pause in the short term, but the long-term dynamics of it are quite interesting. 
So we're good where we are. 
Now if opportunities arise and people start doing stupid things, we would be delighted to take advantage of those things. I don't think it will happen. I think by and large, European real estate is in strong institutional hands. There's not a lot of leverage in the system, notwithstanding the headlines that you hear about some of these open-end funds. And there may be pressure, by the way, on financial center-type office buildings in the U.K. But in our product type, we think there are more buyers than sellers of the quality of product that we have. So we don't think those distressed opportunities are going to materialize, but if they do, we're prepared to take advantage of that.

componenttext:
One 3-part question. Someone told me a while ago that dividends now matter, and we noticed that you increased your net income -- net earnings as range to $1.70 to $1.90. 
Talk about what that does for your dividend. Second part of the question is, are you thinking about any other markets globally given that you've got an abundance of cash? And then third, can you talk a little bit about land prices in the tighter industrial markets and how that's affecting replacement cost rents?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: John, I'll take the first one on dividends. Yes, we did see an increase in our EPS this quarter. It was a combination of 2 things, one just higher realized development gains and also just higher disposition activity, what we would call nondevelopment gain
componenttext: John, I'll take the first one on dividends. Yes, we did see an increase in our EPS this quarter. It was a combination of 2 things, one just higher realized development gains and also just higher disposition activity, what we would call nondevelopment gains, non-FFO gains of operating property just increasing our disposition activity, that's what's driving that. No change in our dividend. We're happy with where our payout ratio is, our payout ratio right now. Based on our AFFO, is about 68%. We're comfortable with where that is and we've obviously had extremely good dividend growth over the last several years. But we see the dividend holding where it is this year.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Hey, John, the dividend has been up 50% over the last, I think, 2-and-change years from about 12 to about 68. I would be surprised if the dividend rate doesn't grow by multiples of inflation going forward. I think we're -- we think our FFO growth is going
componenttext: Hey, John, the dividend has been up 50% over the last, I think, 2-and-change years from about 12 to about 68. I would be surprised if the dividend rate doesn't grow by multiples of inflation going forward. I think we're -- we think our FFO growth is going to be pretty strong and we've got good leverage coming through G&A, which is not growing nearly as fast. It's actually flat compared to our operating earnings. So I think we've got good leverage to grow our dividend above industry rates, pretty clear about that. We are not planning to go to any new markets. In fact, we're in the process of completing our strategic plan vision 2020. And in it, it doesn't contemplate going into any new markets. It's totally based on deepening our presence in the markets we're already in. And with respect to land and replacement cost, I think land in the U.S. has appreciated quite a bit. And I think the constraints on land and its entitlements are significant. And we'll continue to put pressure on some of the most desirable markets in the U.S. like California in the Pacific Northwest and Miami and the like. The markets that are supply-constrained, I think, there's very little land and very tough to get it entitled. So I think replacement costs, rent numbers are going up and up in the U.S. I think land prices have recovered in Europe, but we don't see them zooming ahead because the rents are still relatively slow growing in Europe. They're growing, but they're much slower growing than the U.S. So land has recovered but it's not zooming ahead. In the U.S., land is pretty expensive.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: The only other thing I would add is Asia. It's probably one of more interesting markets with respect to land. Somebody asked the question earlier about our development volumes in China and, obviously, they're increasing. But each incremental piece of land
componenttext: The only other thing I would add is Asia. It's probably one of more interesting markets with respect to land. Somebody asked the question earlier about our development volumes in China and, obviously, they're increasing. But each incremental piece of land that we buy in China, even if it's phase 2, is incrementally more expensive than the land that we just acquired right next door. And as a result, you're seeing market rent growth there continuing at 4% to 5% range depending on what submarket you're talking about. And in Japan, probably the most expressive land market in the world, and the other thing that's impacting replacement costs rents are construction costs. Then our teams expect that the back half of this year we're going to start to see construction cost rise again as we approach the 2020 Olympics and construction resources become scarce. So I think Asia is a pretty interesting place with respect to the land market.

componenttext: Yes, Tom. It's Gene. I'll talk about the U.S. So this segment, as you know, if you followed us over the last several years has really recovered. I think we have a high haste for occupancy under 100,000 square feet coming out of our merger. And now that's 94%, sort of 95% in that range. And you're probably not going to see those size increments move a heck of a lot higher because you have many more spaces, you have naturally shorter lease terms and more role. And I'd say that's pretty full. In fact, historically and we could take a look at this. I'm not sure that segment really gets much higher than that. But having said that, the demand is good, you're going to see us bounce around quarter-to-quarter, but demand is good from those tenants. And probably the single most important customer segment is home building. And that really hasn't returned. If it does, perhaps it pushes a little bit more but we're not concerned about it in terms of where we're at. We're probably sort of topped out. And Gary?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, with respect to Europe. This is a place that we've -- this unit size thing is the place, I think, we talked about on past calls. There's definitely an opportunity for us to make progress in Europe. We're currently across the whole of Europe, about 91
componenttext: Yes, with respect to Europe. This is a place that we've -- this unit size thing is the place, I think, we talked about on past calls. There's definitely an opportunity for us to make progress in Europe. We're currently across the whole of Europe, about 91% occupied in small spaces. And again, we look at that in terms of small business formation and the place that we've liked the most is in Southern Europe where candidly you've had the least amount of small business formation. But we have been focused on that segment even in Southern Europe and if you look, we've probably gained 1,200 or 1,400 basis points over the last year in our Southern European portfolio. So it is a area of focus and one where we think opportunities lie certainly in Europe.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: This is Tom. I would just add that I think this segment has the most NOI upside. It's the last to recover, these spaces are generally the most infill, they have the highest rents per square foot. And I think now that you're seeing, as Gene said, these spa
componenttext: This is Tom. I would just add that I think this segment has the most NOI upside. It's the last to recover, these spaces are generally the most infill, they have the highest rents per square foot. And I think now that you're seeing, as Gene said, these spaces stabilizing, I think that's going to allow us to push rent. It's got a little more to catch up so I think a lot of NOI tailwind from this segment, as well as just -- as Gene talked about, home building really not driving that but, clearly, e-commerce is moving into that space and will be a big driver. And again, I think that's just more NOI upside for us.

componenttextpreview: Hamid, if we just go back to sort of your answer -- your comment earlier on equity, what would make you be more open to issuing equity? Would it be the type of deal? Would it be a pricing? If -- let's just think out loud for a second. And if you were to d
componenttext: Hamid, if we just go back to sort of your answer -- your comment earlier on equity, what would make you be more open to issuing equity? Would it be the type of deal? Would it be a pricing? If -- let's just think out loud for a second. And if you were to do something like a KTR today, versus when you got that completed, would there be an equity component now with your stock sort of where it is? Or are you against equity for other reasons?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: No. Look, it's not a religious belief. I mean, I believe in equity when there's a good use for capital deployment and all that. So it's not, a lot of people thought that we needed equity for balance sheet purposes to achieve our A rating. And unfortunatel
componenttext: No. Look, it's not a religious belief. I mean, I believe in equity when there's a good use for capital deployment and all that. So it's not, a lot of people thought that we needed equity for balance sheet purposes to achieve our A rating. And unfortunately they were wrong. And I don't know -- we were very clear that we didn't. And we have liquidity from internal sources, fund rebalancing, non-strategic asset sales and the like for -- to fund our business going forward, our development business going forward for 5, 6, 7 years on a normal steady-state scenario. The only thing that's not in that plan is an opportunistic long, large acquisition and that, if we run into those and we do -- we go into a hibernation for a couple of years and once in a while we come out and do something big and then go back into hibernation. We don't have a capital plan that contemplates that -- those types of deals but if they were to materialize, that's when we would take a look at equity along with other sources. But I can tell you we got a lot of liquidity right now between lines totaling $3.5 billion and the cash that will build up to about $1 billion in the balance sheet. I mean, we got over $4 billion of liquidity. So -- and we like our currency. I mean, I think yes, we are now finally trading at the NAV of our underlying real estate. But still the market isn't paying us for our development platform, which creates $400 million to $500 million NAV like clockwork every year. So long-winded answer but equity is not the first place we would look to fund even a strategic transaction. There are other places we can go to do that, including private capital and our liquidity resources.

componenttext: This is Mike. Sorry, a little frog in my throat here. Between regional mix and age, we saw a little bit of uptick in cap rates we expect that to normalize on disposition throughout the rest of the year.

componenttext: Most of my questions have been asked. I guess, Hamid, just kind of big picture, I mean, everything seems to be going very well in the business and you guys are even more optimistic today than maybe you were 6 months ago. I guess, what are the potential storm clouds that you're watching that would cause you to either take the development starts down or to get more cautious on the rent growth or NOI growth over the next 8, 12 to 24 months?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Steve, I think it's things outside the real estate market. I mean, we are living in a pretty difficult geopolitical environment and there are some domestic issues going on that are very concerning that could have spill over to the economy. So those kinds
componenttext: Steve, I think it's things outside the real estate market. I mean, we are living in a pretty difficult geopolitical environment and there are some domestic issues going on that are very concerning that could have spill over to the economy. So those kinds of things, I'll argue, we're having as prudent capital structure so that we can -- you can go through any scenario and maybe even capitalize on some other opportunities that come up in those kinds of scenarios, which is not a position we're in, in the last cycle. So we have learned our lessons and I think we're adequately prepared for those types of situations. But I don't really see anything on the real estate markets that concern me. Remember, demand was never and still is not spectacular. I think demand on the 10-point scale is a 6. I just think supply is kind of the 4 to 5. And that's what's been keeping the markets healthy. So it's really the other stuff, the geopolitical and domestic political issues and all the stuff that we read about in newspapers and watch on TV, very concerned about those.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Maybe for Gene and Hamid focusing on the U.S. specifically. Can you detail some of the discussions that you're having with some of your current and potential customers around the development side of the business, kind of what that tells you about your com
componenttext: Maybe for Gene and Hamid focusing on the U.S. specifically. Can you detail some of the discussions that you're having with some of your current and potential customers around the development side of the business, kind of what that tells you about your comfort with spec and build-to-suit and sizing of the pipeline going forward? And I guess maybe a second part to that is, I think you said in your guidance and it was written down that you're going to take a bigger share of the development spend and is there anything we should kind of read into that as well? So...

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Dave, let me start with that. One way to think about the -- kind of risking new development program is if you take all your vacant development, no matter what condition it's in, what percentage of your overall portfolio development and operating, what doe
componenttext: Dave, let me start with that. One way to think about the -- kind of risking new development program is if you take all your vacant development, no matter what condition it's in, what percentage of your overall portfolio development and operating, what does that represent? And over the last couple of years, when we've really sort of ramp our development up, we've been between 4% and 5%. And as of this quarter, it's 3.5%. So we're -- I think fairly derisk on that front. And then if you look at -- you look at starts on the U.S. for example, and this gets to the customer dialogue, we're 89% pre-leased on the starts this quarter because we had effectively 6 build-to-suits or pre-leased deals. And that's a result of lots and lots of customer dialogue that's taking place over a couple of years at this point. But most of our customers, today their focus is on how do they plan for the future. Most of them are in the midst of a supply chain reconfiguration of some type. And the markets are so tight. They have to plan, they have to engage with us more in long-term planning. And so I think actually that the nature of that dialogue is shifted dramatically. It hasn't shifted just in the last quarter, it's taking some period of time but that's why you see lease terms are significantly longer than they were a couple of years ago. And we'd like to think these discussions are strategic versus transactional. So I think that actually is a pretty significant change that we've seen.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, the only thing I would ask to that is that I've been doing this for over 30 years and I have never seen an environment where customers have been as willing to share with us their future plans for growth and asking us to build more product. I mean, li
componenttext: Yes, the only thing I would ask to that is that I've been doing this for over 30 years and I have never seen an environment where customers have been as willing to share with us their future plans for growth and asking us to build more product. I mean, literally, they're asking us to build more spec product and they are coming ahead and telling us where their needs are. And they used to play their cards pretty close to their vest. Now part of this may be just that level of strategic dialogue that we've created with them I mean, with some of these customers we have 30, 40, 50, 60 leases. You can engage in meaningful dialogue when you have that kind of customer connectivity; whereas if you have a random portfolio and maybe the customer is sprinkled in 3 locations, they think of you more as a vendor than a partner. So I think the business is finally getting to the scale, not only because of its size, but also because of its focus on the key markets that the dialogue is becoming more and more strategic and that's what we work very hard to create. So we're very encouraged by all that. And look to take advantage of it. It manifests itself in very high volumes of build-to-suits, not because we want it to be that way, but because it turns out that way that people want to lock up spec capacity ahead of time. So a lot of these are spec-to-suit or buildings we're going to build anyway that get leased up on a build-to-suit basis before we start with very minor modifications. It's a good place to be.

componenttext: I apologize if I missed this, but what specifically is driving the 75 basis point increase in the same-store NOI guidance? Is it something more in the rate side, the mark-to-markets are bigger, you think you're going to end up someplace different on the occupancy range or something else?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Mike, it's Tom. It's a combination of both of those things. It's higher rates that we're seeing, just on roll, as well as occupancy is holding up higher than we anticipated. We -- as you know, we're pushing rents and we were anticipating larger declines i
componenttext: Mike, it's Tom. It's a combination of both of those things. It's higher rates that we're seeing, just on roll, as well as occupancy is holding up higher than we anticipated. We -- as you know, we're pushing rents and we were anticipating larger declines in occupancy than what we've seen, it's -- but I would say the primary driver though is rate.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: So Michael, you'll remember this because you were there and actually you asked us some good questions then. Back in 2012, when we laid out that crazy scenario of 25% rental growth in the U.S., we've blown through that. And remember there was another phase
componenttext: So Michael, you'll remember this because you were there and actually you asked us some good questions then. Back in 2012, when we laid out that crazy scenario of 25% rental growth in the U.S., we've blown through that. And remember there was another phase after that, which is where would market rents go when replacement costs recovered, when construction cost recovered because everybody was working for nothing then and when land cost recovered. That's a whole another acceleration of replacement cost, which is really pushing rent, if you go back to that time more like 35% from that time. So we've been surprised by that last 10%, we thought we're being pretty aggressive. You guys thought all of you -- we were crazy. The market it turned out to be much more -- we were all very conservative in retrospect and the market has blown past that because replacement cost that's blown past that. And we shouldn't really be surprised because nominal rent today are only a few percent higher than what they were in 2000. We had a dry period of 10 to 15 years of very little nominal rental growth and now we're finally getting back to nominal rents that we got in the early 2000. On a real basis, we're still 35% below where we should be. I'm not saying we're going to have 35% more rental growth, don't get me wrong, but I'm just saying nominally, where we were 15 years ago we shouldn't be this surprised. But I guess when you were in the depth -- we were all in the depths of 2012, none of us had enough vision to project 35%, 40% rental growth but that's what's happening.

componenttext: Just a follow-up on development. Starts in the first half were relatively low at around $660 million at your share, which is about 1/3 of guidance, which leaves almost $600 million per quarter to start in the second half to hit guidance. So was the low level of starts during the first half, just attributable to regular seasonality? Or does that have anything to do with you guys looking for more build-to-suit projects that may be harder to kind of the same volume as when you were doing more spec development as well? And then just what should we look for as far as the timing of the remaining $1.2 billion of starts at your share this year?

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: This is Mike Curless. Let me address that, relative to the 35% activities to the first half, that might seem low compared to last year where, I think, we're at 54%, which was unusually high for the first half of the year, but historically since the merger
componenttext: This is Mike Curless. Let me address that, relative to the 35% activities to the first half, that might seem low compared to last year where, I think, we're at 54%, which was unusually high for the first half of the year, but historically since the merger, we're always between 30 in base, because there is some seasonality here and a lot of our work -- I mean, the development starts activity is definitely back-end loaded. And so we have clear visibility to 100% of the items on our forecast this year, which is a very good visibility at this time of the year. And at the end of day, we'd expect about 45% of this activity take place in the Americas, call it 30% Asia, 25% in Europe and that's about the same in Americas as last year, and a little bit down in Europe and a little bit up in Asia. Our confidence level is high to finish through this particularly given the robust activity we're seeing in the build-to-suit arena, which is driving the confidence for the second half.

componenttextpreview: Yes, I think the risk to our starts number this year is to the upside not to the downside.
componenttext: Yes, I think the risk to our starts number this year is to the upside not to the downside.

componenttextpreview: Just a follow-up on your comments about supply. Could you provide a little bit more color as to markets where you're seeing supply? I think you mentioned Houston and Columbus. With Houston, it -- does the supply actually impact your portfolio? My understa
componenttext: Just a follow-up on your comments about supply. Could you provide a little bit more color as to markets where you're seeing supply? I think you mentioned Houston and Columbus. With Houston, it -- does the supply actually impact your portfolio? My understanding is that there's a lot more activity surrounding the port and the downstream portion, the petrochemical business and so that's what driving supply there but any additional color on those markets and others would be appreciated.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, sure Eric, it's Gene. And you're correct about Houston, that's where the supply is. Our portfolio is primarily Northwest and it's pretty built out, there isn't a lot of supply. But if you look at the raw numbers in Houston, it is in an overbuilt cond
componenttext: Yes, sure Eric, it's Gene. And you're correct about Houston, that's where the supply is. Our portfolio is primarily Northwest and it's pretty built out, there isn't a lot of supply. But if you look at the raw numbers in Houston, it is in an overbuilt condition, it still has positive absorption, which probably surprises a lot of people. But it is overbuilt. Other markets that we've called out Columbus, again not a horrendous situation but they have excess of client and a forward pipeline that concerns us. And otherwise, we look at this all the time as you know, other markets just don't scream bad at this point. Dallas has a lot of construction going on and Dallas has a forward supply scenario that has us sort of cautious. But again, a lot of that's in South Dallas, most of our development, most of our portfolio is around the airport in the north now. So I could go on about other markets but the reality is that we're in pretty good shape in these markets in the U.S. And there's something else I'd point out, Eric, and this is worth noting and watching going forward. We've called out a couple of markets historically over the last several quarters Indianapolis is one of them, Central and Eastern Pennsylvania. And what's happened and frankly, I haven't seen this happen before in my career is we -- markets got closed doing over building situation or maybe a little over the line and they've corrected. So both of those markets are actually -- they've taken the foot of the gas, they'd lowered the supply level and they've made corrections. And there's a couple of other markets but New Jersey would also fall on that category, by the way, that's really, really good to see. And again we got to watch this every day. But we continue to be very pleased with the overall discipline.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Yes, Eric. The only thing I would add to what Gene said is that the only place I see around the world where truly stupid things are happening is Poland. I mean, it is irresponsible with a capital. And you've got literally people signing leases on build-to
componenttext: Yes, Eric. The only thing I would add to what Gene said is that the only place I see around the world where truly stupid things are happening is Poland. I mean, it is irresponsible with a capital. And you've got literally people signing leases on build-to-suits with face rents that they then discount with 3 years of free rents on a 10-year lease. And there's some investor that comes up and buys it at the cap rate that they think is the cap rate. And they do it with site letters and all kinds of games that are really not good for our industry's reputation. And we're concerned about that and we will speak about that and as I mentioned to you a couple of quarters ago, we have the real stake in making sure that investors are making intelligent decisions. By the way, Poland is before everybody gets all excited, Poland is 2% of our portfolio and this is really only happening in a few locations in Poland. But it is concerning, it sort of reminds me of Dallas in 1997, '98. And some people are going to get burned doing that and then they'll stop. But at the moment that's the only place in the world that worries me.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016

componenttext: The only comment I would add, Hamid, is that the impact will not have any impact on our existing Polish portfolio because we are -- we value our assets on a net asset or a net effective rent basis. So there should be no impact there but I have to tell you, these investors who are buying these headline capped assets are not going to be happy when these assets or leases roll. So...

componenttext: 2 quick follow-ups. On leasing, it looks like you took care of a lot of -- or at least a bunch of expirations for 2017. headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: Let me hit development. Development margins have been crazy good and a lot of it has to do with the fact that we are monetizing low, cheap land from the downturn that was impaired and all that. I think at market -- with market land values, our development
componenttext: Let me hit development. Development margins have been crazy good and a lot of it has to do with the fact that we are monetizing low, cheap land from the downturn that was impaired and all that. I think at market -- with market land values, our development margins are more normal, they're still high but they're more normal, they're not as crazy high. Remember what we said about development margins? In a steady state market, which we're not in yet, we're better than this. But when the market is totally steady, spec should be around 15 and build-to-suits should be 10 to 12. Right now, we're probably at market 5 points higher in that for both spec and build-to-suit. More for spec. I would say build-to-suits are 10 to 12 when they get to be really competitive. So we've just been spoiled by really good margins. And we haven't built our business or our forecast based on 30% margins like we had last year.

headline: Prologis, Inc., Q2 2016 Earnings Call, Jul 19, 2016
componenttextpreview: And then down on the leasing question, we're always pulling leases forward, it's just a part of how we run the business. There really isn't any strategy around that, we're not specifically targeting any particular vintage of lease, really has to do with t
componenttext: And then down on the leasing question, we're always pulling leases forward, it's just a part of how we run the business. There really isn't any strategy around that, we're not specifically targeting any particular vintage of lease, really has to do with the customer's interest and other things, so that's not a -- but you're going to be able to continue to see that in the normal course of business.

componenttext: Manny, this is Tom. I'll just add one more thing when you look at the net effect of rents and the remaining 2017, what's rolling our share? It actually dropped from last quarter. So our discussion about NOI growth going forward and the very positive mark-to-market and I think that's a really good sign when you think about how high our rent change on roll was this quarter and we've lowered our net effective in-place rents in '17.
